<HEAD>
<TITLE>Greenpeace UK Science</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="8000FF" ALINK="008040" background="icons/smbg.gif"><!--START RISK ASSESSMENT TABLE-->
<a name="ra"><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=720>

<tr><td height=72 width=72><img src="icons/blank72.gif" width=72 height=72 border=0></td>
<td height=72 width=72><a href="index.html#ra"><img src="icons/neg0.gif" width=72 height=72 border=0></a></td>
<td height=72 valign=center><a href="index.html#ra"><img src="icons/hrat.gif" border=0 width=117 height=30></a></td></tr>

<tr><td width=72></td>
<td width=72></td>
<td valign=center width=576>
<!--INSERT TEXT HERE-->
<P><B>Assessing environmental risks: why science alone is 
not enough</B>

<P><B>Greenpeace Business Feb/March 1996
</B>

<P>Has the public got distorted view of environmental risks? The accumulation of 
scientific facts and risk assessments are no longer sufficient to ensure public 
acceptance over a wide range of issues. For  example: 

<P>the Brent Spar wasn’t dumped; 

<P>a prolonged inquiry into Nirex’s proposal to build an underground nuclear waste 
dump is taking place in the UK amidst growing public opposition; 

<P>manufacturers and retailers world-wide have yet to convince consumers of the 
benefits of genetically engineered products. 

<P>How should businesses respond when faced with public responses like these which 
they find irrational?  The commonest answer has been to conduct a rational risk 
assessment and add a spoonful of public education to pre-empt emotional responses. 

<P>Decisions will then, it is claimed, be based on science rather than emotion. 
Conventional thinking in government and industry has been that the public is simply 
over emotional, ignorant or both. But there is mounting evidence that it is not a 
misunderstanding of science or the facts on the part of the public which leads to 
conflict on these seemingly technical matters. Research shows that genuine, rational 
and legitimate concerns of the public are illogically excluded from so-called rational, 
scientific risk assessments. The system needs changing if it is to work. 

<P>In the case of the Brent Spar it was impossible to raise the principle of whether 
dumping rubbish at sea was acceptable at all. The framework for decision-making only 
allowed consideration of the particular metalwork of the Brent Spar. In the public’s 
mind, however, allowing the dumping of one oil installation could lead to more being 
dumped into the sea in the future. In addition, the fact that the public are urged and 
bound by law not to dump their rubbish in the environment, while an industry was 
treated very differently, was also totally excluded from the decision-making. 

<P>At the inquiry into Nirex's proposed dump, questions about less dangerous sites are 
being avoided. Nirex has created a scientific forum for debate which allows it to 
bypass discussions of safety until a later date, possibly well into the next century, by 
which time the economic momentum behind a dump at Sellafield will be difficult to 
dislodge. 

<P>When it comes to genetic engineering the risk assessment looks at the dangers out of 
context. Crops genetically engineered to be resistant to chemical herbicides are 
assessed in isolation from their intended use with herbicide. Only technical details can 
be debated, not the pros and cons of producing herbicide resistant plants or their 
impact on the use of chemicals. Whether genetic engineering is desirable at all is never 
considered. 


<P><B>PUBLIC POLICY ISSUES
</B>

<P>To the public, the strategy of containing debate inside a narrow so-called rational 
scientific framework acts to exclude legitimate discussion of the issues of public 
policy which lie behind them. The presumptions hiding behind the rational 
approaches in these three cases are that; dumping waste at sea is a positive option; that 
the nuclear industry’s short term economic interests are more important than the health 
of future generations; and that risking irreversible change in the genetic make-up of 
nature is an acceptable cost of a new industry. None of these presumptions is founded 
in science. They reflect a particular view of the world which is often at odds with 
public values and perceptions. 

<P>As effective wider debate is not allowed they tend to flare up at unexpected moments, 
as they did with the Brent Spar, when the underlying feelings can get some purchase. 
So they are not expressions of irrational emotion or an anti-science sentiment, but 
symptomatic of deeper divisions between the public and its institutions, including 
business. 

<P>Since none of this is about science, it will not help to provide more scientific facts 
about the impact of dumping the Brent Spar, the hydrogeology of the rocks under 
Sellafield or gene flow from genetically engineered plants. Whilst research also shows 
that the public is interested in, and has confidence in science to address the problems of 
the world, scientific approaches become viewed with suspicion when operating within 
a framework that rules out relevant questions. 

<P>Public education as a response to public anxieties is, therefore, more likely to fuel 
the cynicism with which such exercises are increasingly viewed. People quite sensibly 
evaluate risks partly in terms of whether or not those in control can be trusted and 
what risks they face by having to trust them. PR exercises which result in people being 
patronised as ignorant and irrational are unlikely to reassure the public and lessen the 
sense of risk. 

<P>Following the decision not to dump the Brent Spar, Shell is now investigating some 
200 disposal options. A whole Aladdin's cave of alternatives had been concealed, 
which are now available for business to develop. In contrast, Nirex and the nuclear 
industry will face prolonged, drawn out battles over nuclear waste well into the next 
century if they refuse to address long term safety now. 

<P>Genetic engineering could face the same sorts of battles. Businesses have been 
reluctant to accept labelling of products and have cast off public concerns about the 
morality of genetic engineering as non-scientific. 

<P>Greenpeace will continue to challenge these so called scientific approaches to risk. 

<P><B>Contact: Sue Mayer on 01298 871558 or Helen Wallace on 0171 865 8100

</B>


</td></tr></table>
<!--END RISK ASSESSMENT  TABLE-->
