<HTML><BODY TEXT="FFFF00" LINK="00FF00" VLINK="8000FF" ALINK="008040" background="../icons/xlogo.gif"><basefont=-3></font><kbd><HEAD><TITLE>Genetic Engineering</TITLE></HEAD><BODY><center><!--INTRO TABLE--></a><table border=0 colspan=2 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=576><tr><td valign=top align=center width=72></td><td width=504><kbd><P>
<H2>GENETIC ENGINEERING AND THE ENVIRONMENT</H2>

Genetic engineering enables scientists to transfer genes between species, for instance from animals to plants and from bacteria to plants or animals. All the boundaries of conventional breeding are broken down. Our understanding of species as distinct from one another will be transcended by the power of the technology.

<P>Many applications of genetic engineering, particularly agricultural, depend on the release of genetically manipulated organisms (GMOs), including plants, animals and microbes, to the environment. How will these organisms, whose genetic makeup has been controlled by man bypassing natural evolution, affect the environment? Will they form the "green" solution to pollution and starvation?  Greenpeace does not believe that genetic engineering will provide the answers to these problems but that new environmental risks will be created while the fundamental problems go unaddressed.

<P>The patenting of genetic material and life forms will not only speed the industrialisation of genetic engineering and therefore the release of GMOs to the environment, but will also put the control of genetic resources into the hands of the multinational industries.

<P><tr><td valign=top align=center width=72><a href="gemaize.html"><img src="../icons/gr_ball.gif" border=0</a></td><td width=504><kbd>Genetically engineered maize has been entering the European Community without authorisation. (see "News" below). This Greenpeace document outlines the <a href="gemaize.html">background to genetically engineered maize</a> and Ciba Geigy's application to market it in Europe. December 1996<br><br></td></tr>

