<html><head><title>EXECUTIONERS MOVE ON KEN SARO WIWA</title></head><body>
<body bgcolor="#000000" text="#ffffff" link="#ff0000" alink="#ff0000" vlink="#00ff00">
<a href="index.html"><img src="../icons/shellkem.gif" align=right height=72 width=72 border=0></a>



<p align=center><H1>EXECUTIONERS MOVE ON KEN SARO WIWA</H1>
<p><I>Auckland 10 November 1995</I>
<p align=center><a href="ken.jpg">26kb Jpeg</a><a href="ken.gif"><img src="kent.gif width=74 height=76> 99kb Gif</a>
<p><B>A team of executioners have been turned away from the jail cell
where writer Ken Saro Wiwa and 8 other Ogonis are on death row
awaiting execution.
</B>
<p><B>The squad of military personnel based in Sokoto in the Muslim
North were turned away after a prison warder declared that the
appropriate paper work had not been completed for him to
authorise the removal of the condemned men from the prison.</B>

<p><B>Sources close to Government in Abuja relayed the news to Vincent
Idemyor, President of the US branch of the Movement for the
Survival of the Ogoni people (MOSOP). Mr Idemyor subsequently
confirmed the story with his father in Port Harcourt, Nigeria.
He said "Mandela and Major must call General Abacha now. General
Abacha's working hours are from 11.00pm to 3.00am. If there are
any further delays it will be too late".</B>

<p><B>Ken Wiwa, son of the jailed writer is in Auckland where he is
lobbying the Commonwealth Heads of Government said: "There is a
horrible inevitability about all this. We have warned politicians
here and we can only trust that when they advocate patience they
are fully aware of the seriousness of the situation".</B>

<p><B>Olisa Agbakoba, a lawyer who was part of Ken Saro Wiwa's defence
team at the tribunal, also in Auckland said: "What is needed now
is urgent, strong action against Nigeria. The Mandela quiet
approach just will not work".
</B>
<p><B>Contact: Ken Wiwa or Olisa Agbakoba on +64 25 923 681. </B>
