<head><H4>EXTRACTS FROM:
Smit Engineering BV (1992), Feasibility Study - Phase I, II and II - Report for Scrapping
of the Brent Spar. Contract to Shell UK Exploration and Production.</H4></head><body>

Smit Engineering BV   Page 20 of 159

<P><H4>5. BALLAST PROCEDURE</H4>

<P><H4>5 .1.  INTRODUCTION</H4>



<P>In this chapter the ballast procedure is discussed,
whereby the amount of water ballast in the Spar is
adjusted to enable sectionalising of the Spar. The
ballast procedure, the damage to the Storage Tanks
C27 (T100) and C29 (T500) influences the sequence of
the ballast procedure. In the following paragraphs,
the damage (including the repair) is briefly
described, followed by the ballast procedure and
some ballast procedure details.



<P><H4>5 . 2 .   DAMAGE TO STORAGE TANKS</H4>


<P>The Storage Tanks C27 (T100) and C29 (T500) have
been damaged previously due to operational errors.
The damage is located between 4 and 32 meter from
the bottom of the Spar (see appendix 3).


<P>The damage was repaired later on by bolting straps
on and restoring the structural integrity.  In the
damaged area however three cracks and a large number
(some 73) of 150 mm diameter arm holes remain
present.  The damaged compartments are therefore
considered as leaking tanks, open to the sea.



<P>5.2.1     Water removal method damaged Storage Tanks


<P>The ballast water from the two damaged tanks is
removed by lifting the tanks above sealevel.  In
this way, ballast water will flow from the tanks 
into the sea.




 <P>               Smit Engineering BV



[Figure omitted]


<P>It is necessary to allow simultaneously inert gas to
 enter the top of the damaged tanks.
 The use of inert gas is envisaged to avoid
 explosions in case the tanks contains an oil layer
 on top of the ballast water.


<P>In the event this poses a problem the most obvious
alternative is to patch the holes prior to removing
the contents of the damaged storage tanks into the
watercarrier.



<P>5.2.2 Patching of damage


<P>Patching of the damage is feasible. Although
patching may well be carried out with saturation
divers, we have assumed in this study that only
airdiving is used.
For airdiving, the depth limit is 50 m.
The application of ROV's is not considered since
specific tools will need to be developed to patch
the holes and cracks.


<P>The holes can be patched by using prefabricated
steel patches (see drawing 91.3100-D-010).
The cracks can be patched with putty when they are
not too wide. Otherwise, wooden kegs with putty are
used.                        -




<P><H4>5.3.      GENERAL BALLASTING PROCEDURE</H4>



<P>The ballasting of the Brent Spar is carried out to
ensure proper lifting heights for the various
sections to be lifted off.  The actual ballasting
operation will take place in between the lifting
operations. An exception is made for the intermediate lift
during which the damage is patched.  In this case,
the deballasting is supported by two sheerlegs, in
order to reduce the draft to an acceptable level to
allow air divers to patch the damage, and to ensure
an upright position of the Spar.


<P>In this paragraph, an overview of the ballastlng
activities will be presented.  A detailed
description of these activities can be found in
appendix 4.  A detailed description of some of the
procedure details is given in section 6.4.


<P>Preparations prior to lift 1:
     For bringing the Spar to a draught of 113 m
     three Outer Ballast Tanks are to be filled for
     44%.  This is done by using gravity filling.
<P>Preparations prior to lift 2:
     First the water in the Outer Ballast Tanks is
     removed by mobile pumps.
     This is followed by deballasting of the Storage
     Tanks.  While two storage tanks are open to
     sea, from a Symmetry point of view, only three
     tanks lying in a star formation can be used for
     deballasting.  The other three tanks are kept
     at a level equal to sealevel.
     It is therefore the intention to deballast
     three intact Storage Tanks to 90% by using
     compressed inert gas.
<P> Preparations prior and during intermediate lift
     At this point the oil is skimmed from three
     intact Storage Tanks whereafter submersible
     pumps are lowered into the tanks.  This is
     followed by further deballasting.
     With only three of the six storage tanks used
     for deballasting, the relative water column on
     these three storage tanks increases.



               


<P>     The draught of the Spar is 82m, the
relative water column is 25 m.
At this point, it is suggested  to use the
available lifting capacity to reduce the
draught of the Spar to enable patching of the
damaged areas.


<P>By attaching the two sheerlegs to the damaged
tanks, tank C31 can also be deballasted, while
from the damaged tanks the ballast will flow
into the sea. The upright position is ensured
by the sheerlegs.
With this method it is feasible to reduce the
water column to 20 m, whereby both sheerlegs
are lifting 700 ton.  The reduced draft of the
Spar is 49 m.
<P>At this point it is feasible to patch the
damage with divers.  Bearing in mind that the
lowest point of the damage is 4 meters from the
bottom of the spar, the maximum diving depth
for patching is 45 meters.
<LI>- Preparations prior to lift 3:
<LI>     -After the patching the tanks are filled up to
     again to an average 65% prior to lifting off
     the 3rd section.  During this operation, the
     Spar is assisted by the sheerlegs to stay in an
     upright position. After the tanks are filled,
     the sheerlegs can be disconnected.
-<LI> Preparations prior to lift 4:
     All six Storage Tanks will be deballasted to
     30%.
-<LI> Preparations prior to lift 5:
     All six Storage Tanks will be deballasted until
     no water is left.
-<LI> Preparations prior to lift 6:
     No deballasting is required for the lift of the
     bottom section



<P><H4>5.4 PROCEDURE DETAILS</H4>

<P>In this paragraph some of the ballasting procedure
aspects are discussed in more detail.


<P>On request of Shell Expro, the equipment of the Spar
is not used and mobile and submersible pumps are
used instead.
In those cases where internal piping is used, this
is restricted to the piping previously used by Shell
Expro in normal operational conditions.
Prior to using the piping, it should be checked for
leakage and valves should be checked for proper
operation.


<P>According to Shell Expro, the Storage Tanks are
completely filled with seawater.  Prior to
decommissioning of the Spar all systems were flushed
to remove any oil.  For this study, it is assumed
that there is still a possibility of a top layer of
oil, floating on top of the waterballast in the
Storage Tanks.  This layer should be skimmed from
the Storage Tanks and collected in a special tank.
In order to reduce the risk of pollution, the rest
of the removed ballast water from the storage tanks
is collected in a water carrier.



<P>5.4.1.    Ballasting of Outer Ballast Tanks


The ballasting of the Outer Ballast Tanks in
preparation of lifting the topside can be done based
on gravity.  For a schematic overview of the
piping system see drawing 91.3100-D-004 Sheet 1.
The easiest way for ballasting is to use only tanks
C40, C42 and C44, since tanks C39 and C41, located-
above the damaged tanks, are blinded off .



<P>5.4.2 Deballasting of the Ballasting Tanks

Deballasting of the Outer Ballast Tanks after the
topside is removed, is carried out with mobile
pumps.  These pumps will be positioned in the Pump
Room on the M-deck.  The suction of these mobile
pumps will be connected to the Suction Manifold Ring
either to an available flange, or otherwise by means
of a hot-tap.  The pressure side will be mounted to
a blinded valve, directly connected to the Central
Shaft.  See drawing 9l.3100- D-004 Sheet 2.



<P>5.4.3 Deballasting of intact Storage Tanks with inert gas


Prior to skimming the Storage Tanks, the tanks have
to be entered in order to position the skimming
equipment.  The water level in these tanks is
therefore lowered to create a working space between
the water level and the top of tank.
Due to the fact that the internal equipment of the
Spar can not be used, it is not possible to operate
the Seawater Disposal System of the Spar.  It is
feasible to achieve a working space in the top of
the storage tanks by applying compressed inert gas
to force the ballast waters out via the existing
piping.     


<P>The inert gas hoses can be connected to three
different manifolds, on various levels (see drawing
91.3100-D-006).  The first choice is the Transfer
Manifold on the M-deck.  This one is favoured since
it is close to the top of the tanks.  The second
choice is the Pump Suction Manifold on the J-deck.
Finally also use can be made of the Filling Manifold
on the H-deck


<P>For the discharge of the water ballast, use is made
of the risers in the tanks, which are connected to
the Seawater Manifold.
From this manifold a connection to the water carrier
can be made at an elevation of 105 m. (J-deck),
which is 5 m. above sealevel.  The required pressure
in the system to remove the water ballast is between
3 and 4 bar.


<P>Prior to putting the system under pressure, valves
are to be mounted to the ventlines.  The overflow
lines and the line from the Sea Water Manifold
running to the Tanker have to be sealed-off.


<P>After closure of the water ballast discharge lines
the pressure in the tanks is released by opening the
valves mounted to the ventlines and the tanks can be
opened.  When the tanks are opened, and the top
layer of oil is removed, further deballasting of
these tanks can take place by using submersible
pumps.



<P>5.4.4 Entering the Storage Tanks


<P>The entrance to the main storage tanks can only be
obtained by means of a manhole or with a cold
cutting method such as water jet cutting or with a
diamond saw.
Obtaining entrance is in no way feasible through a
hot cutting method since the possible presence of an
oil layer floating on top of the water ballast could
set off an explosion.


<P>Prior to opening the tanks, the pressure has to be
released by venting and the water level and pressure
inside the tank should be checked.

[Figures omitted]
