<li>         Mrs L Massie, SOAFD, Aberdeen


<P>Dr O Branden from AURIS Environmental contacted us to request information on the
toxicity of Glyoxal and its products. He pointed out that 4.5 m-3 of Glyoxal had been
used to treat 50 000 m -3 of crude oil which had been heavily contaminated with H2S.
This chemical was used to scavenge the hydrogen sulphide, and so reacted with it to form
mono, di, tri and tetra THIOLS (mercaptans).                   


<P>A data search was then performed and data for Methyl and Ethyl Mercaptans was
recovered from the US EPA's AQUIRE [1] database.

<P>In general the data shows that as the size of the molecule increases so does the
Octanol/Water partitioning coefficient (this is a measure of the lipid solubility of a
chemical, anything with a log Pow of >3 with a molecular weight of <600 is liable to
bioaccumulate). From this data it is probable that any large (tri or tetra) thiols will be
liable to bioaccumulate. The retrieved toxicity data indicates that the toxicity of these
chemicals is generally greater than 100 mg/l for freshwater species so that they are only
moderately harmful, and should not pose any particular environmental hazard as long as
any water discharge is very dilute. It should be pointed out that mercaptans are known to
cause taint in fish and shellfish and this should be considered. The provided data indicates
that the maximum level of mercaptans present would be 900 mg/l. Of far greater concern
are the potential levels of heavy metals present in this water.

<P>The sacrificial anodes used to protect these tanks are made of Zinc, which is a PARCOM
black list substance. Levels of zinc in samples of the sludge from 2 of the 7 tanks filled
with this water were reported to be >100 mg/l. It is probable that there will be
considerable levels of Zinc in the water so that it will have to be treated as hazardous
waste (C Vivian pers. comm.). In addition there are very high levels of Copper present in
the sludge, levels reported were 285 mg/l and 1430 mg/l in two of the seven tanks. This
gives a mean level of 857.5 mg/L We recently performed a basic hazard assessment on
this metal and found that toxic effects could be observed at only 9 micro g/l (copy
attached [2]). Therefore a dilution factor of at least 100 000 would be required to reduce
the toxicity of the discharge  to an acceptable level.

<P><B>On the data we have been provided, the chemistry of this water is such that it has to be
considered very toxic to marine biota. It should therefore be treated as hazardous waste,
and discharge should be prohibited (C Vivian pers. cornm.). As the structure has not been
used for two years it is no longer covered by the Statutory Instrument (1985, No. 1699)
which excludes producing facilities from the provisions of FEPA. Shell will have to apply
for a dumping licence to dispose of any water or other wastes from the Brent Spar, and
very stringent controls should be applied.
</B>
<P>AURIS have been put in touch with the Orkney Water Test Centre to discuss treatment
options. this may be the ideal facility to use as it has a direct link to the Flotta Oil
terminal so that hydrocarbons can be removed from the water before it is transferred for
further treatment. It has been pointed out that other facilities may exist which are more or
equally suited to deal with this waste water.





<P>[1] It should be noted that the AQUIRE modelling system predictions should be treated
with some caution. It should reveal the general trend of chemical behaviour, but it is
based on assumptions  which do not apply to North Sea situations (eg temperature).

<P>[2] The hazard assessment is a simple draft format and should not be treated as definitive,
it has not been fully vetted.


<li>W R McMINN</body></html>




