<TD WIDTH=400 VALIGN=TOP>
<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=100% HEIGHT=70>
<TR><TD  VALIGN=TOP>
<FONT SIZE=+2 FACE="MS SERIF">P L U T O N  I U M  <br> S T O C K P I L E S    </FONT>
</TD>
</TR></TABLE>

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=390><TR><TD>

<FONT SIZE=+0 FACE="MS SERIF">       

<B><P>‘Even if one disregards the fissile material from nuclear 
warheads, the excess of isolated plutonium from civilian 
nuclear power programmes poses a major political and 
security problem worldwide’
‘From a security point of view, isolated plutonium is 
best kept in reactors - in the reactor fuel’.</B>

<P><FONT SIZE=-1 FACE="MS SERIF">    <I>William J Dircks, Deputy Director General
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA),Vienna, Austria
Address given to the Japanese Industrial Forum (JAIF) 
13th April 1992</I></font>

<P>Throughout the nuclear age, the proliferation of nuclear 
weapons has depended on the spread of 'dual use' nuclear 
technologies and materials.  Despite the close 
relationship between civil nuclear technology and 
materials and nuclear weapons proliferation, the 
production of nuclear weapons usable plutonium will soon 
increase beyond the levels produced during the entire 
cold war.  





</FONT>
</TD></TR></TABLE>
 
</TD>


