// -->
</script>

<title>Press Release</title></head>

<body background="../icons/nukback7.gif" bgcolor="#d03512" text=#000000 link="#008000" alink= "#000099" vlink="#139000">

<center>
<table border=1 width=1050><tr><td><tt><font size=+2><a href="hotnews.html#krasno"> Press Releases &nbspPress Releases &nbspPress Releases &nbspPress Releases &nbspPress Releases...</a></font></td></tr></table>
<center>
<table border=0 width=600><tr><td><tt> 

<br><br><p><font size=+1>


<!--INSERT TITLE------------------------------------------------------------------------------>



<!--INSERT TITLE------------------------------------------------------------------------------>

<B> ANTI-NUCLEAR REFERENDUM IN KRASNOYARSK REGION
 </B></font>
 
<!--END TITLE----------------------------------------------------------------------------------->

<!--INSERT DATE,TEXT---------------------------------------------------------------------->

<p><B>Moscow 10th December, 1996 - </B>         
 
<p>Today Greenpeace announced that the
Krasnoyarsk Regional Electoral Committee issued a certificate of
registration for an initiative group to prepare a referendum in
the region.  This referendum will decide the future of the RT-2
plant for spent nuclear fuel reprocessing, located in
Zheleznogorsk city (Krasnoyarsk region). The initiative group,
founded with the participation of Greenpeace activists, will
have to collect no less than 50 thousand signatures to initiate
the referendum.
 
<p>The construction of RT-2 started in 1984, but was stopped in
1990. It was designed for reprocessing spent fuel from VVER-1000
design nuclear reactors.  The plant is only 30 per cent
constructed. At present there is only a storage facility for
6000 tonnes of spent fuel (per uranium) being utilised.
Completion of the construction will require an additional 2-4
milliard dollars.
 
<p>Reprocessing is dirty and dangerous.  There are two major
reprocessing factories in western Europe, one at La Hague in
France and the second at Sellafield in the UK, and in the areas
surrounding these plants the rate of leukaemia among children
has been estimated to be between 2-10 times higher than the
national averages.
 
<p>A Feasibility Study by the State Ecological Expertise at the
RT-2 plant has shown that the project has not been thoroughly
developed. For instance, the main technological equipment is
planned to be constructed and subsequently revised.  Some of
radioactive waste - which contains tritium - is supposed to be
pumped down into the earth at the "Severnyj" area for 30 years.
The authors of the feasibility study have not dared to forecast
the consequences of such activity. These envisaged safety
measures will not prevent radioactive elements from entering the
environment.
 
<p>In case of the positive outcome at the referendum, MinAtom (the
Ministry of Atomic Energy) plans to complete construction of the
RT-2 construction would be finally buried.  Moreover, this could
be the first step to blocking future dangerous plans of MinAtom
for developing a new direction in nuclear power technology -
construction of reactors which use mixed uranium plutonium fuel.
 
<p><B>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:

<P> Ivan Blokov,
Evgenij Usov: Greenpeace Russia: 251-90-73, 978-39-50, 
 
<p>Additional Information</B>
 
<p>MinAtom has made several attempts to resume construction at the
RT-2 plant, but failed so because of insufficient financing.
Therefore MinAtom was prepared to sign an agreement on taking
nuclear waste  from foreign nuclear power plants in order to
raise funds.
 
<p>Under pressure from MinAtom the President of the Russian
Federation signed a Decree (1995), permitting the import of
spent nuclear fuel from nuclear power plants for storage and so
called "reprocessing". Later the term "storage" was changed to
"temporary storage for future reprocessing", for the Decree to
be in accordance with the Law. A number of provisions in the
Decree contradicted the Nature Protection Law of the RF and
allowed this ecologically hazardous activity. Greenpeace filed

an action at the Supreme Court of Russia to cancel the
provisions which permit the import of spent fuel from foreign
reactors to the Krasnoyarsk Mill. In 1996 the Supreme Court
agreed to Greenpeace's claim.

<!--END OF TEXT---------------------------------------------------------------------->

</td></tr></table>

