<HTML>
<HEAD>

<TITLE>Conference Notice</TITLE>


</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="purple.jpg">
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<IMG SRC="ama2.gif" ALT="AMA Logo">
</P>
<H2>The Conference</H2>

<P>Experts from around the world are converging in Canberra, Australia from
September 23 to 24 for a major event; The Greenpeace International and
Australian Medical Association Conference on  Climate Change and Human
Health in the Asia-Pacific. 
The health impacts of climate change are emerging as a significant
international issue. The conference will provide a peak forum for
scientists, policy makers, environmentalists and leaders in the health
sector to debate the implications of human-induced climate change for human
health and their relevance to the health sector. Guest Speakers include:</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><B>Professor Anthony McMichael</B> - 
Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><B>Professor Paul Epstein</B> - 
Harvard Medical School</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><B>Professor Alistair Woodward</B> - 
Wellington School of Medicine</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><B>Dr. Charles Guest</B> - 
Australian National University</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><B>Professor Peter Curson</B> - 
Climate Impacts Centre,
Macquarie University</P>

<H2>Convention Theme</H2>

<P>Climate change caused by human emissions of greenhouse gases is emerging as
one of the critical environmental issues of the 21st century. The human
health implications of current and projected changes in global climate is
however a relatively new field of enquiry. The United Nation's
Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) recently conducted the
first globally comprehensive assessment of climate change and human health
and concluded that climate change is likely to have wide-ranging and mostly adverse impacts on human health, with significant loss of life </P>

<P>The principal aim of the conference is to create discussion on the health
impacts of climate change and to improve understanding of the nature and
magnitude of the health impacts of climate change in the researchers, the
health sector, government, non-governmental organisations and the media.
The conference will pursue two main themes. Firstly, internationally and
regionally recognised experts will present the latest scientific findings on
the potential health impacts of climate change. Secondly, health sector
leaders, environmentalists, and climate change policy experts will discuss
the role of the health sector in addressing climate change and the research
needs and health policy implications.</P>

<H3>Theme 1: The Health Impacts of 
Climate Change</H3>

<P>Internationally and regionally recognised experts will present the latest
scientific developments on climate change and its potential impact on health
in a global and regional context. Speakers will include the world s foremost
authority on the health effects of global environmental change, Professor
Anthony McMichael from the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine.
Other speakers will include Professor Paul Epstein from Harvard Medical
School s group on new and resurgent diseases and one of the Asia-Pacific s
foremost authorities, Professor Alistair Woodward from the Wellington School
of Public Health.</P>

<P>
<UL TYPE=DISC>
	<LI>Direct Impacts
	<LI>Heatwaves and other weather extremes
	<LI>Indirect Impacts
	<LI>Emerging infectious diseases
	<LI>Respiratory and allergic disorders
	<LI>Changes in nutritional status from impacts on food and fisheries productivity
	<LI>Changes in freshwater supplies
</UL>
</P>


<H3>Theme 2: Response to the Health Impacts of 
Climate Change</H3>

<P>
<UL TYPE=DISC>
	<LI>Human health and climate change policy
	<LI>The response of the health sector in the Asia-Pacific
	<LI>The potential for adaptation
	<LI>Research needs
</UL>
</P>

