<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Canadian Forests</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCFECC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">

<table border=2 width=100% cellpadding=7><tr><td ALIGN=CENTER>
<a href="forests.html"><img align=right border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/biofor.gif"></a>
<BR><H2>CANADA: RAINFORESTS UNDER SIEGE</H2>
</td></tr></table>

<!--P><a href="http://www.web.net/save-species/">Canada endangered species & habitat at risk</a--> 

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=100% CELLPADDING=5>
<TR><TD>

<h2>The Destruction of the Ancient Forests</h2>
<P>
Canada is home to some of the largest remaining areas of
intact old growth forests in the world. 
Unfortunately, already
over 50% of these great forests have been destroyed or
degraded. 

<BR clear=all>

<center>
<P><a href="../pics/for66.gif">
<img vspace=5 hspace=5 src="../pics/for66s.jpg" width=175 height=116 border=0></a>
</center>

<BR clear=all>
In British Columbia, the province where over 50% of
the logging occurs, over half of the forest that has been destroyed has been logged since 1970. 
<br>
<BR clear=all>
<center>
<a href="../pics/for65.gif">
<img vspace=5 hspace=5  src="../pics/for65s.jpg" width=175 height=116 border=0></a>
</center>

<BR clear=all>
This is possibly because
of increased mechanization in the forest industry and the
reliance on a logging practice called 
<B><a href="clearcas.html">clearcutting </a></B> Across Canada over 90% of the logging is clearcut
logging.   Although much of the land is replanted, Canada's complex ancient forest ecosystems are being replaced with even aged tree farms.  This practice of converting natural forests to tree farms is devastating for wildlife and threatens biodiversity.  
<TD  WIDTH=50% VALIGN=TOP CELLPADDING=10>
<table border=0 cellpadding=7>
<tr><td align=left><font size=+1><b>Press Releases:</b></font>
<tr><td align=left><a href=prfoct23.html><img border=0 src="../icons/bionews.gif" width=25 height=25>October 23rd 1996</a><b> Greenpeace applauds world conservation congress for major moves on BC issues</b>
<tr><td align=left><a href=prfsep25.html><img border=0 src="../icons/bionews.gif" width=25 height=25>September 25th</a><b> Greenpeace supports Earthroots' call for Temagami protection
</table></b>

<table border=0 cellpadding=7>
<tr><td align=left><a href="canrisk.html"><font size=+1><img border=0 src="../icons/biofor.gif" width=25 height=25></a><B>Canadian forests at risk: <a href="canrisk.html">Just the facts</B></font></a></td>
<tr><td align=left><a href="canada02.html"><font size=+1><img border=0 src="../icons/biofor.gif" width=25 height=25></a><B><font size=+1><B>Greenpeace <a href="canada02.html">activists stop the loggers.</B></font></a></td>
</table>

<p><H2>The Greenpeace Campaign</H2>

<a href="../pics/for02.gif">
<img vspace=15 hspace=15 align=left lowsrc="../thumbs/for02t.gif" src="../pics/for02s.gif" width=115 height=176 border=0></a>

<B>Greenpeace is actively campaigning against the practice of
clearcut logging and promoting ecologically responsible forest
use.  Greenpeace has recently contributed to the certification
of the first Canadian clearcut-free logging operation in<a href="clearfre.html">
Vernon </a>, British Columbia.</B>

<br clear=all>
<a href="../pics/for26.gif">
<img vspace=15 hspace=15 align=right lowsrc="../thumbs/for26t.gif" src="../pics/for26s.gif" width=175 height=116 border=0></a> 

<B>For the past several years the forests campaign has been
actively working to protect the biological diversity of the
temperate rainforests on the west coast of Canada.  We have
achieved several important successes including the dramatic

reduction of clearcut logging in <a href="clayback.html"> Clayoquot Sound </a>, on Vancouver Island.  Greenpeace will continue
to work to effect the transformation of the forest industry in

Canada towards more ecologically responsible forest practices
and to protect rare and threatened forest ecosystems.</B>
</center>
</TD></TR></TABLE>
<br>








