<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Greenpeace: Stop Chlorine Bleaching of Paper Pulp!</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FF FF FF" TEXT="#00 00 80" LINK="#00 80 00"
VLINK="#80 00 00" ALINK="#FF FF 00" basefont=3>
<center><a href="/~usa/index.html"><img src="pix/get_inv.gif" WIDTH=504 HEIGHT=101 border=0></a></center>
<p>
<center>
<img src="pix/out_up.gif" vspace=5 width=560 height=23 ALT="Outreach Update">
</center>
<p>
<center>
<table width=560 cellpadding=10 border=2><tr><td valign=top>
<font size=+2><b>Pulp Fiction</b> (<i>pulp fik'shen</i>) <b><i>n.</i> </font><font size=+1>slang The pulp and paper industry's myth that chlorine bleaching of pulp and paper is safe - when in fact, it is not.<p></font>
</td></tr></table>
<p>
<table width=560 cellpadding=5 border=0>
<tr><td colspan=2 valign=top><center>
<font size=+3>Tell President Clinton to Cut Out Chlorine!<br></font>
<b>One of the first environmental decisions of President Clinton's second term could take the pollution out of paper making. You can help make this a reality!</b><p></center>
<img src="pix/can_do.gif" vspace=5 width=560 height=23 ALT="What you can do:"><p>
</td></tr>
<tr><td width=50% valign=top>
For over ten years, Greenpeace and other environmental groups have fought to end hazardous chlorine use in the pulp and paper industry. The success or failure of a dozen years of protests, lobbying and research now boils down to President Clinton making a simple choice about new EPA regulations. Any day, Clinton will either choose to allow the pulp and paper industry to continue their use of harmful chlorine and chlorine dioxide bleaching, or move the industry towards safe, chlorine-free technologies.
<p>
The next days and weeks are critical. Sources within the White House tell Greenpeace that President Clinton is wavering under the lobbying pressure exerted by the multi-billion dollar pulp and paper industry. This could be the first environmental decision of his new Administration. Will Clinton back down on his pledged commitment to protect human health and the environment? Your letters, faxes, emails and phone calls today can make the difference. 
<p>
The pulp and paper industry has claimed for years that chlorine bleaching of pulp and paper is safe. But this is pulp fiction. In fact, the pulp and paper industry's chlorine bleaching is one of the largest contributors to water pollution. Millions of gallons of toxic chemicals, called organochlorines, are discharged into freshwater streams and rivers each day. 
<p>
Many of these organochlorines, such as<br>
dioxin, cause cancer or genetic damage to<br>
humans and wildlife. These chemicals<br> 
persist and accumulate in the environment;<br> 
we all have measurable amounts of these<br>
toxic compounds in our bodies. 
</td><td width=50% valign=top>	
Fortunately, alternative bleaching methods<br>
exist and are widely available. Oxygen<br>
methods of bleaching, for example, are safe<br> 
and release no harmful organochlorines.<br>
They are used by paper mills around the world.
<p>
The pulp and paper industry is lobbying for<br>
permission to replace chlorine with<br>
chlorine dioxide. However, even if all U.S.<br>
mills switched to chlorine dioxide bleaching,<br>
over 47 million pounds of organochlorines<br>
would still be released by mills annually. 
<p>
Chlorine dioxide poses accident and health<br> 
and safety risks. It is highly explosive at<br>
even low concentrations. Train accidents<br> 
involving the transport of poisonous chlorine<br>
gas have resulted in injuries, deaths and<br>
the evacuation of entire communities. Nobody<br>
has ever had to be evacuated from a<br>
community because of an oxygen cloud!
<p>
Let President Clinton and the EPA know<br>
that you care more about fact than fiction.<br>
Write and let them know that you favor<br>
clean paper-making technologies that protect<br>
our planet, ourselves and the health of<br>
future generations. 
<p>
<font size=+1>Please copy this <a href="pulpclinton">sample letter</a> to your<br>
computer, add your name to the<br> bottom 
and mail it to the White House:<p>
President Clinton<br>
White House<br>
1600 Pennsylvannia Ave. NW<br>
Washington DC<br>
20501
</td></tr>
<tr><td colspan=2 valign=top>
<hr>
<center><font size=+3><b>Did You Know That:</b></font></center>
<font size=+1>
<ul>
<li> Pulp and paper mills are the largest source of dioxin in water pollution. Dioxin is one of the most toxic chemicals known to science.</li>
<li> According to the EPA, more than 95% of people tested in the U.S. already have dioxin in their body tissue. 90% of this dioxin comes from our food supply, such as dioxin-contaminated fish.</li>
<li> EPA scientists have concluded that background levels of dioxin found in Americans today may be responsible for serious health effects.</li>
<li> Low income, Native American and African American communities downstream from pulp and paper mills carry the bulk of the toxic burden produced by the pulp and paper industry - a clear case of environmental injustice.</li>
<li> The way to zero dioxin pollution is to use totally chlorine-free (TCF) processes. The first step to TCF is oxygen bleaching, instead of chlorine and chlorine dioxide bleaching.</li>
</ul>
</font>
</td></tr></table></center>
</body>
</html>
