<TITLE>ACTION</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FC9C9C" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">

<table border=1 width=100% cellpadding=7>
<tr><td>

<a href="geneng.html"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/biogen.gif"></a>

<A HREF="actindx.html#act11"><img valign=bottom align=right 
border=0 width=50 height=50 src="../icons/bioact.gif"></a>


<BR><font size=+1 face="arial">ACTIVISTS BLOCK HARBOUR LOCK TO PREVENT FIRST DIRECT  SHIPMENT OF GENETICALLY ENGINEERED SOYA BEANS ENTERING UK</font>
</td></tr>
</table>

<blockquote>

<p><b>  LIVERPOOL DOCKS, NOVEMBER 28 1996</b>

<p><img border=0 width=20 height=20 src="../icons/bioact.gif">&nbsp  At 11.30 on Friday Greenpeace inflatables intercepted the Polish registered  bulk carrier, Orleta Lwowskie, in the Mersey Estuary  protesting its mission  to  unload a cargo of 56,000 tons of genetically  modified soybeans at Liverpool Docks.

<p>The ship was carrying  the first direct  shipment of genetically modified soya into the UK from the United States, imported by trans national grain giant Cargill through their grain terminal in Liverpool.
Once at the dock, four  activists chained themselves to the lock gates and ladders, preventing the ship from docking. 

<br clear=all><br>

<a href="../pics/ge24.jpg"><img hspace=15 vspace=10 width=150 height=100 border=0 src="../thumbs/ge24t.jpg"></a>

<a href="../pics/ge25.jpg"><img hspace=15 vspace=10 width=150 height=100 border=0 src="../thumbs/ge25t.jpg"></a>

<br clear=all>
<P><img border=0 width=20 height=20 src="../icons/bioact.gif">&nbsp A large banner reading "Floodgate to genetic pollution" was hung across the 73,000 tonne, 228 meter long ship's path.<p>

<a href="../pics/ge23.jpg"><img align=left hspace=15 vspace=10 width=150 height=100 border=0 src="../thumbs/ge23t.jpg"></a>

<br clear=all>
<P><img border=0 width=20 height=20 src="../icons/bioact.gif">&nbsp In a simultaneous action further inside the dockyard, Greenpeace climbers scaled the two unloading cranes at the wharf - the shipment's destination - and disabled them by hanging a second banner from their loading arms.

<p><b>  'CONTAMINATED'  DISPLAYS AT SUPERMARKETS</b>

<p>The climbers stayed in position for 25 hours until midday Saturday when the protest was taken from supply to consumer as 40-50 UK local Greenpeace  groups targeted Sainsbury's ( a large UK retail chain who also produce their own brand products) around the UK.

<P><img border=0 width=20 height=20 src="../icons/bioact.gif">&nbsp Supermarket managers found that their entire Flora display had been covered in 'contaminated' stickers while bemused security guards ran around the store trying to find the source of the 'X files' music which activists were playing from their supermarket trolleys.

<p>Customers signed postcards featuring a Flora lid, 4000 of which are on their way to Unilever telling them that their customers do not want to be a part of the genetic experiment. 

<p><br>
<a href="newsindx.html#geneng20"><img valign=middle align=center width=30 height=30 border=0 src="../icons/bionews.gif">related press releases</a>
<br><hr><br>
</blockquote>
<BR>
</body></html>




