<HTML>
<TITLE>ACTION</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FC9C9C" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">

<table border=1 width=100% cellpadding=7>
<tr><td>

<a href="geneng.html"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/biogen.gif"></a>

<A HREF="actindx.html"><img valign=bottom align=right 
border=0 width=50 height=50 src="../icons/bioact.gif"></a>


<BR><font size=+1 face="arial">GREENPEACE BLOCKADES  SHIPMENTS OF GENETICALLY ENGINEERED SOYA</font>

</td></tr>
</table>

<blockquote>

<p><b><font size=+2>Actions highlight first imports to Europe</font></b><br>
<p><center>
</center>
<p><b>ANTWERP, BELGIUM, NOVEMBER 7th, 1996</b>

<P>&nbsp<img border=0 width=20 height=20 src="../icons/bioact.gif">


The action started at about 5.30 pm Thursday when four
activists from the Greenpeace ship MV Sirius
chained themselves to the gate of a lock preventing the
bulk carrier Ziemia Zamojska, carrying genetically manipulated soybeans, from leaving.

<P>Other activists chained an inftatable dingy to the 
rudder of the ship and hung a  banner on the lock gates.
Two tugs
also in the lock were allowed to leave. 
Police arrived at the scene  but no attempt was made to remove the 
activists or the inflatable in the dark.
    
<P>The crew worked in shifts throughout the night and day in cold
and rainy conditions to keep the ship in the lock. 


<br clear=all><br>
<a href="../pics/ge12.jpg"><img hspace=15 vspace=10 width=98 height=150 border=0 src="../thumbs/ge12t.jpg"></a>

<a href="../pics/ge13.jpg"><img hspace=15 vspace=10 width=150 height=100 border=0 src="../thumbs/ge13t.jpg"></a>

<a href="../pics/ge11.jpg"><img hspace=15 vspace=10 width=98 height=150 border=0 src="../thumbs/ge11t.jpg"></a>

<br clear=ALL>    
<P>&nbsp<img border=0 width=20 height=20 src="../icons/bioact.gif"> 
At 4:30 in the afternoon on Friday, the shipowners and importers of the
genetically manipulated soybeans, US grain multinational Cargill, 
obtained a court injunction  
against the Greenpeace action.
<p>The injunction, by which Greenpeace would have incurred a fine of 
one million Belgian francs for every hour the action
continued, was due to come into effect one hour after service.
After succesfully detaining the vessel for 24hrs, the activists unchained themselves.  
<p><B>A Greenpeace spokesperson on the scene commented: 
"We have no choice". -  Just like consumers.</B>

<br><br><br>

<p><b>GENT, BELGIUM, NOVEMBER 11th, 1996</b>

<P>&nbsp<img border=0 width=20 height=20 src="../icons/bioact.gif"> 
In a similar action, Greenpeace activists held up the unloading of another shipment of US soya beans, believed to
     be genetically contaminated, as it arrived at Gent harbour in Belgium early this morning. 

<br clear=all><P>

<a href="../pics/ge14.jpg"><img hspace=15 vspace=10 width=150 height=100 border=0 src="../thumbs/ge14t.jpg"></a>

<a href="../pics/ge15.jpg"><img hspace=15 vspace=10 width=150 height=100 border=0 src="../thumbs/ge15t.jpg"></a>

<br clear=all>
  <P>&nbsp<img border=0 width=20 height=20 src="../icons/bioact.gif">    The Greenpeace vessel the MV Sirius anchored in the berth of the bulk carrier Bunga Saga
     Empat preventing the vessel from unloading at Vamo Mills, 55 per cent owned by oil and
     margarine manufacturer Van Demoortele. 

     Some 25 activists from 12 countries using inflatable boats intend to chain themselves to the
     anchor chain of the Sirius thus preventing port authorities from moving the Greenpeace
     vessel. 

  <P>&nbsp<img border=0 width=20 height=20 src="../icons/bioact.gif">    Greenpeace is calling on Vamo Mills to segregate genetically engineered soya from the
     natural beans and to refuse to accept further shipments of genetically altered beans. 


<p><br>
<a href="newsindx.html#geneng9"><img valign=middle align=center width=30 height=30 border=0 src="../icons/bionews.gif">related press releases</a>
