<HEAD>
<TITLE>press release
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="geneng.html"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/biogen.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html#geneng26"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<blockquote>

<p><b>GREENPEACE STOPS FIRST TRANSGENIC CORN IMPORT AUTHORISED BY EUROPEAN
COMMISSION

<p> AMSTERDAM,  DECEMBER 19TH 1996 </b>

<p>Less than 24 hours after the European
Commission approved genetically engineered maize, Greenpeace today
stopped the unloading of a cargo of genetically manipulated corn and
soya arriving in France.


<p>At 1400 hours, activists from the Netherlands, France, the United
Kingdom, Denmark, Germany, Canada and the USA occupied the vessel and
chained themselves to loading cranes at Saint-Nazaire in Western
France.

<p>The ship, the "Magda P," set sail from New Orleans and has been
circling off shore waiting to unload its hazardous cargo for
approximately one week.

<p>"Our aim is to highlight this vessel's dangerous cargo of genetically
engineered corn and soya," said Greenpeace campaigner Michelle
Sheather.

<p>The corn has been engineered by Swiss multi-national Ciba-Geigy to be
tolerant to a week-killer and to produce toxins to kill a common

insect pest. 

<p>Thirteen European countries objected to the maize being brought into
Europe. They are worried about  environmental and health risks. In
spite of this,  the maize was approved by the European Commission
yesterday for cultivation and sale in Europe. The UK Government's
scientific advisers continued last night to support their original
objections to the corn's approval. 

<p>About one hundred thousand tons of corn had already arrived illegally
in European ports without approval and the USA has threatened a trade
war if it was not allowed in.

<p>There is a danger that the new corn will increase antibiotic
resistance in dangerous bacteria and could also increase pesticide
resistance in insects.

<p>The first imports of genetically engineered soy  have caused
widespread protest across Europe in recent weeks.  Greenpeace has
undertaken over 30 actions around the world on the introduction of the
GE soy crop into the world market.  In France, a Greenpeace campaign
against  these crops  has already been signed by  20,000 people in one
month.   

<p>"Without taking into account the wishes of European citizens, and
without learning the lessons from mad cow disease - which experts once
tried to convince us was safe - the European Commission has given in
to the lobbyists for the agrochemical  giants who are the only
beneficiaries of this dangerous experiment with nature", said
Greenpeace campaigner Arnaud Apoteker in Saint-Nazaire 

<p>"Approval of the maize actually conflicts with the European Council's
own directive which demands that all measures are taken to avoid
adverse effects to human health and the environment.

<p>This Directive (90/220/EEC) also acknowledges that "living organisms
... released into the environment...as commercial products, may
reproduce in the environment and cross national frontiers thereby
affecting other Member States;" and that "... the effects of such
releases on the environment may be irreversible".

<p>"Immediate action must be taken by European countries to protect the
integrity of their environment and the health of their population by
banning genetically manipulated maize," said Greenpeace campaigner
Michelle Sheather.

<b>
<p>For footage of the action please call Anke Scheib or Gina Walker,
Greenpeace International on +31 20  524 9543/4
<p>For photographs please contact Laurence Mermet, Greenpeace France on
33 (0) 1 43 53 85 85

<p>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT: 

<p>Arnaud Apoteker, Greenpeace France  +33 (0) 6 08 76 33 01
<p>Laurence Mermet, Greenpeace France +33 (0) 1 43 53 85 85
<p>Michelle Sheather,  Greenpeace International +31 (20) 523 6279
<p>James Gillies, Greenpeace International =32 20 524 9548
</B><br><br>
<hr>
<br>
<br><br><HR>
</blockquote>
