<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>press release
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="geneng.html"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/biogen.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html#geneng24"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<blockquote>

<p><b>GREENPEACE NAMES SHIPS BRINGING ILLEGAL CORN TO EUROPE<p>BRUSSELS,  DECEMBER 17TH 1996 </b>


<p>Greenpeace today reveals the names of
ships that have entered Europe in the last two months which it
believes contain illegal genetically engineered corn, and condemns the
lack of preventative action by EU member states.

"It is scandalous that foodstuff still under consideration for
possible environmental or health effects is being allowed into Europe
due to lax controls by EU member states," said Louise Gale,  from
Greenpeace's EU Unit.

<p>According to a leaked letter from the European Commission itself,
thousands of tonnes of maize have been entering European ports every
week since the new corn was harvested in October. The Commission even
wrote to member states alerting them to these illegal imports. But
only one EU country --Belgium -- has taken steps to provisionally
impound all US corn shipments for testing. 

<p>"Greenpeace calls on all EU member states to follow Belgium's lead and
take positive action to prevent illegal corn entering their countries
until the Commission anounces a total ban," said Louise Gale.

<p>Tomorrow (Wednesday) the Commission takes a crucial decision on Ciba
Geigy's corn , the second genetically engineered crop to be used in
human food in Europe. Soya, used in 60 per cent of all processed
foods, was approved earlier this year. Greenpeace has been actively
campaigning against its use. 

<p>"If the corn is approved tomorrow the floodgates will have been
opened. No one will be able to avoid genetically engineered food as
two of our staple crops become manipulated by multinational genetech
companies. The Commission will be failing in its duty to protect
Europe from the dangers of genetically engineered crops."

<p>The manipulated corn contains three new genes: one which makes it
resistant to a herbicide, one which kills insects and a "marker" gene
which confers resistance to the antibiotic Ampicillin, used  against a
wide range of disease causing bacteria in animals and humans. 

<p>Permission to import and grow this corn was not granted by the
Commisison after 13 member states opposed it on environmental and
health grounds. The UK expressed concern about the dangers of
antibiotic resistance developing as a result of the new corn being
eaten by humans and animals.


<p>"This product should have been banned in June, but instead the
Commission delayed their decision and referred it to three scientific
committees to examine evidence largely put forward by the
multinational agrochemical company Ciba Geigy who produce the corn,"
said  Greenpeace spokesperson Michelle Sheather. 

<p>"Advice from the Commission's scientific committees did not predict
the disastrous situation arising from BSE when animal carcasses were
allowed to be used as animal feed. Let's hope the Commissioners will
bear this in mind when they make their decission tomorrow. Greenpeace
calls on the Commission to reject permission for Ciba Geigy's
genetically engineered corn outright."



<p><B>Notes to editors</B>

<p>1. Ships coming to Europe containing US corn (approximately 0.6 per
cent genetically engineered this year) since October include: the
Marit Maersk and Mayview Maersk to Felixstowe in the UK; the
Inspiration and the Cape May to Bremerhaven in Germany; the Innovation
to Rotterdam in the Netherlands; and the George L to Ravenna in Italy.


<p>2. The EC Scientific Committees are: The Scientific Committee on Food;
The Scientific Committe on Animal Nutrition' The Scientific Committee
for Pesticides


<p><B>Note to picture editors</B>

<p>Greenpeace will be taking action outside the Commission Headquarters
in Brussels when the Commissioners arrive on Wednesday morning around
8am. Pictures will be available.

<B><p>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT: 
<p>James Gillies, Greenpeace
International Press Desk in Amsterdam on 00 31 20 524 9548
</B><br><br>
<hr>
<br>



<br><br><HR>
</blockquote>
