<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>GENE-TECH SOYA SHIPMENT BLOCKED BY GREENPEACE IS FINALLY IMPOUNDED BY SWISS AUTHORITIES
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="geneng.html"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/biogen.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html#geneng23"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<blockquote>

<p><b>GENE-TECH SOYA SHIPMENT BLOCKED BY GREENPEACE IS FINALLY IMPOUNDED BY SWISS AUTHORITIES
<p>BRUSSELS,  DECEMBER 12TH 1996 </b>

<p>The shipment of genetically engineered
soya meal blocked by  Greenpeace earlier today has been seized by the
Swiss Prosecutor, who announced that all further shipments will also
be impounded unless they are eventually approved.

<p>Meanwhile in Belgium, the Agriculture Ministry sent a memo to the
customs administration proposing that they "provisionally impound all
cargoes of US corn (new harvest) which arrive in Antwerp.  This
holding of the cargo will be in effect until we (the Agriculture
Ministry authorities) have determined if genetically modified
organisms are present."

<p>"It seems that at least some European governments are now willing to
take steps to protect their countries from genetically modified
organisms," said Louise Gale from Greenpeace,"Greenpeace welcomes
these steps and hopes that other member states will now oppose all
further attempts to import, grow or sell genetically altered crops in
Europe".

<p>Earlier today Greenpeace activists boarded the ship MS "Desire" near
Basel to prevent unloading of the illegal cargo of soya meal. The
imports of genetically engineered crops are in fact not approved by
Swiss legislation.<br><br>
<hr>
<br>
<b>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:

<p>Isabelle Meister - Greenpeace International + 31 20 52 36 213. ext 213</b>
<br><br><HR>
</blockquote>
</body>
</html>



