<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>GREENPEACE BLOCKS UNAUTHORISED CARGOES OF GENETICALLY ALTERED CROPS </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="geneng.html"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/biogen.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html#geneng22"><img align=right border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<blockquote>

<p><b>GREENPEACE BLOCKS UNAUTHORISED CARGOES OF GENETICALLY ALTERED CROPS  <p>BRUSSELS,  DECEMBER 12TH 1996 </b>

<p>Today Greenpeace activists in Hamburg stopped the departure of a train carrying an unauthorised cargo of
genetically altered crops, in this case corn destined for animal feed.
The corn is part of a 33,000 tonnes stock from the US which arrived in
Hambourg and is destined for Czech Republic. This country has no
legislation to protect itself from the import of modified crops, which
has not been authorised by the European Union yet. 

<p>Meanwhile Greenpeace protests against genetic engineered soya
continue. Since 7h00 this morning the organisation has been blocking a
shipment of soya  near Basel (Switzerland). The protest has been
supported by the Swiss farmers coalition and the Consumers Association
who are also opposed to the illegal import of  genetically engineered
crops. Last night in Aarhus (Denmark), the organisation had already
protested against the first shipment of genetically altered soya beans
to arrive in Scandinavia.

<p>Next week the European Commission is due to decide whether to
authorise the growth and marketing of the genetically modified corn in
Europe, as well as its importation. " The European Commission must
respect the concerns of consumers and European governments on the
health and safety of these products, and reject them outright." said
Louise Gale from Greenpeace.

<p>The corn, manufactured by Ciba Geigy, contains three different
"unnatural" genes, one of which makes it resistant to an important
antibiotic, ampicillin.  A second introduced gene gives resistance
against a weed killer, Basta, and a third modification, a bacteria
gene, produces a toxin against certain insects.  

<p>"Ciba Geigy's genetic engineered corn plays a high risk game with the
environment as well as animal and human health," says Louise Gale. 
"Ampicillin might soon lose its effectiveness against certain harmful
bacteria if these bacteria take up the ampicillin resistance. 
Ciba-Geigy's open willingness to increase this resistance is
scandalous". 

<p>For more than a year Greenpeace has been fighting against the approval
of this corn by the European Union (EU).  In June the majority of
member states registered their opposition to this genetically
engineered crop with the Commission.  Recently the European Commission
alerted the member states that genetically engineered US corn is
illegally imported into the European Union.  "What is banned in the EU
should certainly not be allowed to enter Czech Republic," says Hana
Pernicova, Greenpeace Czech Republic.  "The Czech Republic has no law
controlling the import and use of genetically engineered crops.  The
United States is taking advantage of this weakness to dump this
altered product on us."  

<p>Greenpeace calls on the European Union to take their responsibilities
seriously and to finally ban the import, growth and sale of
genetically altered crops.<br>
<br>
<hr>
<br>
<b>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:
<p>Isabelle Meister - Greenpeace International,  + 31 20 52 36 213.</b><br><br>
<hr> 
</blockquote>
</body>
</html>
 




