<HEAD>
<TITLE>GREENPEACE ACTIVISTS FIRED AT WITH RUBBER BULLETS AND HELD IN
JAIL </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="geneng.html"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/biogen.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html#geneng21"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<blockquote>

<p><b>GREENPEACE ACTIVISTS FIRED AT WITH RUBBER BULLETS AND HELD IN
JAIL 
<p>BRUSSELS,  DECEMBER 2ND 1996 </b>

 
<P>As the European Environment ministers 
prepare to discuss an intervention by Luxembourg on the mounting
public concern about gene soya - the battle over the import of
genetically altered food turned violent today with Spanish
police firing  rubber bullets at Greenpeace protesters.
 
<P>A group of 18 Greenpeace activists,  protesting the unloading of 
genetically altered soya beans from the Polish cargo ship
Uniwersytet Jaiellonski at Barcelona harbour,  were fired on at
least 10 times by police on board the cargo vessel and a police
launch. Three  Greenpeace activists received minor injuries from
rubber bullets.
 
<P>A total of 14 activists from Spain, France, Germany and the UK
were arrested by  Spanish police at around 10 pm last night
after preventing the ship,  carrying a load of gene soya from
international grain company Cargill, from unloading for several
hours. The  activists were still in police custody early this
evening. Spanish police have the power to detain them for 72
hours without charge.
 
<P>"Spain and other European countries should not be providing a
police  escort for the controversial gene soya. EU countries
should implement their rights to prevent the soya being imported
into their territory," Greenpeace European Unit spokesperson
Louise Gale said. 
 
<P>"It is highly appropriate for the EU Commission to commit  on 
December 9 and 10 to review its decision of April 1996 to allow
the gene soya into the European market.  Environmental and
health cooncerns have not been adequately assessed by the
Commission and until this is done consumers should not have gene
soya products forced on them." 
 
<p>The Spanish action was the seventh in a series of  actions
(Hamburg,  Antwerp, Ghent, New Orelans, Amsterdam, New Orleans,
Liverpool and Barcelona) during the last three weeks against
soya imports into Europe and exports from the United States.  
 
<p>"The need for a police  escort of the soya shipment  shows the
extent of public opposition to genetically altered food. Such
measures are unprecedented against a non-violent demonstration
by the environmental organisation Greenpeace." <br>
<hr>
<br>
<b>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:

<p> Louise Gale on 00-322801400 
<p>Michelle Sheather on 00-31-20-539 30971 (mobile)
 
<p>Photos available from El Pais (Madrid)  and El Periodico in
Barcelona 
 
<p>Video available from Television De Catalunya SA-TVs 00-34-3499
9333,  TV Espanola 00-34-1-3468000/4000</b>
 <br><br><HR> <br> <br> 
</blockquote>
<BR>
</body></html>
 



