http://greenpeace.org:80/~usa/reports/biodiversity/roundup/index.html 193.67.176.1 19970103135616 text/html 4474
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Fri, 03 Jan 1997 13:58:55 GMT
Server: Apache/1.0.0
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 4303
Last-modified: Wed, 09 Oct 1996 23:18:42 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>"Greenpeace Report - Not Ready for Roundup: Why Consumers Should Avoid..."</title>
<META Name="description" Content="Greenpeace report documenting the faults of genetically engineered foods.">
<META Name="keywords" Content="genetic engineering soy beans Monsanto farming pesticides Roundup Greenpeace USA environment">
<body bgcolor="#FF FF FF" text="#00 00 00" link="#00 80 00"
vlink="#80 00 00" alink="#FF FF 00" basefont=3>
<center><img src="pix/roundup5.gif" width=504 height=100 ALT="Not Ready for Roundup"></center><p>
<p>
<table width=575 cellpadding=6 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr>
<td valign=top>
<img src="pix/rdup6.gif" width=127 height=18 ALT="INTRODUCTION">
</td>
<td valign=top>
<b><font size=+1>EXECUTIVE SUMMARY of the Greenpeace Reports:<p></font>
<ul><li>
<a href="/~usa/reports/biodiversity/roundup/roundup.html">
"Not Ready for Roundup: Why Consumers and Farmers Should Avoid Monsanto's Genetically Engineered Soybeans</a>"</li>
<p>
<li><a href="/~usa/reports/biodiversity/roundup/critique.html">"Not Ready for Roundup: A Critique of Monsanto's Risk Evaluation</a>"</li></ul></b>
<p>
<hr>
<p> 
This fall, U.S. farmers will harvest the first crop of genetically engineered soybeans. The soybeans have been genetically altered by chemical giant Monsanto and contain gene sequences from bacteria and viruses.  Monsanto's Roundup Ready Soybeans (RRS) represent a crucial step in a massive genetic experiment in which humans beings and the environment are the guinea pigs.  Although this year less than 2% of US soybeans will be Roundup Ready, the plan is to mix them with traditional soybeans and introduce them into many of the hundreds of products which contain soybeans.
<p> 
Under Monsanto's plan consumers would <b>not</b> have the right to choose whether or not they want to buy or eat genetically altered food.     
<p> 
There is only one benefit of RRS: is can survive exposure to glyphosate (trade name "Roundup"). Against this single benefit weigh the risks of genetic "pollution," allergies, and rising
dependence on herbicides. Genetic engineering is a vast experiment with unknown risks. 
<p> 
Consumers simply do not want it in their food.  Dozens of companies in Europe are demanding soybeans that have not been genetically engineered. Europe is one of the largest markets for U.S.soybeans. 
<p> 
For the sake of Monsanto's profits, the U.S. soybean farmer risks losing
important markets.
<p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td valign=top>
<img src="pix/rdup7.gif" width=127 height=18 ALT="JUST THE FACTS">
</td>
<td valign=top>
<table cellpadding=10 border=1>
<tr><td valign=top>
<ul>
<li>60 percent of processed consumer food products contain soybean material -- from margarine to baby food and chocolate bars.</li>
<li>The U.S. produces most of the world's soybeans and exports about half its crop to Europe and Asia.</li>
<li>Roundup Ready Soybeans bring no benefit whatsoever to the 
consumer -- they are not cheaper, tastier or healthier.</li>
<li>A poll shows over 80 per cent of consumers in Germany are opposed to
genetically engineered food. Germany purchases 1 272 300 Metric Tons of U.S. soybeans per year.</li>
<li>Roundup Ready Soybeans will increase farmer's dependency and use of
Monsanto's chemical herbicide Roundup.</li>
<li>15 percent of Monsanto's total sales is accounted for by Roundup, and it is the world's best selling herbicide</li>
<li>There is significant evidence that Roundup can cause harm to the
environment and human health even at current levels of use.</li>
<li>Other genetically engineered foods have caused unpredicted allergies, illnesses and even death.</li>
<li>Genetically engineered organisms have been known to cross-breed with
wild plants causing unpredictable and irreversible changes to natural
ecosystems.</li>
</ul>
<p>
</td></tr>
</table>
</td></tr>
</table>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b>
Please see our <a href="/~usa/pubinfo/publist.html">Public Information page</a> for 
other Greenpeace Reports.<p>
<a href="/~usa/index.html">Return to Greenpeace USA Homepage</a></b>
<p>
<font size=-1>
