 <title>GREENPEACE TARGETS "HERRING DERBY" IN ENGLISH CHANNEL
</title>
</head>

<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">

<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%>
<tr>
<td><a href="../fish/herr01.html"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60 src="../icons/bioocea.gif"></a>

<a href="newsindx.html#her01"><img src="../icons/bionews.gif" border=0 height=60 width=60 align=right></a></td>
</tr>
</table>

<blockquote>
<p><b>GREENPEACE TARGETS "HERRING DERBY" IN ENGLISH CHANNEL
</b></p>
<b><p>AMSTERDAM DECEMBER 11TH 1996</b> 

<p>The Greenpeace ship 'MV Sirius' today
started to prevent herring trawlers from fishing in the English
Channel near the French town of Dieppe. Greenpeace activists used
inflatables to atttach themselves with ropes to the stern of the
fishing vessel Helen Mary, preventing it from hauling its nets while
other activists attached a banner to the Helen Mary, reading "save our
seas". 

<p>The ongoing actions are directed against mostly Dutch and German
freezer trawlers, fishing primarily  for fish eggs, which are exported
to Japan as a New Year's celebration delicacy. 

<p>The actions take place at the so-called 'Herring Derby' in December
when shoals of herring are forced to run the gauntlet of powerful
modern fishing vessels as the fish pass from the North Sea to the
English Channel to spawn. 

<p>"Greenpeace is demanding an immediate end to the herring-roe fishery,
" said Greenpeace campaigner Just van den Broek, on  board of the
Sirius, adding that "the practice of specifically targetting the eggs
of a seriously depleted fish stock is absurd". The North Sea herring
stock this year reached a historical low of 500.000 tons. 

<p>In July 1996, the EU took an emergency action which meant a cut-back
in herring fisheries of 50%. According to Greenpeace however this was
insufficient, since it would only lead to a restoration to the Minimum
Biologically Acceptable level of 800.000 ton. Below this level the
chance of stock collapse increases dramatically. 

<p>The current situation is comparable to the 1970s which saw a dramatic
collapse in this fishing industry resulting in a total ban on herring
catch for six years. In the 1980's the policy aimed at a stock of 2.2
million. However, the stock only grew to 1.3 million tons in 1989
because of the failure of the European fisheries policy.

<p>"North Sea fish stocks are being over fished. Greenpeace will do
everything in it's power to protect the North Sea ecosystem and
prevent the continued deterioration of these fish stocks. Stopping the
short sighted fishing on spawning stocks is part of this effort." said
van den Broek.  

<p>Note to  Editors: The Helen Mary was subsidised by the EU and the
German Government Note, approximately 12 million DM. The vessel can
freeze 280 tonnes of fish a day, and can store some 4,000 tonnes on
board.<br><br>  
<hr>
<br> 
<p><b>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT: </b></p>
<p><B>Just van den Broek, Greenpeace campaigner on board MV Sirius<br>
++31 653 106 592 or ++ 31 653 280 633 

<p>Robbie Kelman Greenpeace International fisheries campaign <br> 
++31 20 5236 558

<p>For video footage please contact Reuters TV in London or France 3<br></b>
<hr>
<br>
<br>
</blockquote>
</body>
</html>




 


