<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press Release: GREENPEACE MV SIRIUS TOWED AWAY AND CAPTAIN ARRESTED FOR BLOCKADING
GENETICALLY CONTAMINATED SOYA  SHIPMENT
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="geneng.html"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/biogen.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html#geneng18"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<blockquote>

<p><b>GREENPEACE MV SIRIUS TOWED AWAY AND CAPTAIN ARRESTED FOR BLOCKADING
GENETICALLY CONTAMINATED SOYA  SHIPMENT

<p>AMSTERDAM, NOVEMBER 23RD 1996</b>
<P>The captain of the Greenpeace ship MV
Sirius was arrested today, and the ship towed away by Dutch police
after activists from the environmental organisation started a protest
against the import of genetically contaminated soybeans by the US
grain company Cargill. 

<P>The Sirius action against the bulk carrier Pawnee started around 12h00
when Greenpeace activists in inflatables painted the slogan " No X

soya " on the ship as it steamed along the canal leading to Amsterdam.
At about 15h30, the Sirius occupied the berth of the Pawnee, thus
preventing her from unloading. Soon afterward, the Amsterdam
Harbourmaster issued a temporary sailing prohibition for the 100
metres waters around the berth and Greenpeace campaigners entered a
dialogue with the Cargill company. 

<P>At 18h30, Albert Kuiken - the captain of the Sirius -  was arrested by
the Dutch police because he refused to move the ship until Cargill
agreed to take steps towards the separation of genetically engineered
soybeans. At 19h00 approximately, more police boarded the ship and

tugboats towed her 200 metres outside the 100 metres "exclusion zone"
where she was released. 

<P>On 14th of November the European Parliament called on member
governments to segregate genetically engineered soya. "Cargill has
already ignored the wishes of European consumers, retailers and
environmental groups to have the genetically engineered soya
separated" said Isabel McCrea from Greenpeace International. " We want
and we will keep the option of the freedom to demonstrate against this
lack of consideration for the consumers' will and for the
environment." 

<P>These events occurred only 24 hours after the Sirius was freed from a
9 day long seizure in Antwerp, after being issued with a court order
to pay around $US 25,000 for lost earnings, when Greenpeace delayed
the unloading of a shipment of genetically contaminated soya from the
Malaysian vessel Bunga Saga Empa on 10th November.



<P>"This kind of heavy-handed response will not deter Greenpeace from its
campaign against genetic engineering, which will be continuing over
the coming weeks and months" said McCrea.

<P>The captain of the Sirius was released on Saturday late evening
without charges.<br>
<hr>
<br> 
<B>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:
<p>Luisa Colasimone, Greenpeace International Press Desk, mobile (+31)
06  532 38 475 <P>MV Sirius, mobile (+31) 06 532 80 633


</B>
 <br><br><HR> <br> <br> 
</blockquote>
<BR>
</body></html>
 
