<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press Release: US GRAIN GIANT ATTEMPTS TO GAG GREENPEACE EUROPEAN SOYA
PROTEST   
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="geneng.html"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/biogen.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html#geneng15"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<blockquote>

<p><b>US GRAIN GIANT ATTEMPTS TO GAG GREENPEACE EUROPEAN SOYA
PROTEST   




<p>ANTWERP, NOVEMBER 15TH 1996</b>
<p>Only 24 hours after the
European Parliament called on member governments to segregate
and label genetically engineered soya, Greenpeace has been
prevented from taking action to protest against the next
shipment of genetically contaminated soya into Belgium.
 
<p>The US grain distributor and processor Cargill has obtained a
preventative injunction from the Belgian courts prohibiting
Greenpeace from getting within one kilometre of the ship
Stanislaw Kulczynski due to arrive into Antwerp this weekend.
Fines of one million Belgian francs per hour will be imposed
if Greenpeace breaks the injunction.
 
<p>"So much for free speech," said Greenpeace campaigner Isabelle
Meister. "Cargill has already ignored the wishes of European
consumers, retailers and environmental groups and now even the
European Parliament. We thought we at least had the option of
the freedom to demonstrate but incredibly the Belgian courts
have joined forces with a US multinational to prevent
legitimate public protest. We hope this action will be
condemned by the European Union."  
<p>Last weekend Cargill obtained a court order against Greenpeace
when activists held up a shipment of soya on board a Polish
registered bulk carrier coming from the USA. This injunction
stipulated fines of one million Belgian francs per hour if the
protest had continued.
 
<p>Greenpeace reluctantly called off its action but held up a
second delivery of soya the following day being delivered into
Gent by the Bunga Saga Empa. The Malaysian owners also
obtained a court order to halt the action and the Greenpeace
ship the MV Sirius has been impounded in Antwerp docks.   
Greenpeace has launched an international campaign to halt the
release of genetically engineered organisms into the
environment. Protests have taken place throughout Europe and
the United States. This week the MV Greenpeace is on the
Mississippi outside New Orleans. Yesterday 17 Greenpeace
activists were arrested when they chained themselves to barges
and an unloading facility at another major US soya
distributor, ADM. 
<br>
<hr>
<br> 
<B>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:
<p>James Gillies in Amsterdam on
31 20 524 9548 or <p>Jon Walter on mobile phone (31 20) 6 5323
8475

</B>
 <br><br><HR> <br> <br> 
</blockquote>
<BR>
</body></html>
 
