<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press Release: GREENPEACE HALTS OPERATIONS AT ADM GRAIN TERMINAL

</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="geneng.html"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/biogen.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html#geneng14"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<blockquote>

<p><b>GREENPEACE HALTS OPERATIONS AT ADM GRAIN TERMINAL


<p>NEW ORLEANS, LA, NOVEMBER 14TH, 1996</b>
<p>Today Greenpeace occupied the ADM grain
terminal located 60 miles outside of New Orleans.  Activists wearing blue
coveralls with "Genetic Experiment"  written on them and white hard hats,
climbed into and attached themselves onto the 200 foot soybean barges that were
being prepared for export.  These actions caused grain operators to stop all
unloading operations.  Additional activists dressed in white uniforms and
wearing protective face mask and goggles chained themselves to the front
entryway of the grain facility. Today's action marks day four of  the week-long
Greenpeace protest against the release of  genetically engineered soybeans into
the marketplace. 
 
<p>Monsanto's genetically altered "Roundup Ready" soybeans are currently being
exported to Europe and are set to hit the market for the first time this year.
A large fraction of the U.S. soybean output is exported to Europe, and 90% of
those exports go through the port of New Orleans.  The beans are engineered to
tolerate Monsanto's Roundup herbicide.  Environmentalists, farmers and
consumers are concerned about the potential environmental impact of the release
of genetically modified organisms and the subsequent threat to human health.
 
<p>"These grain companies must be stopped from contaminating the environment and
the food we eat with these genetic experiments," said Greenpeace spokesperson
Beth Fitzgerald.
 
<p>Soybeans are the United States' second largest agricultural export, with over
40% of the total crop exported to Europe last year.  Over one hundred European
retailers, food manufacturers, and food processors have already refused to
accept Monsanto's genetically engineered soybeans due to concerns of health
hazards and environmental safety. While they account for only 2% of this years
crop,  Roundup Ready soybeans are planned to be mixed with normal soybeans
before export, therefore contaminating the entire supply.  Loss of this $6
billion market, due to Monsanto's contamination of these beans by mixing, would
cripple the American farm economy.
 
<p>"It is an outrage that this experiment is being forced on consumers around the
world without their knowledge or consent. These contaminated soybeans must be
taken off the market." said Greenpeace international genetic engineering
campaigner Michelle Sheather,  who was chained onto one of the soybean barges.
 
<p>Greenpeace believes that genetically engineered organisms should not be
released into the environment.  They are artificial life forms and their
behavior is unpredictable once planted.  They are able to reproduce and may
mutate to create new organisms which could do irreversible damage to the
environment.  Greenpeace demands that Monsanto's genetically engineered
soybeans be immediately taken off the market.

<p>

<br>
<hr>
<br> 
<B>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:
<p>Terri Johnson, Greenpeace Press Officer, New Orleans - (504)566-9500 or
(504)566-9501
<p>Tzeporah Berman, Greenpeace Biodiversity Campaigner, on site - (504) 421-5262
 
<p>Video available via satellite:  2:30P - 3:00P (EST) ON Telstar 402 (C-band),
Transponder 8
(Line:3860, horiz./down).  Call Washington Int'l Teleport for fiber/playback
details at: (703) 256-3870



</B>
 <br><br><HR> <br> <br> 
</blockquote>
<BR>
