<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press Release: GREENPEACE PROTESTERS ARRESTED WHILE OCCUPYING GRAIN TERMINAL  


</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="geneng.html"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/biogen.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html#geneng13"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<blockquote>

<p><b>GREENPEACE PROTESTERS ARRESTED WHILE OCCUPYING GRAIN TERMINAL  
<p>DESTREHEN, LOUISIANA, NOVEMBER 14TH 1996 </b>
<p>Seventeen
Greenpeace activists were arrested today as they occupied the
Archer Daniels Midland (ADM) grain terminal located 60 miles
outside of New Orleans.  Eight activists wearing blue
coveralls with "Genetic Experiment"  written on them and white
hard hats, climbed into and attached themselves onto the 200
foot soybean barges that were being prepared for export. 
These actions caused grain operators to stop all unloading
operations for  over  three hours.  Another nine activists
dressed in white uniforms and wearing protective face masks
and goggles chained themselves to the front entryway of the
grain facility. Today's action marks day four of  the week-
long Greenpeace protest against the release of  genetically
engineered soybeans into the marketplace. 
 
<p>Prior to arrest, the activists were informed by police that,
if they did not disengage themselves voluntarily, pepper spray
would be used and all participants in the protest would be
arrested. 
 
<p>Today the European Parliament adopted with overwhelming
majority a resolution to call on US soybean producers and all
other producers of genetically modified foodstuffs to
segregate those organisms from conventional ones.  Monsanto's
genetically altered "Roundup Ready" soybeans are currently
being exported to Europe and are set to hit the market for the
first time this year.  "These grain companies must be stopped
from contaminating the environment and the food we eat with
these genetic experiments," said Greenpeace spokesperson Beth
Fitzgerald.
 
<p>Soybeans are the United States' second largest agricultural
export, with over 40% of the total crop exported to Europe
last year.  Over one hundred European retailers, food
manufacturers, and food processors have already refused to
accept Monsanto's genetically engineered soybeans due to
concerns of health hazards and environmental safety. While
they account for only 2% of this years crop,  Roundup Ready
soybeans are planned to be mixed with normal soybeans before
export, thereby contaminating the entire supply.  Loss of this
$6 billion market, due to Monsanto's contamination of these
beans by mixing, would cripple the American farm economy.
 
<p>"It is an outrage that this experiment is being forced on
consumers around the world without their knowledge or consent.
These contaminated soybeans must be taken off the market."
said Greenpeace International Genetic Engineering campaigner
Michelle Sheather,  who was chained onto one of the soybean
barges.  
 
<p>Greenpeace believes that genetically engineered organisms
should not be released into the environment.  They are
artificial life forms and their behaviour is unpredictable
once planted.  They are able to reproduce and may mutate to
create new organisms which could do irreversible damage to the
environment.  Greenpeace demands that Monsanto's genetically
engineered soybeans be immediately taken off the market.<br>
<hr>
<br> 
<B>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:
<p>Terri Johnson, Greenpeace Press Officer, New Orleans -
(504)566-9500 or (504)566-9501
<p>Tzeporah Berman, Greenpeace Biodiversity Campaigner, on site -
(504) 421-5262  
<p>Photos available via wire services:  Reuters, AFP,  AP or
contact Greenpeace office: (504)566-9500
<p>Video footage available contact:  Greenpeace New Orleans
office (504)566-0500 or (504) 421-5262


</B>
 <br><br><HR> <br> <br> 
</blockquote>
