<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press Release: GREENPEACE HALTS  SOYA EXPORT OPERATION IN USA

</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="geneng.html"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/biogen.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html#geneng12"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<blockquote>

<p><b>GREENPEACE HALTS  SOYA EXPORT OPERATION IN USA
<p>NEW ORLEANS, NOVEMBER 14TH 1996 </b>
<p>Greenpeace's campaign
against genetic engineering crossed the Atlantic today as
activists stopped the unloading of genetically contaminated
soya at a facility just outside New Orleans, the US's main
soya export terminal.
 
<p>About 15 activists  --  wearing overalls with "Genetic
Experiment" written on them -- chained themselves to barges
and unloading facilities at the ADM grain terminal just
outside New Orleans. This is the first crop of the genetically
engineered soya and ADM has refused to segregate it from
normal soya.  
 
<p>"These grain companies must be stopped from contaminating the
environment and the food we eat with these genetic
experiments," said Greenpeace campaigner Beth Fitzgerald.
 
<p>Soya beans are the United States' second largest agricultural
export, with over 40 per cent of the total crop exported going
to Europe. Opposition to Monsanto's genetically engineered
soya bean amongst European retailers, food manufacturers and
food processors is growing. Some have already refused to
accept the soya due to concerns about health hazards and
environmental safety.  
 
<p>As the US protest got underway the European parliament in
Strasbourg was about to vote on a resolution calling for the
segregation and labelling of the genetically engineered soya.
This would be a direct challenge to the decision already taken
by the European Commission to allow the soya into Europe
without labelling.
 
<p>Only yesterday the Commission delayed an expected announcement
on the approval of another genetically engineered crop -- Ciba
Geigy's corn.  
 
<p>Meanwhile the Greenpeace ship the MV Sirius was impounded in
Antwerp, Belgium after being issued with a court order to pay
around $US18,000 for lost earnings when Greenpeace delayed the
unloading of a shipment of genetically contaminated soya from
the Malaysian vessel Bunga Saga Empa on Sunday.
 
<br>
<hr>
<br> 
<B>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:
<p>James Gillies or Jon Walter in
Amsterdam on 31 20 524 9548 or <p>Terri Jonson or Tzeporah Berman
in New Orleans on 1 504 566 9500 or 1 504 421 5262
 
<p>Photographs may be available through Reuters, AP and AFP
 
<p>Video footage -- contact Maggie Dolan or Gina Walker in
Amsterdam on 31 20 524 9543/4


</B>
 <br><br><HR> <br> <br> 
</blockquote>
<BR>
</body></html>
