<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press Release: GREENPEACE QUARANTINES CONTAMINATED SOYBEAN SHIPMENTS



</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="geneng.html"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/biogen.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html#geneng11"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<blockquote>

<p><b>GREENPEACE QUARANTINES CONTAMINATED SOYBEAN SHIPMENTS

<p>NEW ORLEANS, LOUISIANA, NOVEMBER 13TH, 1996 </b>

<p>Today the
international environmental group Greenpeace escalated its
campaign against Monsanto's genetically engineered soybeans by
launching a full investigation of five grain terminals along
the Mississippi River.  Greenpeace activists, wearing white
inspection suits and protection masks examined the barges and
labelled the sides with signs that read " X - Genetic
Experiment" and "Biohazard Monsanto Soybeans."      
 
<p>"By allowing these mutant soybeans to contaminate U.S.
exports, these grain companies are spreading an environmental
hazard and putting consumers at risk," said Tzeporah Berman
from onboard the MV Greenpeace.
 
<p>Soybeans are the United States' second largest agricultural
export, with approximately 40% of the crop exported to Europe. 
Over one hundred European retailers, food manufactures, and
food processors, have refused to accept Monsanto's genetically
engineered soybeans due to concerns of health hazards and
environmental safety.
 
<p>Amounting to less than 2% of this soybean crop, Roundup Ready
soybeans are planned to be mixed with normal soybeans before
export, therefore contaminating the entire supply.  Loss of
this 6 billion dollar market,  due to the mixing of these
beans,  will devastate the American farm economy.
 
<p>This week Greenpeace activist in Switzerland, hung a banner on
the headquarters of Nestle, calling for the company to ensure
that their products were free of contaminated soybeans.  In
Germany, 40 activist were arrested yesterday for protesting at
a soybean oil mill, owned by U.S. grain company, Archer
Daniels Midland (ADM).
 
<p>Michelle Sheather, Greenpeace International spokesperson
concluded, "Greenpeace will continue to protest around the
world to stop the release of alien species into the natural
environment."
 

<br>
<hr>
<br> 
<B>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:
<p>Terri Johnson, Greenpeace Press Officer, New Orleans:
(504)566-9500 or(504)566-9501
<p>Tzeporah Berman, Greenpeace Spokesperson, New Orleans: (504)
421-5262 Or visit our website: http://www.greenpeace.org/~usa/
<p>Video and photographs available.



</B>
 <br><br><HR> <br> <br> 
</blockquote>
<BR>
