<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press Release: FOOD INDUSTRY STIFLES GENETIC ENGINEERING DEBATE WITH SECOND
COURT ORDER AGAINST GREENPEACE ACTIONS 




</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="geneng.html"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/biogen.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html#geneng10"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<blockquote>

<p><b>FOOD INDUSTRY STIFLES GENETIC ENGINEERING DEBATE WITH SECOND
COURT ORDER AGAINST GREENPEACE ACTIONS 


<p>GENT, BELGIUM NOVEMBER 10TH, 1996 </b>

<p>Greenpeace's second
major action within 48 hours to try to prevent contaminated
soya beans getting into European food has again been thwarted
by a court order.
 
<p>Vamo Mills, 55 per cent owned by oil and margarine
manufacturer Van Demoortele, and Gent Grain Terminal obtained
an injunction forcing Greenpeace to halt its blockade of the
latest delivery of genetically engineered soya from the United
States. Greenpeace ship the MV Sirius had been occupying the
berth of the bulk carrier Bunga Saga Empat in Gent, Belgium,
for about five hours, in order to prevent it unloading its
cargo.
 
<p>The court order stipulated that Greenpeace would be fined one
million Belgian francs per person for every hour that the
protest continued. It was presented to Greenpeace around
midday and required Greenpeace to leave immediately.
 
<p>"We hope the public will recognise these moves as yet another
attempt by the food giants to withhold information about what
is going into our food and to stifle debate about the whole
issue of genetically engineered organisms," said Greenpeace
campaigner Isabel McCrea.
 
<p>"The food industry has decided to force genetically engineered
food down our throats. They are not even prepared to discuss
the issue. When Greenpeace tries to draw the public's
attention to what is happening they bring in lawyers and court
actions."
 
<p>On Thursday, Greenpeace held up the unloading of a shipment of
genetically contaminated soya beans being imported by the
grain company Cargill as it arrived into Antwerp, Belgium. The
action ended after 24 hours following a similar court action
from Cargill. Greenpeace complied with the court order but
said its campaign would continue. Greenpeace believes
genetically engineered organisms pose a serious risk to
biodiversity and should not be released into the environment.
 

<br>
<hr>
<br> 
<B>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:
<p>Jon Walter on the MV Sirius
on 31 6 5323 8475 or <p>James Gillies in Amsterdam on 31 20 524
9548 or <p>Isabel McCrea on mobile phone 31 6 5341 7945



</B>
 <br><br><HR> <br> <br> 
</blockquote>
<BR>
