<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press Release: GREENPEACE HOLDS UP SECOND CONTAMINATED SOYA SHIPMENT IN 48 HOURS
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="geneng.html"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/biogen.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html#geneng8"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<blockquote>

<p><b>GREENPEACE HOLDS UP SECOND CONTAMINATED SOYA SHIPMENT IN 48 HOURS


<p>GENT, BELGIUM NOVEMBER 10TH 1996</b>
<p>Greenpeace today held up the
unloading of another shipment of US soya beans, believed to be
genetically contaminated,  as it arrived at Gent harbour in Belgium
early this morning.

<p>The Greenpeace vessel the MV Sirius anchored in the berth of the bulk
carrier Bunga Saga Empat preventing the vessel from unloading at Vamo
Mills, 55 per cent owned by oil and margarine manufacturer Van
Demoortele.

<p>Some 25 activists from 12 countries using inflatable boats intend to
chain themselves to the anchor chain of the Sirius thus preventing
port authorities from moving the Greenpeace vessel.

<p>Greenpeace is calling on Vamo Mills to segregate genetically
engineered soya from the natural beans and to refuse to accept further
shipments of genetically altered beans.

<p>The US shipment is believed to contain Monsanto's Roundup Ready soya
beans which have been genetically manipulated to be resistant to the
weedkiller Roundup produced by the US agrochemical mulitnational.

<p>Soya beans are currently used in 60 per cent of proccessed food in
supermarkets.

<p>"The public is being used as guinea pigs by companies like Monsanto
which are forcing them to accept genetically manipulated products in
their food without their knowledge or consent," said Greenpeace
campaigner Martin Besieux. 

<p>"Millers likes Vamo and processign companies like Unilever should
acknowledge the public concern and demand segregation."

<p>On Thursday Greenpeace held up the unloading of a shipment of
genetically altered soya beans imported by grain company Cargill
arriving into Antwerp in Belgium. The action ended after 24 hours when
Cargill was granted a court order threatening one million Belgian
franc fines per hour if the blockade continued. Greenpeace complied
with the court order but said its campaign.

<p>Greenpeace believes that genetically engineered organisms shold not be
released into the environment. They are alien life forms and once
planted their behaviour is unpredictable. The may be able to reproduce
and mutate creating organisms which could do irreversible damage to
the environment.


<br>
<hr>
<br> 
<B>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:
<P>Jon Walter on board the Sirius on 31
6 5323 8475 
<P>James Gillies: 31 20 524 9548
</B>
 <br><br><HR> <br> <br> 
</blockquote>
