<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press Release: CARGILL COURT INJUNCTION STOPS GREENPEACE BLOCKADE OF GENETECH SOYA 
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="geneng.html"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/biogen.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html#geneng7"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<blockquote>

<p><b>CARGILL COURT INJUNCTION STOPS GREENPEACE 
BLOCKADE OF GENETECH SOYA 


<p>ANTWERP, NOVEMBER 8TH 1996</b>
<p>A court injunction has ended a  24 hour 
Greenpeace blockade of one of the first
shipments from the United States believed to contain genetically
engineered soya beans..

<p>The order stipulated that Greenpeace would be fined 1,000,000 Belgian
francs for every hour that the protest continued and set a 1 km
exclusion zone around the ship. Greenpeace hung a banner on the
Cargill unloading facility stating  Genetic experiment - don t buy it
, before the ship came within 1 km of the dock.

<p>Cargill obtained the court order and it was delivered by a court
official to the Greenpeace boat, Sirius, at 16.32 pm . It required
Greenpeace to withdraw, within in one hour,  all activists and boats
from the lock where 

the Polish bulk carrier Ziemia Zamojska had been held since 5.30 pm
Thursday. Activists chained an inflatable boat to the rudder of the
vessel.

<p> Just like consumers Greenpeace had no choice but to end its blockade
 of 
this shipment,  said Greenpeace campaigner Isabelle McCrea.

<p> These heavy handed tactics of Cargill are typical of the approach by
 the 
multinational companies which are forcing  genetically engineered food
onto consumers without their knowledge or their consent,  said McCrea.
Greenpeace is calling on U.S grain giant Cargill to keep their
 genetically engineered soya beans separate from natural soya beans.

<p>McCrea said  obviously Greenpeace  could not  afford  such a large
potential fine and  reluctantly called off its action.  But this is
not the end of Greenpeace s campaign against  genetically engineered
organisms,  she said.

<p>McCrea said the action had been successful in warning the public about
what is to happen to their food with the introduction of genetically
engineered organisms.   We will be continuing to highlight the risks
to the environment and to human health in the coming weeks and months,
 she said. .

<br>
<hr>
<br> 
<B>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:
<P>Greenpeace International.
<P>James Gillies: 31-6-534 17945
<P>Isabelle McCrea: 31-6-532 80633
<P>Michelle
Sheather or Isabelle Meister: 3120--523 6222 or after 6pm on
3120-5249529 or 3120-5236213 

</B>
 <br><br><HR> <br> <br> 
</blockquote>
