<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press Release: GREENPEACE BLOCKS SHIPMENT OF GENETICALLY ENGINEERED SOYA, DAY2

</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="geneng.html"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/biogen.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html#geneng6"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<blockquote>

<p><b>GREENPEACE BLOCKS SHIPMENT OF GENETICALLY ENGINEERED SOYA, DAY 2


<p>ANTWERP, NOVEMBER 8TH 1996</b>
<p>Greenpeace has now held-up, for more than
15 hours, one of the first US shipments of genetically contaminated
soya  beans to Europe at Antwerp harbour in Belgium. 

<p>Greenpeace activists have held the Polish registered bulk carrier,
Ziemia Zamojsk by chaining an inflatable boat to the rudder of the
vessel. It left Cleveland, Ohio on October 8 and was due to unload at
the wharf of US  grain multinational, Cargill at 5.00 pm yesterday
Greenpeace has demanded Cargill segregate its supplies of genetically
altered soya and refuse further shipments. The company has not yet
indicated a willingness to comply.

<p>Earlier Cargill, in a faxed letter to Greenpeace on November 4,  said
"we confirm there are soya beans on this vessel (Ziemia
Zamojska)....we are not able to confirm or deny the presence of
Roundup Ready soybeans because these beans are not separated from
traditional soybeans at harvest". Such beans have been genetically
altered to be resistant to US multinational Monsanto's commercial weed
killer Roundup. 

<p>The US grain multinational Cargill, which is importing the soya beans,
has been in contact with the ship. In a letter deliver to the Sirius
at 10 pm Cargill stated. "We note that Greenpeace activists are
currently impeding the legal progress of the Ziemia Zamojska into our
Antwerp dock. This action is dangerous and should be halted
immediately."

<p>"European supermarkets, food manufacturers, consumer and environmental
groups have made it clear that they don't want their food contaminated
with genetically engineered soya," said Greenpeace campaigner Isabelle
McCrea, referring to the growing list of organisations opposed to
mixing the soya beans . "We want to stop food being contaminated by
genetically altered soya beans"

<p>Soya beans are used in an estimated 60 per cent of processed
supermarket food products, including bread, chocolate, cakes,
margarine, ice-cream and pasta. 

<p>Greenpeace has already identified enough natural soya beans for the
European market from the US and Canada.( Roundup ready soya beans
comprise only two per cent of this year's US harvest). Greenpeace also
dismissed industry claims that segregation was impractical. "Certified
segregation is already occurring and to claim that this can't be done
is simply an attempt by a few big companies to force their product on
consumers." Greenpeace is calling on major food processing companies
such as Unilever International to refuse to use the genetically
altered soya beans. 

<p>On Tuesday night Greenpeace protested against the arrival of a US
shipment of soya beans, believed to contain genetically altered beans,
 when it arrived in Hamburg Germany. 

<br>
<hr>
<br> 
<B>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:
<P>Greenpeace International.
<P>James Gillies: 31-6-534 17945
<P>Isabelle McCrea: 31-6-532 80633
<P>Michelle
Sheather or Isabelle Meister: 3120--523 6222 or after 6pm on
3120-5249529 or 3120-5236213 
<p>Video footage will be available from 
Reuters TV and WTN London, for more details contact Maggie Dolan
31-20-5249 543 
<P>Photos should be available through Reuters, AP and AFP  

</B>
 <br><br><HR> <br> <br> 
</blockquote>
