<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press Release: GREENPEACE BLOCKS SHIPMENT OF GENETICALLY ENGINEERED SOYA

</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="geneng.html"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/biogen.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html#geneng5"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<blockquote>

<p><b>GREENPEACE BLOCKS SHIPMENT OF GENETICALLY ENGINEERED SOYA


<p>ANTWERP, November 7th 1996	</b>

<P>Greenpeace today stepped up its campaign against
the release of genetically altered organisms by blocking the unloading of a
U.S. grain shipment believed to contain genetically altered soya beans in
Antwerp, Belgium, this morning .
 
<P>About 25 activists from twelve different countries using inflatable boats
blocked the Polish registered bulk carrier, Ziemia Zamojska,  which left
Cleveland, Ohio on October 8, from unloading at the wharf of US  grain
multinational, Cargill.   
 
<P>Cargill, in a faxed letter to Greenpeace on November 4,  said "we confirm there
are soya beans on this vessel (Ziemia Zamojska)....we are not able to confirm
or deny the presence of Roundup Ready soybeans because these beans are not
separated from traditional soybeans at harvest". Such beans have been
genetically altered to be resistant to US multinational Monsanto's commercial
weed killer Roundup. 
 
<P>Greenpeace is calling on Cargill to demand the segregation of the soya and to
reject further shipments of the genetically engineered beans. 
 
<P>"European supermarkets, food manufacturers, consumer and environmental groups
have made it clear that they don't want their food contaminated with
genetically engineered soya," said Greenpeace campaigner Isabelle McCrea,
referring to the growing list of organisations opposed to mixing the soya beans
. "We want to stop food being contaminated by genetically altered soya beans"
 
<P>Soya beans are used in an estimated 60 per cent of processed supermarket food
products, including bread, chocolate, cakes, margarine, ice-cream and pasta. 
 
<P>Greenpeace has already identified enough natural soya beans for the European
market from the US and Canada.( Roundup ready soya beans comprise only two per
cent of this year's US harvest). Greenpeace also dismissed industry claims that
segregation was impractical. "Certified segregation is already occurring and to
claim that this can't be done is simply an attempt by a few big companies to
force their product on consumers." Greenpeace is calling on major food
processing companies such as Unilever International to refuse to use the
genetically altered soya beans. 
 
<P>"This is a huge experiment with nature," added Ms McCrea. "Greenpeace believes
that genetically engineered organisms should not be released into the
environment. They are alien life forms and once planted their behaviour is
unpredictable. They may be able to reproduce and mutate creating organisms
which could do irreversible damage to the environment."
 
<P>On Tuesday night Greenpeace protested against the arrival of a US shipment of
soya beans, believed to contain genetically altered beans,  when it arrived in
Hamburg Germany. 
<br>
<hr>
<br> 
<B>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:
<P>Greenpeace International.
<P>James Gillies: 31-6-534 17945
<P>Isabelle McCrea: 31-6-532 80633
<P>Jon Walter or Isabelle Meister: 3120--523 6222

</B>
 <br><br><HR> <br> <br> 
</blockquote>
<BR>
