<head>
  <title>WORKING GROUP ESTABLISHED FOR THE PROTECTION OF THE KARELIAN OLD
GROWTH FORESTS AND PRIMEVAL FORESTS
</title>
   
</head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">

<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%>
<tr>
<td><a href="russia.html"><img src="../icons/biofor.gif" border=2 height=80 width=60 align=left></a><a href="newsindx.html#luebeck1"><img src="../icons/bionews.gif" border=0 height=60 width=60 align=right></a></td>
</tr>
</table>
<blockquote>
<p><b>WORKING GROUP ESTABLISHED FOR THE PROTECTION OF THE KARELIAN OLD
GROWTH FORESTS AND PRIMEVAL FORESTS
<p>ENSO announces a one year moratorium for controversial forest
areas in Karelia and Murmansk
</b></p>

<P><B>HELSINKI OCTOBER 22ND 1996 </B>
<p>After months of sometimes very
difficult discussions, a national Karelian working group will be
formed by 31 January 1997 at the latest for the purpose of
preserving the ecologically important old growth forests and
primeval forests as well as to introduce sustainable forestry.

<p>This is the result of an initiative of the Finnish paper and
forestry group ENSO Oy, the Karelian and Finnish ministries for
the environment .....

<p>.....the members of the Karelian working group may only be
nationals of Karelia. The groups which have an interest and will
participate in this are the state, the wood processing
industries, the population affected as well as the environmental
protection groups.

<p>The working group should set up a list of criteria within one
year. According to this list is will be possible to classify
Karelia's important natural forests. Stock will then be taken of
the forest areas which should be preserved. The current network
of conservation areas should thus be extended on this basis. 

<p>The intention is that the provisional plan will be adopted
jointly at a conference organised by ENSO at the end of 1997.  

<p>In order to support the activity of the working group ....ENSO
will organise a moratorium for all regions in Karelia and
Murmansk which have so far been regarded by WWF and Greenpeace
as being worthy of protection. The moratorium is valid for one
year and affects a region of almost two million hectares. Since
September 15, 1996, ENSO has no longer been renewing its import
contracts for the forest regions in question. The last contracts
will expire in December 1996. An independent assessment group
will ensure that the moratorium is upheld. ENSO is currently in
negotiation with various institutes. 
  
<br><br><hr><br><b>
<p>FOR MORE INFORMATION:  
<p>Thomas Henningsen or Patricia Fromm in Luebeck, mobile ++49-172-3818-149
<p>Greenpeace press officer Svenja Koch in Luebeck, mobile ++49-172-2518504
or <p>the Greenpeace forest campaign in Hamburg, ++49-40-30618-321.

<p></b>
</blockquote>
