<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press release: October 18th, 1996, US ON THE BRINK OF LOSING EUROPEAN MARKETS FOR SOYBEANS
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="geneng.html"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/biogen.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html#geneng3"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<blockquote>

<p><b>US ON THE BRINK OF LOSING EUROPEAN MARKETS FOR SOYBEANS
</b>
<p>Greenpeace releases new statements from European consumers

<p><b>ST. LOUIS, MO., OCTOBER 18TH, 1996</b>

<p>At the Society of Environmental Journalist's
Conference in Missouri today Greenpeace released recent statements from
European consumers who do not want to purchase genetically engineered soybeans.
The statements reveal that concern is growing amongst major food retailers and
producers regarding the potential human health risks and the environmental
hazards of genetic engineering.
 
<p>"For the sake of Monsanto's Roundup sales, farmers are risking not only food
safety but their export markets," said genetic engineering expert Isabelle
Meister, of Greenpeace International. "Consumers in Europe do not want to buy
genetically manipulated foods."
 
<p>Several European countries, food companies and consumer organizations have

expressed opposition to the engineered soybean (list available).  Europe buys
about 25%of the U.S. soybean production. Tuesday, Norway's Daglivarhandelns
Environmental and Packaging Forum, which includes almost all Norwegian food
retailers and wholesalers, wrote to the U.S. Embassy that: "We refuse to sell
products containing soya from the U.S. unless the U.S. distinguishes clearly
between traditional soya beans and the beans that have been genetically
manipulated." 
 
<p>In a related development, Safeway, the third largest food retailer in the UK
noted in a letter to Greenpeace UK that, "We are working with suppliers of
Safeway brand products containing soybean or soya derivatives to identify other
sources of conventional soybean and explore the possibilities of reformulating
some products to utilise alternatives to soya."
 
<p>Greenpeace activists in Germany, Sweden, Austria, and England also conducted
protests this week against Unilever, Europe's largest food company, which has
yet to exclude Monsanto's genetically engineered soybeans from its product
lines.  Last
week, U.S. Greenpeace activists "quarantined" a field in Central Iowa to block
harvesting of Monsanto's Roundup Ready soybeans.
 
<p>"Monsanto is conducting a giant experiment with nature and with our food," said
Greenpeace campaigner Paul Clarke. "The environmental consequences could be
devastating."
 
<p>Monsanto's genetically altered "Roundup Ready" soybeans are set to hit the
market for the first time later this year. The beans are engineered to tolerate

Monsanto's Roundup pesticide. Environmentalists and consumers are concerned
about the potential of genetically engineered soybeans to cause allergies in
humans and "genetic pollution" of natural plants.  While Roundup Ready accounts
for only 2% of this year's soybean crop, Monsanto's plan to mix them with
conventional soybeans threatens to contaminate the entire harvest. Soybean oil
and protein is
contained in some 60% of all processed foods. 

<BR><BR><HR><BR>
<p>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:

<p>Paul Clarke, by cellphone (312) 259-3568; or <p>Beth Fitzgerald (312)
563-6060 ext. 220 
<p>For video footage of recent protests and interviews with soybean farmers and
grain elevator operators contact : Hillary Briggs (202) 462-1177.
<p>For photos: Dwayne Freeman (202) 319-2583.
</blockquote>
<BR>
