<head>
  <title>"OLD GROWTH FOREST DESTRUCTION HAS A NAME - ENSO"
</title>
   
</head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">

<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%>
<tr>
<td><a href="russia.html"><img src="../icons/biofor.gif" border=2 height=80 width=60 align=left></a><a href="newsindx.html#luebeck"><img src="../icons/bionews.gif" border=0 height=60 width=60 align=right></a></td>
</tr>
</table>
<blockquote>
<p><b>"OLD GROWTH FOREST DESTRUCTION HAS A NAME - ENSO"<br>
GREENPEACE ACTION IN LUEBECK HARBOUR AGAINST FREIGHTER WITH ENSO PAPER
</b></p>

<P><B>LUEBECK, OCTOBER 17TH, 1996
</B>
  
<p>Since early this morning, Greenpeace activists have
been protesting in Luebeck harbour against the destruction of the last
remaining old growth forests by ENSO, a Finnish company. They are hindering the
unloading of the freighter "Oihonna" whose cargo is paper from Finland destined
for German markets. A large banner with the slogan "OLD GROWTH FOREST
DESTRUCTION HAS A NAME - ENSO" has been hung across the stern of the freighter
on ropes.  There are more than 3,000 tonnes of paper products from ENSO on
board . In August, Greenpeace protested against ENSO during two actions in
Russia and Finland after Greenpeace research revealed that ENSO had pulped wood
from Russian primary forests to paper. 
 
<p>"ENSO has reacted to our protests by stalling and lying to its customers and
the public. The time is long overdue for ENSO to stop destroying Russian and
Finnish old growth forests and it must declare this intention publicly", said
Thomas Henningsen, forest campaigner at Greenpeace Germany, who is accompanying
the action in an inflatable. The northern old growth forests in the area
between Finland and Russia (Karelia) deserve special protection because they
have not been used commercially until now and they contain untouched wildlife
reserves. The Karelian forests, along with similar areas in Poland and in the
Urals, belong to the last three remaining large old growth forests in Europe. 
 
<p>The Finnish giant ENSO has subsidiaries in 40 countries, making it one of the
largest paper and pulp producers in the world. ENSO has five production areas:
lumber and pulp, food and beverage cartoning, graphic paper and cartons,
printing paper (newspapers and magazines) and specialty papers.   ENSO is the
world's largest importer of Russian round wood, especially from Karelia.
Britain and Germany are by far the largest buyers of ENSO products. About 20
percent of ENSO products are sold in Germany alone.
 
<p>"As long as ENSO is logging old growth, no one will be sure if there isnt a
piece of destroyed old growth forest in their magazine, biscuit wrapper, copy
paper, telephone directory or paperback book," said Thomas Henningsen.
Greenpeace demands that customers of ENSO become aware of their responsibility
and persuade ENSO to stop logging primary and old growth forests. In addition,
ENSO should implement the concept of ecological forest use.
<br><br><hr><br>
<p>To editors:  If you have any questions, please call:
<p>Thomas Henningsen or Patricia Fromm in Luebeck, mobile ++49-172-3818-149
<p>Greenpeace press officer Svenja Koch in Luebeck, mobile ++49-172-2518504
or <p>the Greenpeace forest campaign in Hamburg, ++49-40-30618-321.
<p>Photos are available on request.

</blockquote>
</body></html>
