<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press release: October 16th, 1996, GREENPEACE CALLS ON UNILEVER TO REJECT GENETIC PRODUCTS ON WORLD FOOD
DAY</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="geneng.html"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/biogen.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html#geneng2"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<blockquote>

<p><b>GREENPEACE CALLS ON UNILEVER TO REJECT GENETIC PRODUCTS ON WORLD FOOD
DAY</b>
<p><b>AMSTERDAM, OCTOBER 16TH, 1996</b>

<p>Greenpeace today welcomed the news that
more supermarkets and food wholesalers-- including Switzerland's two
biggest food retailers --  have joined the protest against foods
containing genetically engineered soya from the United States.
Greenpeace is now calling on food giant Unilever to do the same.

<p>Supermarket and wholesale organisations in Austria, Switzerland,
Sweden and Norway* have this week confirmed that they will not be
stocking products containing genetically engineered soya unless the
genetically engineered soya is separated and labelled. They join a
number of others in Switzerland, Germany, Belgium and the Netherlands
who have refused the product or called for labelling.

<p>Today -- World Food Day -- Greenpeace offices in Europe are organizing
protests at Unilever's headquarters in the UK and Germany and at their
Swedish head office. Unilever is a major user of soya which is found
in about 60 per cent of all processed foods, from bread to chocolate.

<p>"What we are seeing is just the beginning of retailers and consumers
saying no," said Greenpeace campaigner Michelle Sheather. "Food
processors thought they could slip this in to our food without telling
us -- but this is a huge experiment with food and nature and people
don't want it."

<p> "Unilever has told Greenpeace that its policy is to ensure
 transparency and labelling but it has done neither. They and others
 like them such as Nestle and Danone have the power to act on behalf
 of their consumers and demand supplies of soya free from genetic
 engineering. We want to know why they are not doing this." 

<p>Only one to two per cent of this year's crop is genetically
engineered. The industry claims that it is impossible to separate the
bean but Greenpeace has already identified suppliers of normal soya.

<p>Greenpeace will also be carrying out an action in the USA where the
soya is currently being harvested. The soya is produced and marketed
by the American multinational Monsanto.*  

<p>In addition to health fears, Greenpeace is concerned about the effects
on the environment of the release of genetically engineered crops.
"This will be the first time genetically engineered ingredients have
appeared in wide range of everyday supermarket products," said Ms
Sheather, "and if the food multinationals have their way millions of
tons of engineered crops will be grown in the environment". 

<p>"In order to find lasting solutions to world food problems we need to
work with sustainable agricultural processes which do not pose threats
to the environment and human and animal health. Genetic engineering,
like the so called `green revolution' is just another short-term
dangerous attempt to provide a quick fix. It does not address the real

problems of world famine."

<p>In a related development, the European Union is still deliberating
about whether to approve Ciba Geigy's corn, which some countries have
objected to.The corn confers resistance to an antibiotic and there is
concern that this resistance could be transferred to bacteria, which
would then become resistant to treatment.

<BR><BR><HR><BR>
<p>NOTES TO EDITORS
<p>1. Monsanto has created a transgentic plant (Roundup Ready Soybean) by
adding genetic material from a virus and a bacterium to normal soya.
This provides no benefit to the consumer but simply makes the plant
resistant to the Roundup weedkiller, also produced by Monsanto.

<p>2. Meinl, one of Austria's leading supermarket chains, will anounce
today that it will not use genetcially engineered soya in its
products; Switzerland's two biggest food retailers, Migros and Coop
Schweiz, called publicly for the soyabeans to be marketed seperately
and labelled; DMF (Daglivarhandelns Enviromental and Packing Forum),
which includes almost all Norwegian food retailers and wholesalers has
anounced it will refuse to buy soya products unless the USA separates
the genetically engineered soya; the Federation of Swedish Food
Industry, which represents the country's main foodsuppliers, has said
it will not be using genetically engineered soya and has called for
its separation and labelling. 

<BR><BR><HR><BR>
<p>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:

<p>James Gillies, press officer, Greenpeace International, Amsterdam 31
20 524 9548
</blockquote>
<BR>
</body></html>
 


 

