<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press release: October 10th 1996, GREENPEACE QUARANTINES GENETICALLY ALTERED "X-FIELD"</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="geneng.html"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/biogen.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html#geneng2"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<blockquote>

<p><b>GREENPEACE QUARANTINES GENETICALLY ALTERED "X-FIELD"</b>

<p><b>ATLANTIC, IOWA, THURSDAY OCTOBER 10TH, 1996</b>

<p>Greenpeace today blocked harvesting and "quarantined" a field of
genetically engineered soybeans --  shortly to be on their way into
European food -- to protest against genetically engineered food and to
highlight the environmental dangers of such technology.

<p>Borrowing a theme from television's "The X-files" Greenpeace activists
used a bright pink non-toxic milk-based spray paint to spray an entire


soyabean field in Iowa in the USA and mark a huge "X" (30 metres by 15
metres) which could be seen from the air.

<p>"Strange things  are happening to America's crop fields -- they're
turning into America's X-fields, said Greenpeace Campaigner Beth
Fitzgerald from the site of the genetic invasion.

<p>Despite protests from European consumer groups, food manufacturers,
retailers and even farmers themselves, the genetically engineered soya
is now being harvested and mixed with normal soya ready for export to
Europe. Soya is used in about 60 per cent of processed foods, from
bread and cakes to chocolate and margarine.

<p>The "Roundup Ready Soybean" developed by the US firm Monsanto -- also
responsible for their production of Agent Orange used in Vietnam --
has been genetically engineered to be resistant to Monsanto's own
"Roundup" herbicide. The soybean contains genes from a virus and a
bacteria.

<p>In addition to the potential dangers of cross breeding with weeds and
subsequent disruption to the environment, Greenpeace believes the use
of genetically engineered crops in food could pose threats to human
and animal health.

<p>"European governments have the right under EU law to refuse imports of
the soybean if they believe they could constitute a risk to human
health or the environment," said Louise Gale of Greenpeace's European
Unit. "We think they should be using that right on both counts."

<p>In a separate action, activists from Greenpeace Germany dressed as
laboratory rabbits today also protested outside the headquarters of

the food giant Unilever, calling on them to use their consumer power
to demand non-genetically engineered soya.

<BR><BR><HR><BR>
<p>NOTE TO BROADCASTERS AND PICTURE EDITORS
<p>. For background video material call Reuters, WTN  and APTV in London

<p>. For US action footage call the above. The action footage will also
be available on satellite: Galaxy 9 (c-band), Transponder 21
(line:4120, vertical) 17.35 - 18.05 GMT (European continental time + 1
hour)  

<p>. For German action footage call Reuters (Bonn, London)


<p>. For photos of the US action call Reuters (London and Washington)

<p>. For photos of the German action call DPA


<BR><BR><HR><BR>
<p>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:

<p>James Gillies, press officer, Greenpeace International, Amsterdam 31
20 524 9548

<p>Terri Johnson, press officer, Greenpeace USA, Chicago 1 312 218 7409 

</blockquote>
<BR>
</body></html>
 


 

