<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press release: 1st October 1996- NEW FIGURES EXPOSE STAGGERING WASTE IN B.C. TRAWL FISHERY 
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="../fish/index.html"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=80 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/oce01t.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html#canada3"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<blockquote>

<P><B>NEW FIGURES EXPOSE STAGGERING WASTE IN B.C. TRAWL FISHERY</B>
<p>MV Greenpeace Investigates Massive Dumping of Fish in Hecate
Strait
<P><B>Queen Charlotte Sound, 1st October 1996</B>
 
<p>New figures
obtained from the Department of Fisheries show that with the
season still underway,  British Columbia's trawl fishery has
already dumped over 12 million pounds of dead and dying fish
overboard.
 
<p>The numbers of discarded fish, gathered for the first time
from observers aboard the trawling fleet, include: 
<ul>
<li>4,143,721 pounds of turbot (arrowtooth flounder) 
<li>2,390,100 pounds of dogfish 
<li>and almost a million pounds of high-value halibut.
</ul>
 
<p>The total to date of 12,981,559 pounds of fish represents 100
separate species including sole, perch, pacific cod, rockfish,
salmon, herring, sturgeon and even steelhead trout.
 
<p>Discarded fish or "by-catch" include any that are the wrong
sex, wrong size, wrong species or for which there is no
commercial market. This is the first year the Fisheries
Department has placed observers on trawlers to monitor the
destruction.
 
<p>"This is appalling waste, especially at time when so many fish
species are in trouble,"  said Greenpeace Fisheries Campaigner
Catherine Stewart  aboard the MV Greenpeace, which is
currently investigating trawlers' activities as they drag
massive nets along the seabed.  "Greenpeace is here to
confront this environmental destruction head on."
 
<p>Many of the species being caught by the draggers could be
fished more selectively, using traps, pots or hooks and lines.
 
<p>Also included in the dumped trawl waste are 41 non-fish
species including harbour seals, California sea lions, rare
Steller sea lions, 68,710 pounds of starfish, 93,805 pounds of
crab and 28,250 pounds of assorted sponges, corals, anemones,
urchins, squid, octopus and prawns.
 
<p>The draggers, owned by B.C.Packers, Ocean Fisheries and
others, cause significant damage to the ocean floor, tearing
up coral and bottom life. Huge steel doors that hold the net

open and heavy chains tear into the ocean bed, dredging up the
bottom and crushing bottom life. Greenpeace is demanding a
phase-out of bottom dragging and a conversion to more
sustainable, selective fishing methods.  

<BR><BR><HR><BR> 
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:

<p>Catherine Stewart, on-board the
MV Greenpeace:  <br>Satellite phone: 011-872-130-0310 or  <p> Steve
Shallhorn in Vancouver:  1-604-253-7701 or <p>Mary MacNutt in
Toronto:  1-416-597-8408. <p> Copies of the DFO  by-catch figures
are also available.</blockquote>

</body></html>





