<html>
<head>
   <title>  GOVERNMENT ADVISORS CALL FOR INDUSTRIAL FISHING BAN ON WEE BANKIE
</title>
   
</head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">

<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%>
<tr>
<td><a href="nsea.html"><img src="../icons/nsea11.gif" border=0 height=80 width=60 align=left></a><a href="newsindx.html"><img src="../icons/bionews.gif" border=0 height=60 width=60 align=right></a></td>
</tr>
</table>
<blockquote>
<p><b>  GOVERNMENT ADVISORS CALL FOR INDUSTRIAL FISHING BAN ON WEE BANKIE
</b></p>

<p>LONDON, FRIDAY, SEPTEMBER 20th  1996
     
           
     <P>The Government's advisors, the Joint Nature Conservation Council 
     (JNCC), has recommended that industrial fishing for sandeels on the 
     Wee Bankie and surrounding areas off the Scottish East Coast be 
     banned. 
     
     <P>In a letter to the Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food (MAFF) 
     the JNCC said, "We are concerned about the effects of industrial 
     fishing on important wildlife concentrations reliant on sandeels.  We 
     therefore suggest that sandeel fisheries be restricted in the area 
     which our work indicates that there is likely to be the largest 
     overlap in occurrence of fisheries and seabird/cetacean usage - the 
     Wee Bankie, Marr Bank and Scalp Bank".
     
    <P> The JNCC recommendation goes on to suggest a possible wording which 
     prohibits fishing in a specified geographical area.
     
    <P> If the UK Government heeds this advice it will call on the European 
     Commission (EC) to adopt this policy and make it legally binding.  The 
     next fisheries meeting of the EC at which this could occur is in 
     October.
     
     <P>Although only made publicly available this week, the recommendation 
     was sent to MAFF on August 19th.  As yet MAFF has not indicated its 
     intentions.
     
     <P>Greenpeace scientific advisor Dr Malcolm MacGarvin said, "It is vital 
     that the Government heeds its own advisors and protect such sensitive 
     areas as the Wee Bankie. It can no longer ignore the calls for 
     political action."
     
     <P>The effects of unregulated industrial fishing in the Wee Bankie area 
     were highlighted earlier this year when Greenpeace began a campaign of 
     action against the industrial fishing fleet.
     
     <P>At a recent meeting of fisheries experts in Norway, a Danish fisheries 
     scientist, Dr Henrik Gislason, accepted there was a case for 
     protecting sandeel stocks on a precautionary basis. Malcolm MacGarvin 
     said, "the scientist acknowledged that there is a case for general 
     limitations on North Sea sandeel fisheries and for banning industrial 
     fishing in areas such as the Wee Bankie. One more reason why the 
     Government should now act."
     ends
  
     <P>Notes to Editors:<br>
     1) Copies of the letter from JNCC available on request.<br>
     2) The geographical area referred to is: <br>
     latitude 55' 45" N, longitude 01' 20" W<br>
     latitude 57' 00" N, longitude 01' 20" W<br>


   
   <BR><BR>
<hr>
<br>

<p><b>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT: </b></p>

<p><b>Greenpeace Press Office  0171-865 8256/7 or 0171-359 4837<br><br>
<hr>
<br>
<br></p>
</blockquote>
</body>
</html>



