<HEAD>
<TITLE>GREENPEACE DEMANDS BAN IN MIDST OF TRAWLER FLEET
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="../fish/index.html#usa2"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=80 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/oce01t.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html#usa3"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<blockquote>

<P><B>GREENPEACE DEMANDS BAN IN MIDST OF TRAWLER FLEET


<P>BERING SEA,  SEPTEMBER 10TH, 1996  </B>

 <p>Over a dozen Greenpeace
activists in four inflatable boats have brought the call for a
ban on factory trawlers into the midst of the Bering Sea
factory trawler fleet.
 
<p>Last month Greenpeace launched a campaign to ban factory
trawlers from U.S. fisheries. Yesterday, 15 activists from the
MV Greenpeace began an on-going direct action among the
factory trawlers by driving small, inflatable boats in front
of the moving factory trawler Ocean Rover (owned by American
Seafoods).
 
<p>"We're here to end the pillaging of our oceans by factory
trawlers,"  said Greenpeace's Dave Batker aboard the MV
Greenpeace.  "These trawlers pass through an ocean ecosystem
and tear out the heart of the food web." Greenpeace's action
begins days before the U.S. Senate is due to debate on the
Magnuson fishery Conservation and Management Act, the nation's
primary fisheries law North Pacific marine mammals and birds,
which depend on the fish caught by factory trawlers, are
declining drastically.  The Steller sea lion is being
considered for endangered species status in the areas where
factory trawlers have fished most heavily ends
 

 <BR><BR><HR><BR> 
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:


<B>
<p>Bering Sea - Dave Batker, MV Greenpeace - 011 (872) 130 0310
($10 per minute) 
<p>Seattle - Mark Floegel, Greenpeace media,
(206) 632-4326, ext 111 
<p>Washington, DC - Deborah Rephan,
Greenpeace media (202) 319-2492 
<p>Greenpeace International -
James Gillies, Press Office, Amsterdam, 00 31 20 524 9548 

</B>
 
</B><BR>
<BR><HR><BR><BR>


</blockquote>

