<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press release: 29th August 1996 - GREENPEACE CONFRONTS DESTRUCTIVE FISHING IN BERING SEA </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="../fish/index.html#usa"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=80 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/oce01t.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html#usa2"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<blockquote>

<P><B>GREENPEACE CONFRONTS DESTRUCTIVE FISHING IN BERING SEA




<P>WHO: Greenpeace Activists aboard the M/V Greenpeace
 
<P>WHEN: September 1-15, 1995 
 
<P>WHERE: The Bering Sea, off Alaska



<P>SEATTLE,  THURSDAY, AUGUST 29TH, 1996  </B>
<P>Greenpeace fisheries activists 
will confront the "factory trawler" fleet that is stripping the
Bering Sea of fish.
 
<P>The activists, aboard the MV Greenpeace, will be amid the factory
trawler fleet for the late summer fishing season in the Bering Sea
(September 1-15).
 
<P>While the season is underway, the U.S. Senate will consider the
reauthorization of the Magnuson Fishery Conservation and
Management Act, the nation's primary fishing law.  The bill, which
is seen as the most important piece of environmental legislation
considered by the 104th Congress, is scheduled for Senate debate
on September 4.
 
<P>Greenpeace has launched a campaign calling for the phase-out of
U.S. factory trawlers by 2001.
 
<P>Natural sound, beta b-roll is available.  Call Greg Howard at
Fenton Communications (202-745-0707).
 
CONTACTS:
 Dave Batker, aboard the MV Greenpeace - 011-872-130-0310
Mark Floegel, Greenpeace media, Seattle - 206-632-4326, ext. 111
Niaz Dorry, Fisheries campaign, Washington, DC - 202-319-2523


