<html>
<head>
   <title>GREENPEACE BLOCKS LOGGING OF RUSSIAN OLD GROWTH FOREST</title>
   
</head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">

<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%>
<tr>
<td><a href="russia.html"><img src="../icons/biofor.gif" border=2 height=80 width=60 align=left></a><a href="newsindx.html#karelia1"><img src="../icons/bionews.gif" border=0 height=60 width=60 align=right></a></td>
</tr>
</table>

<p><b>GREENPEACE BLOCKS LOGGING OF RUSSIAN OLD GROWTH FOREST 
</b></p>

<P><B>The Finnish giant paper company Enso breaks its promise and
continues to use timber from old growth forests </B> 



<P>
<B>Karelia. Tuesday August 20th, 1996 -</B>
 
<P>Today, 20 Greenpeace activists
from Russia, Finland, Sweden, Denmark, Austria and Germany
took direct action in Karelian forests near Kostamus,
Russia, to stop the ongoing destruction in one of the last
remaining European old growth forests.   
 
<P>"Enso has broken their promise not to use timber from old
growth forests. This is chop-and-run style logging, and they
are taking all the profits with them across the border to
Finland," said Sergey Tsyplenkov of Greenpeace Russia. 
 
<P>The activists chained themselves to the harvesters blocking
further logging and displayed banners in English and Russian
reading "Stop Enso Destroying Russian Forests". Enso Group
is a Finland-based multinatinal corporation, and is one of
the world's largest paper producers.  
  
<P>"We have come to defend the remaining old growth forests of
Karelia. Enso is contributing to the destruction of one of
the last remaining old growth areas in Europe," said
Tsyplenkov.
  
<P>Greenpeace has repeatedly demanded an immediate halt to
logging in old growth forests in Europe, an end to
clearcutting and the adoption of ecologically responsible
forest use.
   
<P>Many residents of Karelia and neighbouring areas are bitter
about the loss of the forests and the lack of substantial
compensation. Most of the profit from logging is being made
 
by value-added production in Finland and Western Europe.
 
<P>Old growth forests and their wildlife have disappeared
throughout most of Europe. In Sweden and Finland, for
example, only less than 5 per cent of the old growth forest
remains. Despite its extreme importance for conserving
biodiversity in Northern Europe, the Green Belt, as this
strip of untouched forests along the Russian-Finnish border
is known, lacks a comprehensive conservation plan. The
Karelian forest is a vital habitat for brown bear, wolf,
Karelian deer and beaver. 
 
 
<br> <br> <hr>      
<P><B>FOR MORE INFORMATION CONTACT::
<P>Sergey Tsyplenkov in Karelia +358-(9)49-292 484
<P>Greenpeace Finland - Matti Ikonen + 358-(9)0-6150 1677,
+358-(9)49-25 77 55
<P>For photos and video footage available plase call Greenpeace
in Helsinki, Ana Toni  +358-(9)0-6150 1688    

NOTES:
 
<P>p1. In a letter to BBC Enterprises Ltd in UK, 24th
January 1996, Enso said: " Enso does not buy wood from the
oldgrowth forests, natural conservation areas or areas
planned to be natural conservation areas." 
 
 <UL>
<LI>In European Russia there are two significant belts
of oldgrowth: the Komi Republic forests along the Ural
Mountains, which have been recognised internationally, and
the Green Belt along the Finnish-Russian border. According
to Russian environmentalists, only 10-15% of Karelia's
oldgrowth forests still stand. 

 
 
<LI>p3. Half of all Russian raw timber exports go to
Finland. Enso Group is the largest importer of Russian raw
timber. In 1995 Finnish importers purchased 8.9 million
cubic metres of raw timber, Enso responsible for almost half
of this, mostly from the Northwest of Russia. 
</UL>

</B> 

<br>
<br>
<hr>
<br>
<br></p>

</body>
</html>


