<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press release: 15th August 1996 - BAN FACTORY TRAWLERS IN THE U.S.</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="../fish/index.html#usa"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=80 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/oce01t.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<blockquote>

<P><B>GREENPEACE LAUNCHES CAMPAIGN TO BAN FACTORY TRAWLERS
<p>Report Details Destruction to Fisheries, Marine Environments  
<P>SEATTLE, THURSDAY, AUGUST 15TH, 1996</B>



<p>With commercial fisheries around the U.S. in
crisis, Greenpeace today launched a campaign to ban the U.S. fleet of "factory
trawlers" -- the massive, industrial-scale fishing vessels capable of catching
500,000 pounds of fish per tow -- that are devastating marine environments
around the world.  Greenpeace is releasing a report,  Sinking Fast,  Thursday
in Seattle, Washington, detailing the environmental damage caused by factory
trawlers. The new campaign follows Greenpeace's successful effort to ban drift
net fishing on the high seas.  

<p><B>(NOTE: The official launch, and report release, are taking place Thursday at
11 a.m. Pacific Daylight Time, at a news conference at Myrtle Edwards Park in
Seattle.)</B>

<p>Modern factory trawlers have transformed fishing into an ocean-going
strip-mining industry.  Factory trawlers use nets with openings two miles in
circumference, into which a dozen 747 jumbo jets could easily fit.  The
trawlers' huge nets catch an enormous amount of incidental species (bycatch). 
In 1994, factory trawlers threw overboard, dead, more than half a billion
pounds of fish because they were the wrong sex, size or species.  The U.S.
industry is dominated by multinational corporations, including Arkansas-based
Tyson Foods, which owns 11 factory trawlers.
 
<p>"This technology was used to hunt the great whales to near-extinction," said
Greenpeace Executive Director Barbara Dudley.  "No longer able to hunt whales,
this technology was modified to catch whale-sized nets of fish."
 
<p>Greenpeace called on the U.S. Department of Commerce to phase out the U.S.
factory trawler fleet by 2001.  The group also demanded that U.S. fisheries be
closed to all foreign trawlers.
 
<p>"This environmental tragedy isn't being perpetrated by a developing nation
desperate for cash," said Dudley.  "This is an American fleet, backed by
Norwegian and Japanese investors. 
Greenpeace is committed to ending this wasteful depletion of our oceans."
 
<p>Concerned citizens can send a free fax in support of the ban to the CEO's of
Tyson Foods and American Seafoods (the largest owners of these trawlers) by
going to www.interactivism.com on the Internet. 
                                

<BR><BR><HR><BR> 
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:


<B>
<p>Mark Floegel, Greenpeace USA: ++ 206-632-4326, ext 111
          <p>Niaz Dorry, Greenpeace USA: ++ 617-266-2505
               <p>Alfred Mills, Pyramid Communications: ++ 206-625-6939
</B>
 
</B><BR>
<BR><HR><BR><BR>


</blockquote>

</body></html>
 



