<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press release: 12th August 1996 - SPANISH FISHERMEN MEET GREENPEACE AT SEA
TO TAKE  JOINT ACTIONS AGAINST DRIFTNET FISHING
 </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="../fish/index.html#fish"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=80 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/oce01t.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html#drift02"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<blockquote>

<P><B>SPANISH FISHERMEN MEET GREENPEACE AT SEA
TO TAKE  JOINT ACTIONS AGAINST DRIFTNET FISHING
</B>
<P><B>Balearic Sea, Western Mediterranean - 12th August 1996</B>
 
<P>
Today, Spanish Mediterranean longliners have had a meeting onboard the MV Arctic
 Sunrise with Greenpeace members.  
<P>The aim was to joint efforts against illegal

driftnet fishing. During this meeting, it was agreed to take actions to eject th
e Italian driftnetters from the Balearic sea as well as to ask the Spanish gover
nment to push Italy to implement a plan to eliminate driftnet fishing.
 
<P>Both fishermen and environmentalists agree on their opposition to this type of no

n selective fishing. Apart from the problem of its illegal use, high seas driftn
etting makes a great impact over the commercial and not commercial  marine speci
es.
 
 
<P>Spanish longliners participants:
MAITE REINAU (Almeria), ROSELLO BLANQUET (Alicante), HERMANOS RUIZ-SAEZ
(Almeria), FRANCISCO Y MARGARITA (Murcia), ZUBI EDER (Almeria), KALIMA
(Murcia), MORENO TORRES (Almeria), GONZALEZ RUIZ (Almeria), JOAQUINA Y ANTONIO
(Almeria), GARCIA PEREZ (Almeria), PLAYA AZUL (Almeria), ESPANOLETO (Almeria) ,
DORADA (Almeria), LA LLANA (Almeria), JAFFET (Murcia) GARCIA RODRIGUEZ
(Almeria) NICOLAS E ISABEL (Almeria).
 
<P><B>Note for the editor</B>: 

<P>The maximum net lenth per vessel established by the European community and the
Italian government is two and a half kilometres, nevertheless the Italian
fishermen use nets of 12, 15 or even 20 kilometres of length. Less than  20% of
the fish caught is swordfish (the target species) and the rest of the catch is
normally discarded. Sperm whales and dolphin populations in the Mediterranean
are seriously threatened if this type of net is not eliminated.

<BR><BR><HR><BR> 
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:

<P>Alessandro Gianni on 00 31 653 9117 73

<P> Helene Bours on 00 3241 68 68 51 

<P>James Gillies on 00 31 6 5323


<BR><BR><HR><BR>

<B>
<P>NEW ADDRESS:
<P>Keizersgracht 176
<P>1016 DW AMSTERDAM
<P>THE NETHERLANDS
<P>phone: 31 (20) 523 6222/ 524 9548 (direct line)
<P>fax: 31 (20) 523 6200
</B>
</blockquote>

