<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press release: 7th August 1996 - Canadian Salmon Campaign</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="../fish/index.html#fish"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=80 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/oce01t.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<blockquote>

<P><B>   GREENPEACE CONFRONTS IRRESPONSIBLE FRASER RIVER  SALMON FISHERY
</B>
  
<P>VANCOUVER, WEDNESDAY, AUGUST 7TH, 1996


<P><B> Activists stop gillnets from being deployed--Condemn Federal
management 
</B>
 
                                     
<P>Today Greenpeace activists
interfered with gillnets deployed in the controversial Fraser
River commercial sockeye fishery.  Volunteers in zodiacs,
launched from the Greenpeace vessel Moby Dick, pulled gillnets
from the water and
bundled them with twine to prevent sockeye catches. The action
was designed to highlight the irresponsible decision of the
federal government to go ahead with a one day gillnet opening
despite the extremely small size of this year's Fraser River run.
 
<P>"This is not the "risk averse" management we were promised - this
is a complete failure of the federal government's  mandate to
conserve fish for the future," said Catherine Stewart, Greenpeace
Fisheries Campaigner.  "Canadians should be asking who has
pressured the federal government to make this decision.
Greenpeace believes the Department of Fisheries has caved in to
the lobby efforts of B.C.Packers and the Canadian Fishing
Company. Industry's processing needs are taking precedence over
conservation."
 
<P>Despite unreliable estimates of an increase in the run size to
2.7 million sockeye, the 1996 run is still the smallest in almost
50 years. DFO has set targets of 2.5 to 5 million spawners in
recent years, this year's low target of 1.1 million spawners was
based only on the low returns. Greenpeace roundly denounced the
claim that a total run of 2.7 million is enough to allow for a
commercial fishery.
 
<P>In May, 1996, Greenpeace issued a comprehensive "Salmon Recovery
Plan" which includes a demand for a moratorium on commercial
fishing of all vulnerable salmon stocks including the Fraser
River sockeye runs.
 
<P>Canada has committed themselves the Precautionary Principle
regarding fisheries management at the United Nations conference
on Highly Migratory and straddling stocks, and DFO has
additionally committed to a risk averse management strategy. 
Allowing a commercial fishery on a run that is this low when
returns have been so difficult to accurately predict is clearly a
violation of these commitments and poses a serious threat to the
stocks.
 
<P>Greenpeace demands the immediate closure of commercial fisheries
for Fraser sockeye in 1996 with no further openings allowed.
 

<BR><BR><HR><BR> 
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION AND PRESS BACKGROUNDER CONTACT:


<B><P>Catherine Stewart at 604- 220-7701 (on board the
Moby Dick):

<p>Steve Shallhorn at 604-329-2991 (on board the
Moby Dick):

<p>Tamara Stark at Greenpeace Vancouver: 604-253-7701
<p>Mary MacNutt at Greenpeace Toronto: 416-597-8408


<P><B>Copies of the report "Fishy Business" can also be obtained by
contacting the Greenpeace office.</B>
 
</B><BR><HR><BR><BR>


</blockquote>

</body></html>
 

