<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press release: 27th July 1996 - ITALIAN PLAN TO ELMINATE DRIFNETS</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="../fish/index.html#fish"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=80 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/oce01t.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html#drift01"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<blockquote>

<P><B> ITALIAN PLAN TO ELMINATE DRIFNETS NOT GOOD ENOUGH SAYS GREENPEACE</B>
<P><B>Amsterdam - 27th July 1996</B>

<P>Greenpeace today criticised a multi-million dollar plan to eliminate

Italian driftnets by 1999 as lacking  in the detail needed to end 
illegal driftnetting practices  in the Mediterranean.

<P>An estimated $283 million of public money -- half of it from the
European Union and half from the Italian Government -- is believed to
have been allocated to the programme.

<P>"Of course we strongly support  the objective of ending overfishing
and the accidental catching in driftnets of whales and dolphins and
other marine species, " said Greenpeace campaigner Alessandro Gianni,
"but this is a huge amount of public money and we would have expected
a much more detailed and thorough plan from the Italian Government.

<P>"The plan contains no indication of how the nets will be withdrawn
from use or how this will be verified. Unless this is ensured the nets
will continue to be used  and the whole programme could turn out to be
a huge waste of public money. Even the European Commission has
insisted that compensation should be linked to the confiscation and

destruction of the nets."

<P>In addition, the  plan is voluntary and while it states that those who
continue to use driftnets will be subject to stricter controls, the
Italian Government has a poor record in this area. Earlier this year
the EU confirmed that illegal driftnetting by italian fleets was
widespread.

<P>"A control system must be put in place to ensure that the money
allocated to compensate fishermen is effectively used to eliminate
driftnets once and for all," added Greenpeace.

<P>The Greenpeace boat Arctic Sunrise has been patrolling the sea around
Sicily this week and identified 10 illegal driftnets in a few days. 
In the last four fishing seasons alone 32 sperm whales  were
discovered dead as a result of driftnet fishing off the Balearic
Islands. The true total will be much higher.

<P>The Italian fleet is thought to be responsible for the largest number
of illegal driftnets in the world. Their target is primarily swordfish
but other animals are caught up in the nets and die. 


<BR><BR><HR><BR> 
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:

<P>Alessandro Gianni on 00 31 653 9117 73

<P> Helene Bours on 00 3241 68 68 51 

<P>James Gillies on 00 31 6 5323


<BR><BR><HR><BR>

<B>
<P>NEW ADDRESS:
<P>Keizersgracht 176
<P>1016 DW AMSTERDAM
<P>THE NETHERLANDS
<P>phone: 31 (20) 523 6222/ 524 9548 (direct line)
<P>fax: 31 (20) 523 6200
</B>
</blockquote>

