<head>
   <title>ENVIRONMENTAL GROUPS CALL FOR GOVERNMENT ACTION ON INDUSTRIAL FISHING
</title>
   
</head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">

<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%>
<tr>
<td><a href="nsea.html"><img src="../icons/nsea11.gif" border=0 height=80 width=60 align=left></a><a href="newsindx.html"><img src="../icons/bionews.gif" border=0 height=60 width=60 align=right></a></td>
</tr>
</table>
<blockquote>
<p><b>ENVIRONMENTAL GROUPS CALL FOR GOVERNMENT ACTION ON INDUSTRIAL FISHING</b></p>

<p>COPENHAGEN, THURSDAY, JULY 25th 1996 </p>


 
<p>Environmental, fishing groups and politicians
today called for urgent action from 
governments to address industrial fishing in the North Sea as the Greenpeace
ship MV Sirius concluded the
first stage of its campaign against overfishing. 

 
<p>A total 15 fishing associations,  16 environmental groups,  European
politicans, fish buying and selling
companies and marine scientists have signed petitions calling on Dutch, German
and British governments
to  ensure urgent measures are taken to control industrial fishing in sensitive
marine areas of the North Sea.
 
<p>The MV Sirius today arrived in Copenhagen from the Wee Bankie area off the
Scottish coast near Edinburgh. 
 
<p>For the past three months the MV Sirius  has been conducting direct action to
stop industrial fishing 
by Danish, Scottish, Norwegian and English boats in an area known as the Wee
Bankie off the Scottish 
North Sea coast.
 
<p>Greenpeace is calling on European Environment Ministers, at a special meeting

of the North Sea Ministers
conference in March next year to agree an emergency recovery plan for the
overfished North Sea. This should
include a programme to increase all threatened fish stocks such as cod, herring
and plaice to safe levels, a ban
on discarding, massive reductions to by-catch of other species and major cuts
to fishing capacity. 
 
<p>"European environment ministers must look beyond national self-interest and
take urgent action to 
stop the current plundering of  North Sea fish stocks which cannot withstand
current fishing levels
and practises," said a Greenpeace spokesperson 
 
<br><br>
<hr>
<br>

<p><b>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT: </b></p>

<p><b>DESLEY MATHER ON THE MV SIRIUS  00-316 523 80633 OR SAT PHONE 00-874 130 0144


<p>OR YOUR FOR YOUR NATIONAL GREENPEACE OFFICE CONTACT DETAILS SEE THE NAVIGATOR ON THE <a href="/greenpeace.html">HOME</A> PAGE.<br><br><hr>
<br>
<br></p>
</blockquote>
