<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press release: 22ndJuly1996 - UNREGULATED TESTS OF GENE-TECH PLANTS </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="geneng.html"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/biogen.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html#geneng1"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<blockquote>

<P><B>UNREGULATED TESTS OF GENE-TECH PLANTS THREATEN 
ENVIRONMENT AND ECONOMY OF DEVELOPING COUNTRIES
</B>
  
<P><b>AARHUS, DENMARK, MONDAY JUNE 22ND, 1996</b>
 

<P>Unregulated field-testing of genetically

manipulated plants threaten 
to cause genetic pollution and damage to the environment and economy of
developing countries,
 Greenpeace concludes in a case-study of Guatemala released on Monday at the
start of global 
negotiations on a Biosafety Protocol in Aarhus (Denmark).
 
<P>Investigations by Greenpeace Central American office in Guatemala found that
one of the companies,
the US-based Asgrow, which had imported and tested genetically 
engineered tomato, squash and cantaloupe, had taken no measures to prevent
accidental releases 
of genetical material from the genetically engineered products. 
<P>Several varieties of tomato and squash in particular can be found in Guatemala,
making genetic 

pollution an acute risk. In fact, for these two species, Guatemala represents a
center of biological 
diversity, and as such a unique gene-pool for future cultivation. This could
well be destroyed by 
such irresponsible activities. 
 
<P>Guatemala has no legislation to specifically regulate the flow of genetically
engineered organisms 
and the country has been used as a testing field. Even the Ministry of
Agriculture, Guatemala's 
competent authority for the import of seeds, was not informed about those
tests. 
Not even a prior notification was received by these authorities, despite the
threat of 
ecological and economic damage. In fact, the introduction of improved
commercial species could 
totally displace other varieties and accelerate the disappearance of native
cultivars.
 
<P>Since 1994, Greenpeace has documented several illegal and unregulated
field-tests of gene-tech plants
 in developing countries."There is clearly a need for a stringent biosafety

protocol, which regulates 
not only the transboundary movement of genetic material, but also provides
clear rules of liability 
which makes foreign companies responsible for the damage they may cause", says
Jester Grolin, 
Greenpeace Political adviser on genetic engineering.
 
<P>Until such a stringent protocol is in place, Greenpeace urges governments at
the global biosafety
 negotiations in Aarhus to introduce an unconditional moratorium on all
field-testing and releases
 of genetically manipulated organisms. 
 
<BR><BR><HR><BR>
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:

<P>- Jester GROLIN, t. +45 40 55 32 03
<P>- Isabelle MEISTER, Greenpeace Switzerland, t. +41 1 295 94 21
<P>- Luisa COLASIMONE, Greenpeace International t. +31 20 52 49 546
 


<BR>
<BR><HR><BR>


<B>
<P>Background information:
<P>Genetic engineering allows the transfer of genes between totally unrelated
species. <P>Genes have
 been transferred from humans to fish, from bacteria to plants and from animals
to vegetables. 
<P>In this manner, food companies believe genetic engineering can improve the
quality of certain 
foodstuffs. However, independent studies are still underway to verify  that
this type of products
 do not present toxic effects or allergic reactions in humans. In addition,
genetically manipulated 
plants can transfer their "alien" gene to wild related plant species threby
causing genetic pollution
 of natural species. 
<P>Greenpeace believes that a precautionary approach should
be applied in general, 
otherwise the consumers' health would be at risk for the commercial interests
of these companies.

<P>The Biosafety Protocol is being negotiated as part of the Biodiversity
Convention 
agreed at the Earth Summit in Rio.
</B>

</blockquote>
<BR>
</body></html>
 


 

