<head>
   <title>DANISH FISHERMEN USE RIFLES TO THREATEN GREENPEACE
</title>
   
</head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">

<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%>
<tr>
<td><a href="nsea.html"><img src="../icons/nsea11.gif" border=2 height=80 width=60 align=left></a><a href="newsindx.html"><img src="../icons/bionews.gif" border=0 height=60 width=60 align=right></a></td>
</tr>
</table>

<p><b>DANISH FISHERMEN USE RIFLES  TO THREATEN GREENPEACE </b></p>

<p>AMSTERDAM, MONDAY, JULY 8th 1996 </p>

<P>This morning, Greenpeace attempted to stop 
industrial fishing vessels from operating after they returned today to fish
the Wee Bankie area 20 km off the Scottish North Sea coast near Edinburgh.


<P>After Greenpeace tried to stop one of the vessels,  one chased back to throw
seal-bomb at Greenpeace inflatables. Since 3.00 pm Greenpeace had tried to
stop a second vessel, the Benne Dorthe, which was attempting to set nets. As
a reaction, fishermen on the vessel aimed rifles at Greenpeace activists. The
confrontation continues.  

<P>The industrial fishing fleet had left the sensitive marine area last week
after continuing confrontations with the Greenpeace vessel,  MV Sirius.
However, this morning 17 industrial fishing vessels, including Scottish and
Danish boasts, returned to fish the area,  which is a feeding ground for
commercial fish stocks, sea birds, dolphins and other marine life.  

<P>"Greenpeace will continue to stop industrial fishing boats from operating in
these sensitive marine areas but it's time the European governments stopped
talking and took some action to prevent this ecological disaster from
continuing in the North Sea," said Greenpeace campaigner Desley Mather.  

<P>The exclusion of industrial fisheries from sensitive areas is one part of an
emergency recovery plan needed for the overfished North Sea.  For industrial
fisheries, Greenpeace also believes any catch limits outside sensitive areas
should be set using the precautionary approach and bycatch of other species
should be cut drastically.   

<P>Industrial fishing uses ultra-fine nets to catch sandeels and other small fish
near the bottom of the marine food web. These fish are food for "table" fish
, sea birds and other marine wildlife.
<BR>
<p><b>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT: </b>

<p><b>DESLEY MATHER ON THE MV SIRIUS 00-44-402605187 </b>

<b>or </b>

<b>sat phone ($US10 per minute) 00 874 130 0144 </b>

<P><b>OR </b>

<p><b>JON WALTER AT GREENPEACE INTERNATIONAL ON +31 20-524-9547 </b>
