<head>
   <title>INDUSTRIAL FISHING VESSELS RETURN TO THE  SCOTTISH COAST 
</title>
   
</head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">

<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%>
<tr>
<td><a href="nsea.html"><img src="../icons/nsea11.gif" border=2 height=80 width=60 align=left></a><a href="newsindx.html"><img src="../icons/bionews.gif" border=0 height=60 width=60 align=right></a></td>
</tr>
</table>

<p><b>INDUSTRIAL FISHING VESSELS RETURN TO THE SCOTTISH COAST </b></p>

<p>AMSTERDAM, MONDAY, JULY 8th 1996 </p>

<p>Greenpeace attempted to stop industrial fishing vessels from operating
after they returned today to fish the Wee Bankie area 20 km off the Scottish
North Sea coast near Edinburgh. </p>

<p>The industrial fishing fleet had left the sensitive marine area last
week after continuing confrontations with the Greenpeace vessel, MV Sirius.
However this morning 17 industrial fishing vessels, including Scottish
and Danish boasts, returned to fish the area, which is a feeding ground
for commercial fish stocks, sea birds, dolphins and other marine life.
</p>

<p>Greenpeace launched two inflatable boats from the Sirius with seven
people aboard in an attempt to stop the Danish vessel Heidi Marlene from
fishing. The protesters managed to tie a knot in the vessel's fishing net
as it was being hauled in, in an attempt to delay the Danish vessel from
recasting its nets. </p>

<p>&quot;Greenpeace will continue to stop industrial fishing boats from
operating in these sensitive marine areas but it's time the European governments
stopped talking and took some action to prevent this ecological disaster
from continuing in the North Sea,&quot; said Greenpeace campaigner Desley
Mather. </p>

<p>The exclusion of industrial fisheries from sensitive areas is one part
of an emergency recovery plan needed for the overfished North Sea. For
industrial fisheries, Greenpeace also believes any catch limits outside
sensitive areas should be set using the precautionary approach and bycatch
of other species should be cut drastically. </p>

<p>Industrial fishing uses ultra-fine nets to catch sandeels and other
small fish near the bottom of the marine food web. These fish are food
for &quot;table&quot; fish (such as cod, haddock and whiting), sea birds
and other marine wildlife. </p>

<p><b>NB: PHOTOGRAPHS SHOULD BE AVAILABLE FROM REUTERS, AP AND PA. </b></p>

<p><b>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT: </b></p>

<p><b>DESLEY MATHER ON THE MV SIRIUS 00-44-402605187 </b></p>

<p><b>or </b></p>

<p><b>sat phone ($US10 per minute) 00 874 130 0144 </b></p>

<p><b>OR </b></p>

<p><b>JON WALTER AT GREENPEACE INTERNATIONAL ON 3120-524-9547 </b>
<br>
<br>
<hr>
<br>
<br></p>

