<HEAD>
<TITLE>BRITAIN'S MAJOR GREEN GROUPS JOINED BY FISHERMEN</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="nsea.html"><img align=left WIDTH=60 HEIGHT= 80 src="../icons/nsea11.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<P><B>BRITAIN'S MAJOR GREEN GROUPS JOINED BY FISHERMEN IN CALL
FOR ACTION ON INDUSTRIAL FISHING
 </B>
  
<P>MONDAY, JULY 1st 1996 

 

<P>Seven leading environment groups today join forces with
scientists, politicians and fishermen's organisations to
call on Fisheries Minister Tony Baldry MP to "ensure that urgent measures are taken to control industrial fishing"
in ecologically sensitive areas such as the Wee Bankie.
 
<P>The unique alliance uses an advertisement in today's
edition of  "The Independent" to deliver its message.  It is signed by the green groups
Friends of the Earth, Greenpeace, Royal Society for the
Protection of
Birds,  The Marine Conservation Society, The Scottish
Wildlife Trust, The Wildlife Trusts  (Royal Society of
Nature Conservation) and The World Wide Fund for Nature,
together with leading environmentalists David Bellamy and Jonathon Porritt; Alex Falconer MEP; Tony Rice of the
Southampton Oceanography Centre; The Abroath Fishermen's
Association; The Fishermen's Association Ltd; Fishermen's Mutual Association (Pittenweem) ; The Fife Fisherman's
Association and The Salmon and Trout Association.
 
<P>This week the groups are seeking a meeting with Tony
Baldry.
 
<P>The common demand comes as Danish and other fishing boats continue fine-net trawling for sandeels across the Wee
Bankie off Eastern Scotland, a feeding ground to
porpoises, dolphins, whales and tens of thousands of
seabirds, and a fish nursery.
 
<P>The statement highlights the importance of protecting the "feeding, spawning and nursery grounds".  Haddock, once a mainstay of Arbroath fisheries (Arbroath smokies) are now almost absent from the Wee Bankie thanks to overfishing.
 
<P>Greenpeace Campaign Director Chris Rose says "It is
unprecedented that Britain's major environmental
organisations can unite with people in the fishing
industry to oppose industrial sandeel fishing: the
Minister must now wake up to public opinion and put a
stop to this unacceptable hoovering of the seas".
 
<P><B>Statement:</B>
 
<P>(Addressed to Rt Hon Tony Baldry MP, Minister of State,
Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food: `Regarding
industrial fishing for sandeels on the Wee Bankie off the Scottish coast and other areas of the North Sea')
 
<P><B>"Recognizing the importance of protecting the marine
environment and conserving fish feeding, spawning and
nursery grounds, the following organisations and
individuals call on the UK Government to ensure that
urgent measures are taken to control industrial fishing
in sensitive areas."</B>
 

 

 <BR><BR><HR><BR>


<P><B>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:



<P> Greenpeace: 0171 359 4837 (press office);

<P>Alex Smith (owner FV Sincerity, Arbroath) 01241 875880;

<P>The Wildlife Trusts [RSNC]: 01522 544400 (Tim Sands);

<P>WWF: 01483 426444 (Indrani Lutchman);

<P> RSPB: 01767 680551 (Phil Rothwell); 

<P> Scottish Wildlife Trust 0131 312 7765
(Nigel Doar), 

<P>Salmon & Trout Association (Chris Poupard)
0171 929 1389; 

<P>Arbroath Fisherman's Association 01241
73132;  

<P>The Fisherman's Association Ltd 01224 633926
(Roddy McCaul);  

<P>Fisherman's Mutual Association
Pittenweem 01333 311263 (Billy Hughes); 

<P>Alex Falconer MEP 01383 417957.
 </B>

