<HEAD>
<TITLE>FISHERIES PROTECTION REQUESTS GREENPEACE TO CEASE "INTERFERING"   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="nsea.html"><img align=left WIDTH=60 HEIGHT= 80 src="../icons/nsea11.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<P><B>FISHERIES PROTECTION REQUESTS GREENPEACE TO CEASE "INTERFERING"   
WITH INDUSTRIAL FISHERIES OFF THE SCOTTISH COAST 
 </B>
  
<P>TUESDAY, JUNE 25TH 1996 

<P>Greenpeace this morning was continuing its 
campaign to stop industrial   
fishing in sensitive marine areas off the Scottish North Sea Coast 
despite a request from the Fisheries   
Protection Agency to stop interfering with the fishing vessels.   
  

<P>Greenpeace spokesperson aboard the MV Sirius Stefan Flothmann said it 
was ironic that the   
government agency entrusted with protecting the marine environment 
was telling Greenpeace to stop    
campaigning. Industrial fisheries are virtually unregulated and yet 
take nearly 50 per cent of all fish   
landed in the North Sea, he said.   
  

<P>"Greenpeace is protecting the marine environment of the North Sea  
while European governments are   
protecting the financial interests of the industrial fishing fleet," 
said Flothmann. "Greenpeace is   
calling on European governments to stop industrial fishing in 
sensitive marine areas of the North   
Sea."  
  

<P>Greenpeace this morning was again attempting to stop Danish vessels 
from industrial fishing in an   
area known as the Wee Bankie, a feeding ground for birds,  fish, 
dolphins and other marine wildlife    
near Edinburgh off the Scottish North Sea coast.   
  

<P>Greenpeace's third consecutive day of  protest began at 8 am with the 
Greenpeace vessel MV Sirius,   
using four swimmers with buoys and four inflatable boats, attempting 
to stop the Danish vessel   
Thinghold from fishing in the Wee Bankie.  
  

<P>At least two other Danish industrial fishing vessels were in the area 
and also a Fisheries Protection   
boat.   
  

<P>"Greenpeace will  stay on the Wee Bankie and continue to protest 
non-violently against industrial   
fishing in sensitive marine areas until either the industry agrees to 
leave these areas or European   
governments take action to stop this destructive fishing practise in 
the North Sea," said Stefan   
Flothmann.  
  

<P>Yesterday a Danish industrial fishing vessel rammed the MV Sirius 
while others fired flares at   
Greenpeace inflatable boats during a confrontation between Greenpeace 
and 11 industrial fishing   
boats including one Scottish registered vessel. On Sunday the English 
vessel, Omega B, agreed to   
leave the area after Greenpeace stopped it fishing on the Wee Bankie. 
  
  

<P>Industrial fisheries using ultra-fine nets to catch sandeels and 
other small fish near the bottom of the   
marine food web.  These fish are food for "table" fish (cod, haddock 
and  whiting), sea birds, whales   
and dolphins and other marine wildlife.  
  

<P>The exclusion of industrial fisheries from sensitive areas is  one 
part of an emergency recovery plan   
needed for the overfished  North Sea. For industrial fisheries, 
Greenpeace also believes any catch   
limits outside sensitive areas should be set using the precautionary 
approach  and bycatch of other   
species should be cut drastically.  
  
 


<BR><BR><HR><BR>
 

<B>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT

<P> STEFAN FLOTHMANN OR PHIL AIKMAN ON THE 
MV SIRIUS 040 605187 OR SAT PHONE ($US10 PER MINUTE) 00-874 130 
0144. 
<P>OR 
<P>CHRIS ROSE ON 0831-388 503 OR 01273-486 476 
<P>OR 
<P>JON 
WALTER AT GREENPEACE COMMUNICATIONS 0171-833 0600
 </B>

