<HEAD>
<TITLE>BASIS FOR NORWEGIAN WHALING WRONG: IWC SCIENTISTS.</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="whales.html"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=80 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/biowhai.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<BLOCKQUOTE>

<P><B>BASIS FOR NORWEGIAN WHALING WRONG: IWC SCIENTISTS.

<P>International Whaling Commission (IWC) Conference, Aberdeen</B>
  
<P>ABERDEEN, MONDAY, JUNE 24TH, 1996







<P>
 
A new estimate adopted unanimously by IWC scientists demonstrates
that Norway re-opened its whaling industry under false premises,
Greenpeace said from the IWC conference in Aberdeen today.
 

<P>In 1992 Norway announced that it was starting whaling on the
strength of an estimate of 86,732 minke whales, an estimate
prepared by Norwegian scientists. This number, the IWC later
found, had been inflated by a computer error.  The IWC now
estimate that the number should have been 67,500.
 

<P>"That is a drop of almost 20,000" said Greenpeace whale
campaigner, John Frizell, "Norway's decision to start whaling was
based on a mistake".
 
<P>A 1995 Norwegian survey of the same minke population produced an
estimate of 118,000, a substantial increase on 1992. The slow
growth rate of whales means that this difference cannot be due
 
to natural increase. John Frizell, "In the last 15 months Norway
has announced population figures ranging from 69,600 to 112,000.
It is clear that Norway just don't know how many whales there
are".
 
<P>Norway has used this latest estimate to justify its decision to
nearly double its quota from 232 to 425 minke whales in 1996. 
Ironically the market for whale meat in Norway has collapsed and
subsidies are now required to keep the hunt alive. Figures
released last week show that Norway had only sold 59 of the 239
whales it had killed.
 
 

 
 

<B><P>Notes to correspondents:</B>

<P> Both the 1989 survey (which produced the figures used in 1992)
and the 1995 survey were paid for by Norway, used mostly
Norwegian whalers as observers and the data was prepared in
Norway.  The final calculations were done by a Norwegian computer
programme.
 
 

<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:

<P>Mirella Lindenfels ++ 831 594 724


<BR><HR><BR><BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
</body></html>
 
