<HEAD>
<TITLE>FISHING CREWS ATTEMPT TO SLASH INFLATABLE BOATS</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="nsea.html"><img align=left WIDTH=60 HEIGHT= 80 src="../icons/nsea11.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<P><B>FISHING CREWS ATTEMPT TO SLASH INFLATABLE BOATS AS GREENPEACE 
CONFRONTS DANISH INDUSTRIAL FISHING FLEET OFF SCOTTISH COAST 
 </B>
  
<P>SUNDAY, JUNE 23rd 1996 release 3, 6pm


 

<P> Industrial fishing crews used poles with knives to try
and slash 
Greenpeace inflatable boats as the environmental organisation tried  to stop a
group of Danish vessels 
from industrial fishing this afternoon off the Firth of  Forth, on the Scottish
North Sea coast.
 

<P>Four Greenpeace activists from the Greenpeace ship MV Sirius and an oil boom
were placed in front 
of the Danish vessel the "Jannie" in an attempt to stop it fishing for sandeels
on the Wee Bankie, 
which is  a major feeding ground for commercial fish stocks,  dolphins, and
birds..
 
<P>The action began at about  2.10 pm and soon four other Danish industrial
fishing vessels arrived to 
assist the Jannie. During two hours of  manoeuvring the  fishing boats managed
to pull in and slash 
the oil boom and pull up several buoys held by the four Greenpeace activists in
the water. However 
Greenpeace successfully stopped the five vessels from fishing during afternoon. 
 
<P>Earlier today the MV Sirius successfully stopped the English industrial fishing
vessel Omega B from 
fishing on the Wee Bankie and the vessel agreed to leave the area. The MV
Sirius has been patrolling 
ecologically sensitive areas along the Scottish coast since the beginning of
May and prevented major 
industrial fishing activities.   
 
<P>"This is just the first confrontation of a long campaign against overfishing
until the European 
governments get sensible and take action to stop the plundering of the North
Sea," said Greenpeace 
spokesperson Stefan Flothmann.  "Industrial fisheries take about 50 per cent of
all fish landed in the 
North Sea yet are virtually  unregulated."
 
<P>Industrial fishing uses ultra-fine nets to catch sandeels and other small fish
near the bottom 
of the marine food web. These fish are food for "table" fish (such as cod,
haddock and whiting), sea 
birds and other marine wildlife. 
 
<P>The exclusion of industrial fisheries from sensitive areas is one part of an
emergency recovery plan 
needed for the overfished North Sea.  For industrial fisheries, Greenpeace also
believes any catch 
limits outside sensitive areas should be set using the precautionary approach
and bycatch of other 
species should be cut drastically.   

 <BR><BR><HR><BR> 

<P>NB VIDEO FOOTAGE AVAILABLE FROM BBC SCOTLAND IN GLASGOW  041-339 8844
AND PHOTOGRAPHS OF THE ACTION ARE AVAILABLE ON REUTERS, AP AND PA.
 

<B><P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT STEFAN FLOTHMANN OR PHIL AIKMAN 
ON THE MV SIRIUS 0402605187 or  sat phone ($US10 per minute) 00 874 130 0144.   

<P>OR
<P> CHRIS ROSE  0831-388503  or 01273-486 476 
<P> OR
<P> JON WALTER AT GREENPEACE 
COMMUNICATIONS 0171-833 0600</B>


<BR>
