<HEAD>
<TITLE>GREENPEACE STOPS INDUSTRIAL FISHING OFF THE SCOTTISH COAST  </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="nsea.html"><img align=left WIDTH=60 HEIGHT= 80 src="../icons/nsea11.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<P><B>GREENPEACE STOPS INDUSTRIAL FISHING OFF THE SCOTTISH COAST  
 </B>
  
<P>SUNDAY, JUNE 23rd 1996






<P> The Greenpeace vessel MV Sirius used swimming
protesters and an oil 
boom today to stop an industrial fishing boat fishing in a sensitive marine
area off the Firth of Forth, 
on the Scottish North Sea coast.   
 

<P>The  English vessel,  Omega B, was found fishing at 4 am this morning east of
Edinburgh in an area 
known as the Wee Bankie. Greenpeace believes the Wee Bankie is ecologically
sensitive because it is 
a major feeding ground for commercial fish stocks,  dolphins, and birds
including the large 
population  on the Isle of  May.  The MV Sirius has been patrolling such areas
along the Scottish 
coast since the beginning of May and prevented major industrial fishing
activities in these areas.   
 
<P>"Until now the industrial fishing fleet has avoided these sensitive areas but
today the Omega B 
ignored our requests not to fish in this area. Other industrial fishing boats
have also been sighted and   
Greenpeace will be attempting to stop them," said Stefan Flothmann aboard the
MV Sirius. The Danish vessels, the Jannie and the Jette Toft, have been sighted
by the MV Sirius. 
 
<P>Greenpeace called the Omega B at 4.40 am and requested it to stop fishing in
the sensitive area but it 
refused.   Four Greenpeace protesters, wearing survival suits,  were placed in

the water in front of the 
Omega B in an attempt to stop the vessel but it continued. In a  second
successful attempt Greenpeace 
used an oil boom as well as the swimmers to stop the vessel fishing.  The Omega
B hauled in its net 
and told Greenpeace it would stop fishing in the area.     
 
<P> "Greenpeace has stopped the industrial fishing fleet on this occasion but it
is time for North Sea 
governments to take action and finally control the virtually  unregulated
industrial fishing industry
which takes about 50 per cent of all fish landed in the North Sea," Flothmann
said. "Overfishing is 
destroying the North Sea and industrial fishing is a major cause of this
ecological and economic 
crisis."
 
<P>Industrial fishing uses ultra-fine nets to catch sandeels and other small fish
near the bottom 
of the marine food web. These fish are food for "table" fish (such as cod,
haddock and whiting), sea 
birds and other marine wildlife. 
 
<P>The exclusion of industrial fisheries from sensitive areas is one part of an
emergency recovery plan 
needed for the overfished North Sea.  For industrial fisheries, Greenpeace also
believes any catch 
limits outside sensitive areas should be set using the precautionary approach
and bycatch of other 
species should be cut drastically.   
 

 <BR><BR><HR><BR>

<P><B>NB VIDEO FOOTAGE AND PHOTOGRAPHS OF THE ACTION WILL BE AVAILABLE
 
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:
<P> STEFAN FLOTHMANN OR PHIL AIKMAN 
ON THE MV SIRIUS 0402605187or  sat phone ($US10 per minute) 00 874 130 0144.
   <P>
<P>OR CHRIS ROSE  0831-388503  or 01273-486 476 
<P> OR JON WALTER AT GREENPEACE
COMMUNICATIONS 0171-833 0600
</B>

<BR>
