<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press release: 14th June 1996 #2</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="whales.html"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=80 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/biowhai.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<BLOCKQUOTE>

<P><B>
	GREENPEACE BLOCKADE OF NORWEGIAN WHALERS ENDS 
	AS LOCAL THUGS THREATEN VIOLENCE
</B>
  
<P>OSLO, FRIDAY, JUNE 14TH, 1996
                                    


<P>With the arrival of local Norwegian youth apparently called in by whalers to forcefully end Greenpeace's peaceful effort to prevent their leaving port for the whaling grounds today, Greenpeace agreed to end its protest after four hours.


<P>Some 15 local Norwegian youth arrived at the port of Kristiansand in Norway and physically tore down a Greenpeace banner being held by activists near the four whaling vessels they were blockading.  Protesters were physically shoved by the youth and one youth wielded a hook.  


<P>To ensure that their efforts remained non-violent, Greenpeace agreed to end its four-hour protest and leave the site. Inflatable vessels were taken out of the water and whalers disentangled their vessels from the floating blue net protesters used to tie them up.


<P>Three Greenpeace activists were arrested in all, including whale campaigner Urmi Musak of Germany, but all were released shortly after without charge.
 

<P>Earlier today, 40 Greenpeace activists from six nations (Norway, Sweden, Finland, Denmark, UK and Germany,) blockaded four Norwegian whaling vessels (Villduen, Seie, Senet and Seiebuen) to prevent them leaving port.  Activists secured themselves to the railings of one whaling ships and tied floating blue rope through three of the vessels.  Other activists remained in the water with buoys blocking their exit and held up a banner reading "NORWAY STOP WHALING."     


<P>"For four hours Greenpeace prevented Norwegian whaling ships from leaving port," said Greenpeace's Katrin Brubbak of Norway.  "With the International Whaling Commission meeting starting in less than 10 days, we call on those nations attending to force Norway to comply with the international ban on commercial whaling and end this slaughter once and for all."


<P><B>Contact:</B>

<P><B>Greenpeace at the action site:</B> +4790-107-904 and -174-871

<P>J<B>ohn Frizzell, Greenpeace International:</B> +441273-476-839

<P><B>Blair Palese, Greenpeace Communications: </B>+44171-833-0600


<P><B>Photos via AP, footage via Eurovision.</B>


<BR><HR><BR><BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
