<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press release: 13th June 1996 - Canadian Salmon Campaign</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="../fish/index.html#fish"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=80 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/oce01t.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<blockquote>

<P><B>   B.C. PACKERS AWARDED BLUE RIBBON 
                     AS TOP SALMON DESTROYER</B>
  
<P>VANCOUVER, THURSDAY, JUNE 13TH, 1996


<P><B> Greenpeace occupies corporate offices and calls for      
       50 per cent cut in corporate seine fleet</B>
 

<P>Greenpeace activists today
"pointed
the finger" at B.C. Packers, awarding Galen Weston's firm the
blue
ribbon for first place salmon destroyer.
 

<P>Volunteers from the environmental organization scaled the offices
of B.C. Packers in Steveston, to unfurl a blue ribbon banner
reading "#1 salmon destroyer". Greenpeace also held aloft a giant
hand to "point the finger" at the company's over-harvesting of
salmon stocks. Four activists occupied the offices and Greenpeace
demanded that B.C. Packers begin an immediate decommissioning of
50
per cent of their seine fleet. The seiners are the most powerful
boats in the fishing fleet and despite Fisheries Minister
Mifflin's
ineffective efforts to cut the number of vessels, there is still
far too much catching capacity to ensure a future for salmon in
B.C..
 
<P>"Canadians are quite familiar with the failings of our federal
fisheries department," said Catherine Stewart, Greenpeace
fisheries campaigner. "But it's time to name the powerbrokers
behind the fisheries minister's throne--the corporate harvesters
pushing the overfishing agenda."
 
<P>B.C. Packers, a subsidiary of food giant George Weston Ltd.,
owned by entrepreneur Galen Weston, is the marketer of "Clover
Leaf" brand salmon.  The company owns over 90 salmon seiners, the
most "efficient" harvesters in the salmon fishery, with nets
large
enough to encircle a 747 jumbo jet and capable of taking as much
as
20,000 salmon in a single set of the net.  
 
<P>A frightening number of B.C.'s salmon stocks are in a state of
crisis and can no longer withstand the tremendous fishing
pressure
of the corporate seine fleets. As Canada's Ambassador for the
Environment, The Honourable John Fraser said "The capacity of the
seine fleet in Johnstone Strait in 1994 was such that, in a 12-
hour
opening on August 20, an estimated one million Fraser River
sockeye
were caught." The entire Fraser River sockeye run in 1996 is
currently being forecast at 1.3 million.
 
<P>Greenpeace also released a report entitled "Fishy Business",
which
outlines the corporate profile of key industry players driving
the
destruction of fisheries in Canada. On the Pacific coast, B.C.
Packers and the Canadian Fishing Company (CanFisCo) are in first
and second place, respectively.
 
<P>CanFisCo is owned by B.C. entrepreneur Jimmy Pattison and holds
46
seine licenses.  The company fishes, processes and markets salmon
under the Gold Seal Label through Pattison's control of the Save-
On, Overwaitea and Buy-Low chains of supermarkets.
 
<P>"Corporations and businessmen like Galen Weston and Jimmy
Pattison have an ethical obligation to harvest salmon with an eye
to the future of the stocks. The survival of our fish is more
important than shareholder profit," said Stewart.  "It's time to
hold these companies up to public scrutiny.  Weston and Pattison
must be held accountable for their actions - the future of salmon
is not just up to DFO."
 
<P>Greenpeace recently called for a moratorium on almost all salmon
fishing in British Columbia's waters for the 1996 season and is
demanding a fundamental restructuring of the fishing fleet and
fisheries management.


<BR><BR><HR><BR> 
<P>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:


<P><B> Catherine Stewart: </B> 604-253-7701;  604-313-0159 (cell) 
  
<P>     <B> or</B> 


<P><B>Mary MacNutt:</B>  416-597-8408
 
 

<P><B>Copies of the report "Fishy Business" can also be obtained by
contacting the Greenpeace office.</B>
 
 
<BR><BR><HR><BR>
<P>DIRECTIONS TO B.C. PACKERS:


<P>Take the Oak or Knight Street bridge south to Highway 99. Exit
at Steveston Hwy. Go west on Steveston Hwy. to No. 2 Road. Turn
left on No. 2 Rd., then turn right on Moncton Rd. (four way
stop). B.C.
<BR>Packers is located at 4300 Moncton Rd.


<BR><HR><BR><BR>


