<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press release 13th June 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="nsea.html"><img align=left WIDTH=60 HEIGHT= 80 src="../icons/nsea11.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<P><B>GREENPEACE WARDS OFF INDUSTRIAL FISHERS AS ENVIRONMENT MINISTERS
FALTER OVER NORTH SEA FISHERIES CRISIS</B>
  
<P>BERGEN, THURSDAY, JUNE 13th 1996



<P>Greenpeace vessel mv Sirius has
chased two Danish industrial fisheries vessels out of an
ecologically sensitive area near the Scottish coast, acting to
protect the North Sea from overfishing where environment
ministers have failed to act.
 
<P>Today, environment and fisheries officials meet in Bergen,
Norway, to decide on a draft declaration for an "emergency"
meeting on North Sea fish stocks.   However, environment
ministers have so far failed to challenge the fisheries ministers
on reducing fishing catches and protecting the marine
environment.  At last year's 4th International Conference on
Protection of the North Sea, environment ministers vowed to press
fisheries ministers to achieve a 16 point action plan to
safeguard fish stocks and marine life.  They have yet to meet
this commitment.
 
<P>"The environment ministers are failing across the board," said
Greenpeace's Chris Rose from the mv Sirius.  "They are
surrendering the fate of North Sea fisheries and the marine
environment to the nationalistic infighting of the fisheries
ministers, which is a recipe for disaster."
 
<P>Yesterday, the Sirius took the lead when its crew found and
chased away two industrial fishing vessels east of Scotland's
Firth of Forth.  Industrial fishing is virtually unregulated and
accounts for over half the weight of fish landed from the North
Sea.  The vessels found were searching for shoals of sandeels,
which are at the hub of the North Sea foodweb.  Once fished, the
sandeels are ground up into oil and meal for use in margarine and
cakes and animal feed.  Greenpeace has repeatedly asked the 
Danish industrial fishers and their representatives to stay out
of areas likely to be sensitive to industrial fishing. 
 
<P>A ban on industrial fishing in sensitive areas is one of the
first steps of an emergency recovery plan that must be adopted
by environment and fisheries if the North Sea fisheries crisis
is to turned around.
 
<P>"We are defending key wildlife areas from industrial, or
`hoover', fishing -it's time for ministers to act, otherwise the
North Sea Conference will be a waste of time," said MacGarvin. 

<P>At their meeting on Monday, EU fisheries ministers at the EU
Fisheries Council failed to reach agreement to cut herring quotas 
despite scientific advice for a 50% cut in 1996 and 1997.
Fisheries ministers also took no action on industrial fishing. 
 

 <BR><BR><HR><BR>
 

<P><B>For more information contact:</B> 

<P><B> Malcolm MacGarvin</B> in Bergen on
(mobile) ++47 94128531,

<P><B> or</B>

<P><B> Chris Rose</B> (UK) <B>Diederik Samsom</B>
(Holland), <B>Peter Pueschel </B>(Germany)  on MV Sirius   +44 402
605187;  

<P><B>or</B>

<P> <B>Jon Walter,</B> Greenpeace Communications ++44 171 833
0600 


