<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press release 4th June 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="oceans.html"><img align=left WIDTH=50 HEIGHT= 50 src="../icons/bioocea.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<P><B>GREENPEACE DEMANDS THAT FISH INDUSTRY STOPS TRADING NORTH SEA
HERRING AND FARMED SHRIMPS</B>
  
<P>BREMEN, TUESDAY, JUNE 4th 1996



<P>Greenpeace demands that fish traders and
processors take definite steps to stop the exploitation of the
oceans. At a press conference during the Fish Conference of the FAO
in Bremen, Greenpeace demanded that the industry no longer process
North Sea herring and no longer do trade in tropical shrimps from
Asian or South American farms.
 
<P>Herring fishing and shrimp farming are two of the most urgent
examples where the industry must behave responsibly. "Global trade
of fish products is increasing the exploitation of the seas", said
Stefan Flothmann, Greenpeace marine biologist. Greenpeace is calling
for a fisheries reform. In February, the environmental organisation
published the "Greenpeace Principles for Ecologically Responsible
Fisheries" and called for industry and trade to base fish product
buying on ecological criteria. 
 
<P>As far as North Sea herring is concerned, this means that fishing
must stop until stocks have recovered. In the past few weeks,
scientists have observed that herring stocks in the North Sea have
collapsed. Greenpeace is starting an aid fund to support small
coastal fisheries during a ban on herring fishing. 
 
<P>In addition, Greenpeace is calling on shrimp importers to stop
buying from shrimp farms that clearcut mangrove forests on South
American and Asian coasts. "Shrimp farming leads to salination and
contamination of drinking water", said Matthew Gianni, Greenpeace
International fisheries expert. "The local population must often be
relocated."
 
<P>In reaction to the "Greenpeace Principles for Ecologically
Responsible Fisheries", the Unilever food company, together with
WWF, initiated the "Marine Stewardship Council".  This council will
develop ecologically sound buying criteria. Greenpeace welcomes this
step but insists that protective measures begin immediately so that
the fish industry can prove its credibility.
<BR><BR><HR><BR> 
<P><B>For more information, please call</B>

<P>Stefan Flothmann, Greenpeace marine biologist,
<P>Matthew Gianni, Greenpeace International, at mobile phone
0172/3818148
<P><B>or</B> Greenpeace Press Office, Hamburg, ++49-40-30618-340.
<BR>
<BR><HR><BR><BR>
