<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press release 23rd May 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="nsea.html"><img align=left WIDTH=60 HEIGHT= 80 src="../icons/nsea11.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<P><B>FISH OIL AND MEAL ASSOCIATION SET UP FIGHTING FUND TO OPPOSE 
GREENPEACE CAMPAIGN AGAINST INDUSTRIAL FISHING IN THE NORTH SEA </B>
  
<P>LONDON, THURSDAY, MAY 23rd 1996

<P>Stung by the withdrawal from the market
of  major customers such as Unilever,  the international fish oil
and  meal association is attempting to set up a  $US100,000
fighting  fund to combat a Greenpeace campaign to stop the
destructive  practise of industrial or hoover fishing in
sensitive areas of  the North Sea.
 
<P>The International Fishmeal and Oil Manufacturers Association, in 
a circular to members, states that the Greenpeace campaign 
against industrial fishing in sensitive marine areas was of  
"serious concern" and calls for minimum donations of $US2,000 
from each member to establish an "emergency fund starting at 
$US100,000".
 
<P>The circular says the fund would be administered by an 
international committee made up of representatives from Norway, 
Chile, Peru, USA, Iceland, Denmark, United Kingdom, Spain and 
South Africa. 
 
<P>Industrial fishing is virtually unregulated and takes over half 
the weight of all fish landed in the North Sea. Using ultra-fine 
nets industrial fishing fleets take sandeels and other small fish 
near the bottom of the marine food web. These fish are food for 
"table" fish (such as cod, haddock and whiting), sea birds and 
other marine wildlife.
 
<P>The exclusion of industrial fisheries from sensitive areas is one 
part of an emergency recovery plan needed for the overfished 
North Sea.  For industrial fisheries, Greenpeace also believes 
any catch limits outside sensitive areas should be set using the 
precautionary approach and bycatch of other species should be cut 
drastically.  
 
<P>The Greenpeace ship,  Sirius, is currently patrolling  sensitive 
marine areas off the east coast of Scotland near Edinburgh which 
are feeding grounds for birds, seals, dolphins and fish.  
Greenpeace has also written to North Sea fisheries and 
environment ministers asking for an urgent response on what they 
will do to stop industrial fishing in such sensitive areas of the 
North Sea. 

<P>Stefan Flothmann, Greenpeace campaigner on the MV Sirius said: 
"This is a last ditch attempt to defend an ecologically 
destructive industry which should not be allowed to continue to 
operate in  sensitive areas of  the North Sea such as feeding and 
nursery grounds." 
 
<P>It's now clear that  industrial fishers are ignoring the calls 
for them to leave these sensitive areas.  We are now urging 
governments to act quickly to stop this destructive fishing 
practice."
<BR><BR><HR> <BR>
