STRICTLY CONFIDENTIAL - GREENPEACE TO ATTACK FISH MEAL AND OIL 
INDUSTRY 
 
On the 25th April the Governing Body of IFOMA considered the 
unofficial but usually reliable reports from a number of European 
sources that Greenpeace are about to launch an attack on the fish 
meal and oil industry.  This attack has now commenced in the UK 
with peak time TV news coverage on 13th May together with a great 
deal of press publicity.  Greenpeace is targetting the consumers 
of fish oil.
 
These actions are of serious concern to the Governing Body and 
the commercial actions of Unilever in announcing its intention
to  cease purchasing fish oils derived from North Sea fish and
to  review its continued use of other types of fish oil were
noted.  (See Unilever News Release attached) and United Biscuits,
the  largest biscuit manufacturers in Europe, to announce a stop
in  using fish oil (see press statement).
 
Press calls for supermarkets to follow Unilever's lead has 
already resulted in one of the UK's largest supermarkets 
(Sainsbury's) announcing the phasing out of fish oil from all 
their food products (see press statement attached).
 
The Governing Body therefore called upon all fish meal/oil 
producers and the related trade to set up an emergency fund 
starting at US$100,000 to fight against this attack.
 
The fund would be administered by IFOMA but be held in a separate 
bank account and would only be used to fight this campaign.  The 
fund would be used to fight campaigns in any part of the world 
where it was felt to be necessary.

(cont)
 
page 2
 
The fund and campaign would be administered by an international 
committee made up of:
 
