<P><B>NORWAY TO BUILD WHALE MEAT MOUNTAIN </B>
  
<P>MONDAY, MAY 20, 1996

<P>Norway's whalers went to sea today to hunt for 425 minke whales - 
  nearly double last year's catch of 218. 
 
<P>"This is absurd," said Katrin Brubakk, Greenpeace Norway's whale  
campaigner. "What do they intend to do with 425 whales? They  
could not sell all the meat from last year's catch and had to  
freeze 50 tons. Do they plan to build a mountain of whale meat?" 
 
<P>The Norwegian government claims that hunt is small scale  and 
traditional and its purpose is to sustain communities in the  
sparsely populated north of the country. Export of whale meat,  
which would demonstrate the commercial nature of the hunt, is  
forbidden. 
 
<P>"By doubling the quota the government is encouraging whale meat  
smuggling," said Brubakk. "This is a charter for smugglers. 
 
<P>An April 1996 seizure of 6 tons of smuggled Norwegian whale meat  
in Japan led to the uncovering of a conspiracy to smuggle 60 tons  
to Japan, equivalent to 30 whales, almost 15% of the 1995 catch.  
There have been two seizures in the last three years of whale  
meat smuggled from Norway - in both cases the contraband had  
cleared Norwegian customs without difficulty. 
 
<P>"Not only are they catching far more than they can consume, but  
there is no scientific basis for the quota," said Brubakk. "Over  
the last 13 months Norwegian government sources have used six  
different figures for the population and not one of them has been  
agreed by the International Whaling Commission. The IWC has said  
that they have no agreed estimate for this whale population an 
so  there is no basis for calculating any quota. The Norwegian  
government is ignoring the normal rules for international  
cooperation because its own interests are at stake." 
 
<P>Norwegian whalers, who have disproportionate clout in Norwegian  
politics since the thinly populated north of Norway needs fewer  
voters to elect an MP, have been vociferous in demanding increase  
quotas and weakening of IWC regulations. When Norway resumed  
whaling in 1992, the Norwegian press attributed the decision to  
polls showing that the government was losing ground in the north. 
 
 
<P>"The Norwegian government is putting national politics ahead of  
protecting the environment," concluded Brubakk. "Mrs Brundtland  
should be ashamed." 
 
                           <BR><HR><BR>
 
 
For more information call Katrin Brubakk 4794383057 
  <BR><HR>

<P><B>Note to editors: </B>
 
 
 
<P>Whale population figures put forward by Norway  
 
<pre> 
Date                            Number         Source 
 
 
1992 until April 1995           86,700       Govt of Norway 
 
April 6 1995        a bit above 80,000       Nor. scientist (1) 
 
April 6 1995                    91,000       PM Brundtland  (2) 
 
April 28 1995                   69,600       Govt of Norway  (3) 
 
May 8  1995                     75,600       Nor. scientists (4) 
 
May 6 1996                     112,000       Ambassador to US (5) 

</pre>
  
<P>Since the population is depleted (it has not yet recovered from  
intensive commercial whaling by Norway), under the IWC's revised  
management procedure (RMP), which Norway claims to be following,  
quotas would fall to zero at a population figure of about 53,000  
whales. 
 
 
<P>References: 
<UL> 
<LI>1 Fiskerbladet (Fisheries newspaper) Thursday, April 6  1995 
 
<LI>"The latest estimate of minke whales still stands a little bit  
above 80,000 animals." Lars Walloe, chief scientific advisor to  
the Norwegian government on whales.] 
 
<LI>2. Mrs. Brundtland gave the figure of 91,000 at a press briefing  
for Norwegian journalists. 
 
<LI>3. "A new calculation indicates that the figure of 69,600 is a 
more accurate estimate. The adjusted quota is therefore based on 
this figure," Norwegian fisheries department press release, Oslo,  
April 28. 
 
<LI>4. This is the figure given by Norway to the IWC's scientific  
committee in 1995. 
 
<LI>5.  Norway's acting ambassador to the United States, Karsten  
Klepsvik, quoted by Reuters on 6 May 1996.  
  </UL>                            

