<P><B> GREENPEACE FINDS INDUSTRIAL FISHERS OFF SCOTLAND</B>
  
<P>FRIDAY, MAY 17, 1996-

<P>Greenpeace vessel MV Sirius has found
industrial fishing boats off the Scottish North Sea coast.  
 
<P>The eight Danish vessels were found fishing east of Aberdeen
inside an area that Greenpeace believes is ecologically sensitive
to industrial fishing.  In a meeting in Copenhagen last week,
Greenpeace asked representatives of the Danish industrial fishing
industry to voluntarily stay out of these areas ahead of
government regulation.
 
<P>The MV Sirius crew contacted the boats this morning and delivered
a leaflet explaining the Greenpeace demands with a map of these
sensitive areas.
 
<P>Greenpeace also today wrote to North Sea fisheries and
environment ministers asking for an urgent response on what they
will do to stop industrial fishing in those sensitive areas.
 
<P>Industrial fishing is virtually unregulated and takes over half
the weight of all fish landed in the North Sea. Using ultra-fine
nets industrial fishing fleets take sandeels and other small fish
near the bottom of the marine food web. These fish are food for
"table" fish (such as cod, haddock and whiting), sea birds and
other marine wildlife.
 
<P>The exclusion of industrial fisheries from sensitive areas is one
part of an emergency recovery plan needed for the overfished
North Sea.  For industrial fisheries, Greenpeace also believes
any catch limits outside sensitive areas should be set using the
precautionary approach and bycatch of other species should be cut
drastically.  
 
<P>Stefan Flothmann, Greenpeace campaigner on the MV Sirius said:
"It's now clear that these industrial fishers are ignoring the
calls for them to leave these sensitive areas.  We are now urging
governments to act quickly to stop this destructive fishing
practice."
 
 
<P>EDITOR'S NOTES:
