<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press release 13th May 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="nsea.html"><img align=left WIDTH=60 HEIGHT= 80 src="../icons/nsea11.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<P><B> BISCUIT GIANT CRUMBLES BEFORE PUFFIN PROTEST</B>
  
<P>13th May 1996

 
<P>Following a Greenpeace protest today United Biscuit has agreed “to cease the use of fish oil 
from non-sustainable industrial fishing in European waters within one year”. This 
announcement came after 150 Greenpeace activists dressed as puffins, with a 40 foot lorry, 
blocked the entrance of McVitie’s biscuit factory in Harlesden, West London this morning.

<P>The decision was greeted by cheering from the Greenpeace “puffin” protesters, and the 
organisation called on other users of fish oil, including Tescos, Heinz, Co-op, Iceland, Spar 
Asda and Safeway, to follow suit immediately.   The companies have been approached by 
Greenpeace and the Co-op has already agreed to stop using the oil.

<P>McVitie’s currently use around 6,000 tonnes of fish oil in their biscuits each year, some of 
which comes from the North Sea.  

<P>John Sauven of Greenpeace said, “United Biscuit’s swift decision must be congratulated. It’s 
great news. United Biscuit’s, Unilever and Sainsburys now all recognise the folly of using 
unsustainable industrial fish oil.”

<P>Each year,  8 billion sandeels are taken from the North Sea by industrial fishing.  This 
particularly destructive form of fishing threatens the puffins’ food supply. Sandeels are also a 
food source for “table” fish such as cod and haddock whose numbers are already perilously 
low, as well as seals, porpoises and whales.  Using fish oil in products like biscuits could 
threaten the North Sea marine eco-system.

<P>Today’s event marks the start of Greenpeace’s campaign against industrial fishing for sandeels 
in the Wee Bankie (off the East Coast of Scotland) and other sensitive areas in the North Sea. 
The Greenpeace ship MV Sirius is currently in the Firth of Forth, ready to take part in this 
campaign.  



<BR><HR><BR>
FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CALL THE UK PRESS OFFICE:- 0171  359 4837 or 0171 865 8255/6/7 
