<HEAD>
<TITLE>Press release 7th May 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCCCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=1 cellpadding=5 width=100%><tr><td>

<a href="nsea.html"><img align=left WIDTH=60 HEIGHT= 80 src="../icons/nsea11.gif"></a>
<a href="newsindx.html"><img align=right  border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bionews.gif"></a>
</td></tr></table>

<P><B>GREENPEACE DEMANDS GOVERNMENT ACTION ON INDUSTRIAL FISHERIES</B>
  
<P>DUNBAR, Scotland, May 7, 1996 -
<P>Greenpeace today called for an 
end to  industrial "hoover" fishing in ecologically sensitive 
areas as part of an emergency recovery plan for the overfished 
North Sea.
 
<P>In a letter sent to North Sea governments, Greenpeace has called 
for urgent regulation to stop industrial fisheries in sensitive 
areas of the North Sea including fish spawning and nursery 
grounds and important bird feeding grounds. Any catch limits 
outside sensitive areas should be set using the precautionary 
approach and bycatch of other species should be cut drastically. 
 
<P>Greenpeace released a map, showing areas in the North Sea that 
should be immediately closed to all industrial fisheries until 
governments present a more comprehensive assessment of sensitive 
areas. Greenpeace believes that these areas are likely to be 
included as areas identified as senstitive by North Sea 
Governments.
 
<P>The Greenpeace vessel MV Sirius is currently stationed in 
Scotland's Firth of Forth -- a crucial feeding ground for 
seabirds, fish and marine mammals. The Firth of Forth is the 
site of one of the biggest sandeel fisheries, where Danish and 
Scottish industrial fishing boats are due to start fishing for 
sandeels within the next few weeks. 
 
<P>Tomorrow, at a meeting called by the Danish fishmeal industry, 
Greenpeace will ask Danish industrial fishers to voluntarily 
stay out of sensitive areas until governments have implemented 
formal regulations for the fishery that adequately protect the 
North Sea.  
 
<P>Industrial fishing at present is virtually unregulated and takes 
over half the weight of all fish landed in the North Sea. Using 
ultra-fine nets industrial fishing fleets take sandeels and 
other small fish near the bottom of the marine food web. These 
fish are food for "table" fish (such as cod, haddock and 
whiting), sea birds and other marine wildlife.  
Fish oil is used to make food products such as cakes, biscuits 
and margarine.  Fish meal is fed to poultry, pigs and farmed 
fish.
 
<P>Chris Rose of Greenpeace said: "Industrial fishing in areas like 
the Firth of Forth threatens marine wildlife and further 
contributes to the crisis of overfishing in the North Sea.  Time 
and again industrial fishing has led to the collapse of fish 
stocks. We cannot allow this to happen in the North Sea.   
Governments must call an immediate halt to this particularly 
destructive practice in sensitive areas of the North Sea."  

<BR><BR><HR>
FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:
<BR> CHRIS ROSE 00873 1300144 or 0402 605187, 
<BR>STEFAN FLOTHMANN 01368 865 982 
<BR><HR><BR>
<P><B>Letter to government ministers demanding immediate action</B>
 
<P>Dear Minister,
 
<P>We wrote to you recently regarding Greenpeace's extreme concern 
at the state of North Sea fisheries. One of the issues 
identified in that letter was that of industrial
fisheries.
 
<P>While the UK Government brought up this issue at the recent 
Fisheries Council Meeting, little progress was made. This issue 
is extremely urgent, not least because one aspect of industrial 
fisheries that gives us great concern -the targeting
of coastal areas for sandeel - is due to resume in the next few 
weeks.  
<P>We are therefore asking you to take urgent action to protect 
sensitive areas from
industrial fishing.
 
<P>Specifically, we are calling on you to:
 
<P>1) initiate a process for the general regulation of North Sea 
industrial fisheries,
based on the precautionary principle, to be implemented in time 
for the 1997 season.  Greenpeace would expect this to include 
both general regulation and limitation of catches, a reduction 
of by-catch to levels approaching zero and the
establishment of special measures for critical (or sensitive) 
areas.  
<P>We ask that you and your colleagues secure immediate agreement 
in principle to such measures. This will allow significant 
progress to have been made in addressing the practical 
requirements in time for the June 10 EU Fisheries Council,
and the June 13/4 preparatory meeting for the 1997 Inter 
Ministerial (Fisheries) Meeting on the North Sea.
 
<P>2) as an emergency measure, to declare provisional critical 
areas from which unregulated industrial fishing will be excluded 
forthwith.  
In the attached annex we set out what we believe to be relevant 
criteria when establishing critical areas, and a map indicating 
those areas of the North Sea that
we believe would be likely to be defined as critical areas using 
such criteria.  
<P>Governments have the ultimate responsibility to act decisively. 
However it is imperative that action is now taken to protect 
these sites in the short term, and
that all parties do everything in their power to facilitate this 
process.   
<P>In pursuit of protection of marine life in these sensitive 
areas, and the ultimate
well-being of the fishing industry, we are presently stationed 
in the Firth of Forth.
<P>We will be asking industrial fishers to cease operations in such 
areas until governments have established a formal (and 
convincing) regulatory mechanism.  
<P>We ask you to lend the support of your Government to this 
initiative, as part of your response to the wider North Sea 
fisheries issues outlined in our letter of [whenever national 
letter sent].
 
<P>Yours etc.,
<BR>
<BR><HR><BR><BR>
</body></html>
 



 

 





