<HTML>
<TITLE>ACTION</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FC9C9C" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">

<table border=1 width=100% cellpadding=7>
<tr><td>

<a href="geneng.html"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/biogen.gif"></a>

<A HREF="actindx.html"><img valign=bottom align=right 
border=0 width=50 height=50 src="../icons/bioact.gif"></a>


<BR><font size=+1 face="arial">&nbspACTIONS ACROSS EUROPE ON WORLD FOOD DAY</font>

</td></tr>
</table>

<blockquote>

<p><b><font size=+2>Greenpeace calls on Unilever to reject genetic products</b></font><br>
<p><center>
</center>
<p><b>AMSTERDAM, OCTOBER 16TH, 1996</b>

<P>&nbsp<img align=left border=0 width=20 height=20 src="../icons/bioact.gif">
 <br>Today -- World Food Day -- Greenpeace offices in Europe are organizing
protests at Unilever's
     headquarters in the UK and Germany and at their Swedish head
     office. Unilever is a major user of soya which is found in about
     60 per cent of all processed foods, from bread to chocolate. 


<a href="../pics/uksoya1.jpg"><img hspace=15 vspace=10 align=left width=72 height=109 border=0 src="../thumbs/uksoya1.jpg"></a>
<br clear=ALL>    

<a href="../pics/uksoya2.jpg"><img hspace=15 vspace=10 align=right width=109 height=72 border=0 src="../thumbs/uksoya2.jpg"></a>


<p> "What we are seeing is just the beginning of retailers and
     consumers saying no," said Greenpeace campaigner Michelle
     Sheather. "Food processors thought they could slip this in to our
     food without telling us -- but this is a huge experiment with
     food and nature and people don't want it." 
<P>&nbsp<img align=left border=0 width=20 height=20 src="../icons/bioact.gif">
 <br>In addition to health fears, Greenpeace is concerned about the effects
on the environment of the release of
     genetically engineered crops. "This will be the first time
     genetically engineered ingredients have appeared in wide range of
     everyday supermarket products," said Ms Sheather, "and if the
     food multinationals have their way millions of tons of engineered
     crops will be grown in the environment". 
<br clear=all>
<br>
<center>
<table border=0 cellpadding=4>
<tr><td align=middle><a href="../pics/gersoya1.jpg"><img valign=middle align=center width=109 height=72 border=0 src="../thumbs/gersoya1.jpg"></a>
<td align=middle>    <a href="../pics/gersoya2.jpg"><img valign=middle align=center width=109 height=72 border=0 src="../thumbs/gersoya2.jpg"></a>
</tr>
</table>
</center>


 <br>"In order to find lasting solutions to world food problems we
     need to work with sustainable agricultural processes which do not
     pose threats to the environment and human and animal health.
     Genetic engineering, like the so called `green revolution' is
     just another short-term dangerous attempt to provide a quick fix.
     It does not address the real problems of world famine." 

<br><br>
<a href="prgoct16.html"><img valign=middle align=center width=30 height=30 border=0 src="../icons/bionews.gif"> The press release</a>

</blockquote>
<BR>
</body></html>
 


 


