<HEAD>
<TITLE>ACTION</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FC9C9C" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">

<table border=1 width=100% cellpadding=7>
<tr><td>

<a href="geneng.html"><img border=0 align=left WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/biogen.gif"></a>

<A HREF="actindx.html"><img valign=bottom align=right 
border=0 width=50 height=50 src="../icons/bioact.gif"></a>


<BR><font size=+1 face="arial">&nbspGREENPEACE ACTIVISTS 'QUARANTINE' GENETIC SOYBEAN FIELD</font>

</td></tr>
</table>

<blockquote>
<font size=+2>"Strange things are happening to America's crop fields..."</font>
<p><B>10th October 1996</B>

<P>&nbsp<img align=left border=0 width=20 height=20 src="../icons/bioact.gif">
 <br>More than 30 GP activists travelled to the remote area of Atlantic, Iowa,
and successfully "quarantined" a field of Monsanto's
"Roundup Ready Soybeans." Using non-toxic, milk and flour based paint, the
activists worked all night to paint huge slogans on the three acre field to be visable from the air: an enormous, 100-foot high "X" spoofing television's "The X-files" theme, and the
message: "Biohazard! Monsanto." 

<center>
<a href="../pics/ge07.jpg"></B><img width=150 height=95 src="../thumbs/ge07t.jpg" hspace=0 vspace=20></a>
<a href="../pics/ge08.jpg"></B><img width=150 height=95 src="../thumbs/ge08t.jpg" hspace=30 vspace=20></a>
</center>
<br clear=all>A similar message was printed on a banner
that could be viewed from the ground.  In addition, the activists occupied
the farm's harvesting equipment for the duration of the action so the field
could not be harvested. 

<P><img align=left border=0 width=20 height=20 src="../icons/bioact.gif">&nbsp"Strange things are happening to America's crop fields -- they're turning into America's
     X-fields, said Greenpeace Campaigner Beth Fitzgerald from the site of the genetic invasion. 

 <P>Despite protests from European consumer groups, food manufacturers, retailers and even
     farmers themselves, the genetically engineered soya is now being harvested and mixed with
     normal soya ready for export to Europe. Soya is used in about 60 per cent of processed
     foods, from bread and cakes to chocolate and margarine. 

 <P>The "Roundup Ready Soybean" developed by the US firm Monsanto -- also responsible for
     their production of Agent Orange used in Vietnam -- has been genetically engineered to be
     resistant to Monsanto's own "Roundup" herbicide. The soybean contains genes from a virus
     and a bacteria. 

<P><img align=left border=0 width=20 height=20 src="../icons/bioact.gif">&nbsp
     In a separate action, activists from Greenpeace Germany dressed as laboratory rabbits today
     also protested outside the headquarters of the food giant Unilever, calling on them to use their
     consumer power to demand non-genetically engineered soya. 


</blockquote>

<BR><BR><HR><BR>

</blockquote>

<BR><BR>

</body>
