<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Brazil: Rainforest Under Seige</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="CCFECC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">






<table border=2 width=100% cellpadding=5><tr><td>
<a href="forests.html"><img align=right WIDTH=60 HEIGHT= 60 src="../icons/biofor.gif"></a>
<BR><H2>BRAZIL: RAINFOREST UNDER SEIGE</H2>
</td></tr></table>

<table width=100% border=0 cellpadding=7>
<tr><td width= 50% valign=top>
<font size=+2><B>Greenpeace celebrates a victory in its fight to save the Brazilian Rainforests!</B></font>

<p><A HREF="prjul11.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="../icons/bionews.gif" HEIGHT=30 WIDTH=30 ALIGN=LEFT></A><B><A HREF="prfjul26.html">PRESS
RELEASE<BR>
</A></B>


 
<P> <hr>   
<H3>The Amazon Rainforest</H3>

 The  Amazon rainforest extends for 4 million  SqKm,  and 
is  home  to  hundreds  of thousands of  animal  and  plant 
species.  Although it  covers only  3.5% of the overall
Earth's surface  -  it is home to around 50% of the world's
living species (estimates  range from 2 to 30 million
species), many of which are still  unknown  to humans.   It has
been estimated that  a  hectare  of  forests  in Eastern
Amazon can  contain  up  to  120  species  of trees. 

<BR><a href="../pics/for61.gif">
<img vspace=10 hspace=20 align=left lowsrc="../thumbs/for61t.gif" src="../pics/for61s.gif" width=115 height=175 border=0></a>
 
<P>The Amazon is also home to some 250,000 indigenous
peoples in 510 areas, many of them fighting for rights to
land that they and their ancestors have lived on for
centuries.  In the last decade many thousands of indigenous
peoples have been forced off their lands as more and more of
the forest is taken over for cattle ranching, the expansion of
cash crops, mining and logging.  This development that is
destroying the forests and threatening indigenous cultures is
often made possible through government subsidies for
colonization of uninhabited forest land given to big companies
and in some areas to landless workers that were evicted from
other regions of Brazil.   In the last decade as much as 12%
of the original forest cover of the Amazon has been destroyed.

<BR clear=all><BR>
<table border=2 cellpadding=5><tr><td align=center>
<B> An acre of Brazilian rainforest is destroyed every nine
seconds.
<P>
In Brazil there have been 90 distinct indigenous cultures that
have become extinct this century.</B>
</td></tr></table>


<BR>

  <P>   Mahogany  logging  can  be singled out as one  of  the 
main  catalysts  for  deforestation  and  forest  degradation 
in   the  Brazilian Amazon. Most of this logging occurs inside
Indian lands or protected areas,  and  extractive reserve,
with no control  by  the  authorities.   According  to  an 
ITTO/FUNATURA study  published in 1993, the  majority  of the 
mahogany  exploited (from 53 different areas of Indian land)
is illegal.  
  
     Mahogany logging in the Amazon has been so intensive that
now trucks  have to travel hundreds of kilometers to reach 
the  last  mahogany  stands. By bulldozing long roads to log,
access is provided into the   previously inaccessible virgin
forest lands for cattle  ranchers,  speculators  and  landless
farmers, who slash and burn the forest in the  quest for
survival. As many as 3000 kms of roads  have  been  opened in
the State of Para only, in order to  log mahogany.

<BR><a href="../pics/for72.gif">
<img vspace=10 hspace=20 align=left lowsrc="../thumbs/for72t.gif" src="../pics/for72s.gif" width=115 height=175 border=0></a>


 <P>    Companies,  such  as Peracchi,. Maginco, Bannach  have 
been  repeatedly accused  of corruption and misbehavior, and
the first were found guilty of illegally logging in indian
lands  by  a  Federal judge in 1993.  Yet the logging
continues.

<P>Mahogany from the Amazon and seeral other timber species are
exported to furnish  the  sitting  rooms  or  toilets  of 
British,  Spanish or US  families.  Mahogany  export  volumes
in 1971-1990 have been assessed to amount to 1.5  million 
cubic  meters of sawntimber. In order to produce this amount, 
as  many as sawn =  600,000 trees would have to be felled. 

 <P>    According  to  Brazilian press, losses  caused   by 
illegal  logging and illegal  timber  trade in  Brazil  have
been assessed  to be around USD 1.2 billion  a year,  with
losses due to illegal  trade  of  mahogany in Para amounting
to  USD 2 million  a  year.  Most  of  it is due to tax
frauds. In Para only, in four   Fiscal   regions,  the
percentage of tax frauds equaled between 91-99  per  cent in 
1993.  

  <P>   Mahogany  logging is a very destructive practice: 
Brazilian  scientists have assessed that  the predatory
logging of a  single  mahogany tree causes  -  in  average -an
opening in the   canopy  equal to 356m2, that - summed  up  to
the openings for roads  and  others infrastructures - will 
lead to the figure of 1,450 m2  of  forest  per  each tree.
For each mahogany tree felled,  28  other  trees with a dbh 10
cm are damaged and regeneration is scarce.

</td>
<td width=50% align=left valign=top>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B>Rio de Janeiro 26th July 1996</B>
</p>
<br>
<B>The executive director of Greenpeace
Brazil, Roberto Kishinami, sent today a letter to the Brazilian
President, Fernando Henrique Cardoso, saluting his decision of
signing a decree determining a two year moratorium in the Mahogany
(Swietneia macrophyla King.) and Virola (virola surinamensis Warb)
logging in Amazonia. 
These species are the most valuable timbers
exported by Brazil. 
<P>In the same letter, Kishinami observes that now
it is crucial to identify and label the existing stocks already
cut, and to make an inventory of the areas of occurrence of these
timbers, in order to guarantee the success of the presidential act.
"Is very important the involvement of civil society in the
controlling process", said Kishinami.
<P>Greenpeace has been campaigning this issue for the last four years
- using direct actions and political pressure with the help of
other NGOs. <P>The moratorium is the most important victory in GP
Brazil short history.

<P>The only exception in the decree is the timber from plantations -
which doesn't exist, in the case of mahogany. The Ministry of
Environment and Legal Amazonia, and the Brazilian Institute for
Environment and Natural Resources (IBAMA) have 60 days to identify
and cancel all concessions of irregular logging companies. 

<P>This means: 
<BR>1) the Government will not give any new license to
explore Mahogany and Virola in the next two years; and 
<BR>2) the
companies operating now will be submitted to audit - and the one
with irregularities will have their licenses canceled. The official
expectation is that 60% to 70% of the actual licenses will be
canceled.

<P>In another decision (a provisory act, which gets immediately
into force but must be further approved by Brazilian Parliament)
the President legally ban the increase of deforestation in
agricultural areas in the whole "Legal Amazon" - which include
the states of Amazon, Acre, Para, Roraima, Rondonia, Amapa and
Mato Grosso, and the northern regions of Tocantins, Goias and
Maranhao states. The act limit to 20% the area freed for
agriculture in forest regions, against the limit of 50% to date.

According to IBAMA, US$ 6 million will be spent in the controlling
program, using 650 agents, 120 vehicles, 30 boats and 300 flight
hours. 

<P>The presidential decisions were personally communicated to
Greenpeace by the president of IBAMA, Eduardo Martins. Ibama is
the federal agency for the environment. "This is a Greenpeace
victory", said Mr. Martins during his phone call, asking for GP
support to convince the Parliament to approve the provisional
act. 

"We expect an important reaction from logger's lobby, deputies and
senators from Northern States", said Roberto Kishinami. "To face
this upfront and guarantee the approval governmental decisions,
Greenpeace Brazil is organizing a meeting with NGOs to set up a
common strategy." 

<P>"Both decisions - the decree and the provisory act - mean a very
important contribution to our fight to preserve the Amazonian
biodiversity", said Kishinami. "And can contribute to reduce
increasing deforestation in the region, which grew
from 11,130 square kilometers/year (in 1991) up to 14,896 sq
km/year (in 1994). These figures were announced yesterday by INPE
(National Institute of Space Research). The INPE monitors
Amazonian using data from the Landsat satellite. According to the
Government, the area affected by deforestation in the Amazonian
region was 470,000 square kilometers.

<P>"These numbers show that the authorities failed in controlling the
destruction", said Kishinami.
</B>



</td></tr>
<tr><td colspan=2>
<hr>
<B><H2>The Greenpeace Campaign</H2>

   <P>  Greenpeace  Brazil has been working with  local 
communities  and  indigenous peoples to stop the plunder of 
the  Amazon  rainforest,  by targeting the mahogany industry. 

<P>As a result of Greenpeace~s work and the coordinated effort
with other environmental groups, several logging  companies 
have  been forced to  stop their  operations in the Indian
lands of the State of Para. In addition the state  Association
of Timber Exporters was forced to sign an  agreement  not to
log in Indian lands anymore.  But  the fight goes on.


<P>Greenpeace Brazil forests campaign has been pursuing the following
goals:

<UL>
<LI> implement  a moratorium on mahogany logging to  push  for 
the  ecological reform of the broader timber sector;
<LI> reduce the consumption of mahogany in the main consumer
countries  (the  US,  the UK, Spain) as well as in  the 
Brazilian  domestic  market;
<LI>help  to  strengthen  the  institutional  capacity   of  
the  governmental  agencies, such as IBAMA, to  increase 
transparency  and  enforce  legal controls on mahogany
logging,  marketing  and  exports
<LI>include mahogany in Appendix II of CITES at the next
Conference  of the Parties in July 1997; -  assist and support
local communities in the identification  of  environmentally 
and  socially sound alternative  use  of  forest  resources.

</B>






</td></tr></table>

