<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Whales</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="9CFCFC" TEXT="130036" LINK="D51C27" VLINK="970000" ALINK="E200A9">
<table border=0 width=100% cellpadding=6>
<tr><td colspan=2>
<a href="oceans.html"><img align=right border=0 width=60 height=60 src="../icons/bioocea.gif"></a>
<a href="../pics/biowha02.gif"><img border=0 ALIGN=left WIDTH=80 HEIGHT=67 src="../icons/biowhai.gif"></a>
<H2>Whales - the slaughter continues</H2>
</td></tr>

<tr><td  width=50% valign=top>

 
<P><B>The history of commercial whaling is one of ruthless
overexploitation and has lead to the near extinction of several whale
species.</B>

<P>Greenpeace has been influential in creating a whale sanctuary in Antarctica and in achieving a world-wide moratorium on commerical whaling.  But the slaughter continues...
<BR><BR>
<table border=0 width=100% cellpadding=7><tr><td align=center>
<a href="../pics/oce12.gif">
<img  lowsrc="../thumbs/oce12t.gif" src="../pics/oce12s.gif" width=175 height=115 border=0></a><font size=-1><BR>A slaughtered whale<BR> in Antartica</font>
</td></tr></table>

<P>Despite growing opposition to whaling by people around the world and the International Whaling Commission (IWC) moratorium both Norway and Japan are currently hunting whales for commercial
gain.  Norway is openly flouting the moratorium, while Japan 
is hunting whales under a "scientific research" loophole in the IWC convention.

<P><B>Such whaling has been driven by greed with no concern for the protection 
and preservation of whale stocks.</B> The income 
from the international trade in whale meat, whale products and associated 
illegal trade, is the catalyst driving the whaling industry.
 
<P>The whaling industry in both countries currently hunt the minke whale, the
smallest of the great whale species and the only one left in anywhere near its
original numbers.  The minkes, although larger than elephants, were too small
for whalers to bother with until the early 1970s when most of the larger whale
poplulations were decimated by commercial whaling.<BR><BR>

<table border=0 width=100% cellpadding=7><tr><td align=center>
<a href="../pics/biowha01.gif"><img  align=top border=0 width=142 height=216 src="../thumbs/biowha1s.gif"></a>
<P><font size=-1>A Minke Whale is hauled aboard a Japanese factory ship in the Southern Ocean</font> 
</td></tr></table>

<P>  
<B>Whales have inhabited the earth's oceans for millions of years and play a 
vital role in maintianing the balance in ocean ecosystems.  You can help protect the world's remaining whale populations from senseless slaughter.  For more information read on....
</B>  
<!--END OF LEFTHAND CELL-->
</td>

<!--START OF RIGHTHAND CELL-->

<td width=50% valign=top>
<table border=1 width=100% cellpadding=7 ><tr><td align=LEFT>

<br clear=all>
<FONT SIZE=+1>GREENPEACE ACTION:</FONT>
<p><b><a href="actw01.html"><img align=left border=0 width=35 height=35 src="../icons/bioact.gif"> &nbspJune 14th 1996:</a><br>
Greenpeace blockade of Norwegian Whalers ends as local thugs threaten violence</b>
<br clear=all>

<br clear=all><br>
<FONT SIZE=+1>PRESS RELEASES:</FONT>
<p><b><a href="prwjul16.html"><img align=left border=0 width=30 height=30 src="../icons/bionews.gif"> July 16th 1996</a><br>
WHALERS FAILURE TO FILL QUOTAS CASTS DOUBT ON POPULATION ESTIMATES. </B>

<p><b><a href="prwju14b.html"><img align=left border=0 width=30 height=30 src="../icons/bionews.gif">June 14th 1996</a> 
<BR>GREENPEACE BLOCKADE OF NORWEGIAN WHALERS ENDS AS LOCAL THUGS THREATEN VIOLENCE.</B><br>
40 Greenpeace activists from six nations (Norway, Sweden, Finland, Denmark, UK and Germany,) blockaded four Norwegian whaling vessels (Villduen, Seie, Senet and Seiebuen) to prevent them leaving port.  

<br clear=all><br>
<a href="../pics/wha04.jpg"><center><img border=0 width=150 height=97 src="../thumbs/wha04t.jpg"></center></a>
<BR clear=all>
