<html><head>From:   Blair Palese, International Press Officer, from Tokyo
<br>Date:   April 23, 1995  5:45 PM, Japan time
 
                <P><H4>GREENPEACE PREPARES TO PROTEST ARRIVAL OF NUCLEAR WASTE SHIP TO JAPAN</H4>
 
</head><body><P> Yesterday we held a press conference on board the Solo after it
arrived.  It was attended by about 36 press outlets including
most of the major Japanese press and a number of international
press outlets based in Tokyo.
 
<P>The press conference room on board the Solo was standing room
only with TV cameras everywhere.  The 18 member international
crew was a bit overwhelmed by all the people swarming onto the
boat after more than 60 days at sea with no other human contact
but each other.  
 
<P>Afterward, we held a crew update meeting attended by the staff
of Greenpeace Japan, the boat crew and those of us who are here
from Greenpeace international.
 
<P>This morning, a number of Greenpeace staff boarded trains to go
north to Aomori, Japan where the dump ship is to arrive early
Tuesday.
 
<P>Last night, however, those who already there, a campaigner and
a number of local activists from near Sellafield nuclear facility
in Britain and COGEMA in France were told by their hotel, the
only one near the arrival harbour, that they could not stay there
after that night.  When asked why, the owner said it was because
the Japanese plutonium company told them not to allow Greenpeace
or others opposed to their plutonium trade to stay there.  We've
been fighting with them, the government and the company ever
since.   Fortunately, we have been working quite closely with
local Japanese people opposed to their home being used as a
nuclear storage site and they have been quite helpful and
supportive. 
 
<P>There have been a number of local and regional protests around
the arrival of the nuclear waste shipment up in Aomori, Japan and
more are expected.  Today is a national election day and it is
believed that the nuclear waste ship, which could easily have
arrived in port before today, was held offshore to try to protect
elected officials from being unseated by angry local people.
 
<P>The crew of the Solo will finally be able to get off the boat and
spend some shore leave time on land.  They are eager for a change
of scenery after such a long voyage.
 
<P>More later from Japan.  Sayonara.  Blair.
