<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Greenpeace USA Nuclear Reports</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FF FF FF" TEXT="#00 00 80" LINK="#00 80 00" VLINK="#80 00 00" ALINK="#FF FF 00" basefont=3><table width=100% border=0><tr><td colspan=2 align=right valign=top>
<a href="/~usa/index.html"><img src="pix/pub_vid.gif" WIDTH=504 HEIGHT=101 border=0></a>
</td></tr>
<tr><td valign=top><H1>Greenpeace Nuclear Reports</H1>Reports are listed in chronological order according to publication date. Within each year, titles are listed in alphabetical order.<p><b>Also check out our up-to-the-minute <a href="/~usa/campaigns/nuclear/">Nuclear Campaign page</a>.</b></td><td valign=top><IMG VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="pix/publist.gif" WIDTH=154HEIGHT=156 ALT="Photo of 3 Greenpeace Reports"></td></tr></table><hr><ul>
<li><b>"Stop Plutonium"</b> (1996) Campaign Bulletin exposing the dangers of secret, highly radioactive, plutonium waste transports around the world.  &#169; Greenpeace International.<br>
<b>Only available <a href="/~usa/reports/nuclear/stop_plutonium/index.html">on-line</a>.</b></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"Nuclear Flashback"</b> (1996) Report of a Greenpeace scientific expedition to Amchitka Island, Alaska -- 
site of the largest nuclear test in U.S. history.  New evidence uncovered by Greenpeace, detailed in this report,  
suggests that the site is leaking deadly radiation. &#169; Greenpeace Inc. (USA).<br>
<b>Only available <a href="/~usa/reports/nuclear/amchitka/index.html">on-line</a> (slightly abridged from limited-edition print version).</b></li>
<hr align=left>
<li><b>"Germany Plutonium & Proliferation - The Unstated Threat"</b> (1995) This report balances the proliferation debate and confronts it's realities.&#169; Greenpeace International. 13 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Changing Targets: Nuclear Doctrine from the Cold War to the Third World"</b> (1995) This report traces the policy statements and decisions which have transformed U.S. nuclear doctrine to a global perspective.  It also provides details on new U.S. nuclear weapons programs.&#169; Greenpeace International,  95 pages and appendices<br><b>$5.00</b><br><b>Also available <a href="/~usa/reports/nuclear/changing.html">on-line</a> (abridged).</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"The 520 Forgotten Bombs"</b> (1995) This report gives an overview of the hundreds of U.S. and British nuclear bombs deployed in Europe. It discusses implications of the NPT and outlines rationales to these weapons by NATO and the U.S. Greenpeace 21 pages and appendix<br><b>$5.00</b><br><b>Also available <a href="/~usa/reports/nuclear/520.html">on-line</a> (abridged).</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"The Non-Proliferation Teaty: A Critical Assessment"</b> (1995)A review of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty and its failure in stopping the spread of nuclear materials and technologies. &#169; Greenpeace International, 20 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li>  <hr align=left> <li><b>Briefs Submitted at the NPT(Non-Proliferation Treaty) Conference in September 1994:</b> <ol><li> Stopping proliferation at source</li> <li> U.S. nuclear Forces</li> <li> Russia's nuclear forces</li> <li> Britain's nuclear forces</li> 
<li> France's Nuclear Forces</li><li> China's Nuclear Forces</li></ol><b>$5.00</b> <i>each</i></li><hr align=left><li><b>"TNT-5 Radioactive Waste Tanker and Naval Nuclear Waste Crisis in Far East"</b> (1994) This brief report summarizes Greenpeace's findings regarding liquid radioactive waste tankers tied up in the Zvezda shipyard in the closed city of Bolshoi Kamen near Vladivostok, Russia. &#169; Greenpeace International. 2 pages<br> <b>Only available <a href="/~usa/reports/nuclear/tnt5.html">on-line</a>.</b> <hr align=left> <li><b>"The Unlawful Plutonium Alliance: Japan's Supergrade Plutonium and the Role of theUnited States"</b> (1994) This report summarizes Greenpeace's findings regarding the illegal transfer of reprocessing data and technology from U.S. nuclear weapons plants to Japan. The report also discusses the international implications of these transfers for nuclear nonproliferation policy. &#169; Greenpeace International. 100 pages<br><b>$10.00</b></li><hr align=left> <li><b>"The Plutonium Trade: A Troubling New Era of Proliferation"</b> (1993) A review of Plutonium proliferation concerns in Japan and North and South Korea. &#169; Greenpeace International. 64 pages<br><b>$10.00</b></li> <hr align=left> <li><b>"Trip Report: Greenpeace Visit to Moscow and Russian Far East July-November 1992"</b> (Released 1993) This report deals with the safety and construction of Russian navy nuclear submarines, defense  conversion, decommissioning, and nuclear waste disposal problems. &#169; Greenpeace. 90 pages with supporting documents<br><b>$15.00</b></li> <hr align=left><li><b>"Facts and Problems Related to Dumping of Radioactive Waste at Seas Washing the Territory of the Russian Federation"</b> Materials of the Report of the Governmental Commission for Questions related to Dumping of Radioactive Waste at Sea which was created by the Decree of the President of the Russian Federation from October 24, 1992. No. 613-RD.  &#169; Administration of the President of the Russian Federation.<br><b>$15.00</b> <i>Russian language original of the Yablokov Commission's report, 108 pages</i><br> <b>$20.00</b> <i>English translation by Greenpeace Moscow with additional supporting documents, 140 pages</i></li> <hr align=left>   <li><b>"Fiscal Fission: The Economic Failure Of Nuclear Power"</b> (1992) This report writes the bottom line for the massive government, industry, and ratepayer investment in commercial reactors. Produced by Komanoff Energy Associates, Fiscal Fission shows that commercial atomic power has thus far cost $492 billion -- $97 billion in the form of federal subsidies. Investments and subsidies from 1950 to 1990 are delineated, showing the remarkable excess cost of U.S. nuclear power over virtually any alternative. &#169; Greenpeace. 83  pages<br><b>$50.00</b><br><i><b>$20.00</b>  Greenpeace supporters and non-profits</i></li> <hr align=left> <li><b>"The IAEA File"</b> (1992) A briefing document prepared for the general conference of the International Atomic Energy Agency, Vienna, Austria, September 21-25, 1992. Published by Greenpeace International. 16 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li> <hr align=left> <li><b>"Taking Stock: U.S. Nuclear Deployments at the End of the Cold War"</b> (1992) This report ranks 25 states and seven European countries that host U.S. nuclear weapons and explains the largest shift in deployment of U.S. warheads since the 1950s.  Published by Greenpeace and the Natural Resources Defense Council. 33 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li> <hr align=left> <li><b>"U.S. Military Activity in the Arctic in the 1990s: Is It Needed?"</b> (1992) Thisreport is a brief prepared for a panel for <i>"The Changing Role of the United States in the Circumpolar North"</i> Conference at the University of Alaska, in August 1992. &#169; Greenpeace International.<br><b>Only available <a href="/~usa/reports/nuclear/arctconf.html">on-line</a>.</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Preliminary Report: Greenpeace Visit to Vladivostok and Areas Around the Chazma Bay and Bolshoi Kamen Submarine Repair and Refuelling Facilities 9-19 October 1991"</b> (1991)   &#169; Greenpeace. 20 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li> <hr align=left> <li><b>Preliminary Report: Greenpeace Visit to Closed City of Severodvinsk 1-2 October 1991"</b>  (1991) &#169 Greenpeace. 5 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li> <hr align=left> <li><b>"Nuclear Weapons and the Persian Gulf"</b> (1991) &#169; Greenpeace. 29 pages<br> <b>$5.00</b></li>  <hr align=left> <li><b>"On Impact: Modern Warfare and the Environment: A Case Study of the Gulf War"</b>  (1991) The most comprehensive analysis yet of the Gulf War. The report catalogs the damage done to the human, natural, and human-made environment in what the authors call "the most momentous and destructive war in modern history." At a time when the Pentagon refuses "to count bodies" the report also includes a casualty estimate from the war and its aftermath. A new casualty estimate through mid-July 1991 is also included. &#169; Greenpeace. 171 pages<br><b>$15.00</b></li> <hr align=left> <li><b>"Neptune Papers No. 7: Aircraft Carriers, The Limits of Nuclear Power"</b> (1994) This report outlines the history and legacy of the world’s nuclear-powered navies. It compares the performance of nuclear and conventional (oil powered) aircraft carriers in the Vietnam war, Gulfwar, and a variety of Cold War crises. It shows that no meaningful military advantage has ever been attained by aircraft carriers with nuclear power. &#169; Greenpeace. 63 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Neptune Papers No. 6:  U.S. Naval Nuclear Weapons in Sweden"</b> (1990) This report documents that U.S. Navy ships visiting Swedish ports between 1960 and 1989 routinely carried nuclear weapons in violation of Swedish nonnuclear policy. &#169; Greenpeace. 99 pages (out of print -- only photocopied versions are available)<br><b>$10.00</b></li><hr align=left><li><b>"Neptune Papers No. 5: Nuclear Warships and Naval Nuclear Weapons"</b> (1990) A Complete Inventory. Updates Neptune Papers No. 2 and examines the changes in naval nuclear forces in the past two years. &#169; Greenpeace. 108 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li>  <hr align=left> <li><b>"Neptune Papers No. 4: Naval Safety 1989: Year of the Accident"</b> (1990)  Surveys worldwide naval accidents in 1989 and provides data on U.S. naval accident trends in the 1980s.  &#169; Greenpeace. 26 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li>  <hr align=left> <li><b>"Neptune Papers No. 3: Naval Accidents 1945-1988"</b> (1989) Analysis worldwide naval accidents, with particular attention to nuclear-related accidents, from 1945 to 1988. &#169; Greenpeace. 83 pages<br><b>$5.00</b></li><hr align=left> </ul> <p><h2>Greenpeace Public Information <a href="order_form.html">Order Form</a></h2><h3><a href="publist.html">Return</a> to the main Public Information Page</h3><p>If you have questions about these reports or about ordering these publications in quantity,please contact our Public Information office by <a href="mailto:usa.supporter.services@green2.greenpeace.org">e-mail</a>,fax, or phone (Monday through Friday, 9:30am-5:30pm, EST).<P><b>Greenpeace Public Information<BR>1436 U Street NW<BR>Washington DC<BR>20009<BR>phone (202) 319-2444<BR>fax (202) 462-4507</b><P><i>Prices include shipping and handling. Availability of information is subject to change at any time. You will receive your order within two weeks of our receipt of your request (with payment), unless the publication is out of print.<p><b>The lists are updated biannually and were last updated in September 1996.</b></i><pre></pre><CENTER><IMG SRC="pix/rnbwbar.gif"><H2>...Because our kids deserve a future</H2><IMG SRC="pix/rnbwbar.gif"></CENTER><P><H5>photo of Greenpeace reports &#169; Jay Townsend/Greenpeace 1995</H5><pre></pre></BODY></HTML>
